<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Names Dangers To Press  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A rebel leader from Sierra Leone, the supreme
leader of Iran and the president of Yugoslavia head the list of
''10 Enemies of the Press'' from the Committee to Protect
Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Foday Sankoh, the Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Slobodan Milosevic,
and the others on the list ''use methods that range from outright
torture and murder to more subtle techniques aimed at keeping
uncomfortable truths from being told,'' said Ann Cooper, the
committee's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The annual list released Wednesday from the New York-based press
freedom group also includes the leaders of Cuba, China, and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh of Sierra Leone led the list. He is the leader of the
Revolutionary United Front, a rebel movement that the committee
accused of killing at least eight journalists during the country's
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   He was new to the list, as was Khamenei, who was next on the
list.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said Khamenei has created a repressive atmosphere
for reformist newspapers, and that after a speech of his last
month, 16 newspapers were forced to close.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was on the list for the second consecutive year.
According to the committee, authorities in Yugoslavia have
''intensified their crackdown on the independent Serb media with an
almost daily barrage of attacks on press freedoms in the first few
months of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The other names on the list were:
</P>
<P>
   -- Jiang Zemin, president of China, who the committee alleges had
18 Chinese journalists in jail at the beginning of this year. Six
were convicted last year due to their use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   -- Zine al-Abdine Ben Ali, president of Tunisia, who according to
committee has ''brought Tunisia's press to its knees with
newspapers closures, the prosecution of reporters, economic
pressures against publications, and intimidation by security
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Nursultan Nazarbayev, president of Kazakstan. The committee
said Nazarbayev promised freedom of the press when the country
gained independence in 1991, but that the current ''stranglehold''
on information is much like that under Soviet rule.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fidel Castro, president of Cuba, accused of keeping four
independent journalists in jail for crimes such as
''dangerousness,'' for reporting stories critical of the Cuban
system.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jose Eduardo dos Santos, president of Angola, who has
''effectively made public mention'' of the rebel organization,
UNITA, or the ongoing war, a crime.
</P>
<P>
   -- Alberto K. Fujimori, president of Peru, described by the
committee as pooling all his resources to ''trashing'' a ''thriving
and vigorous'' press that existed five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mahathir Mohamad, prime minister of Malaysia. He is accused by
committee of controlling most major media in the country for nearly
20 years. In 1999, he ''tightened the screws on his country's small
opposition press, following an election in which the opposition
made significant gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Zemin, Castro, Ben Ali, Fujimori, and Mohamad have appeared on
the list before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 0002 </TRAILER>
