<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Young Men Stress Family Time  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN FINUCANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Younger men are placing a strong emphasis on
having a job schedule that allows for family time, according to a
survey by the Radcliffe Public Policy Center.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found 82 percent of men ages 21 to 39 ranked having a
family-friendly work schedule as ''very important'' to them as a
component of their job, said study director Leslie Cintron.
</P>
<P>
   The random telephone survey of 1,008 men and women age 21 and up
was conducted Jan. 18 to Feb. 2 nationwide by Harris Interactive.
The margin of error was plus or minus 5 percentage points, with
greater margins for subgroups.
</P>
<P>
   The survey only looked at the attitudes of men and women at one
point in time, but researchers said they believed it had captured a
snapshot of attitudes that are in flux -- a younger generation of
men that is becoming more family-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say that there has been a sea change in attitudes of
young men who report that they want to take a much greater role in
raising their children,'' Cintron said.
</P>
<P>
   Cintron said that focus groups conducted with Harvard students
unearthed similar results.
</P>
<P>
   ''Young men were beginning to tell us a story that differed
remarkably from the one that is expected of men, young men as well
as old men. They were not willing to give up having family time for
a job, for a career.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say I think this is a very significant finding and one
that definitely requires further exploration. It was somewhat
surprising for us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveyed were asked to rate how important seven
characteristics of a job were to them. They could pick more than
one characteristic as ''very important.''
</P>
<P>
   The responses were then broken down by age and sex groups.
</P>
<P>
   For younger men, in the 21-39 group, a family-friendly schedule
was picked most often as ''very important'' -- by 82 percent of the
group.
</P>
<P>
   For men, ages 40-64, a family-friendly schedule was only picked
by about two-thirds as ''very important.''
</P>
<P>
   In the older age groups, doing challenging work and having a
good relationship with co-workers were picked more often as ''very
important'' job characteristics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
