<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of America Head Sounds Warning  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN BACHMAN, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Myriad state laws to ensure privacy in the
financial services industry would lead to ''untenable''
infrastructures for banks and higher costs for consumers, Bank of
America chief Hugh McColl Jr. said Tuesday at a gathering of
business journalists.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans increasingly worry about how much of their personal
information is collected, stored and shared across the Internet,
McColl said legislators' search for security ought to be prudent
and restrained.
</P>
<P>
   ''The temptation to exploit consumers' privacy concerns for
political gain is great,'' said McColl, chairman and chief
executive of the country's biggest bank, which serves more than 30
million households and 2 million businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''But in the end, the public will not be served by rash,
ill-considered action.''
</P>
<P>
   McColl spoke at the 37th annual Society of American Business
Editors and Writers convention.
</P>
<P>
   In a keynote speech later that evening, Time Warner vice
chairman and CNN founder Ted Turner used the meeting as a
soundboard for a rambling diatribe against nuclear weapons, saying
that a nuclear disaster would be ''very bad for business.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who started the Cable News Network 20 years ago next
month, spoke for 20 minutes about the dangers of nuclear weapons,
greenhouse gas emissions, and failure of the world's governments to
clean up nuclear wastes and pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ''How does this affect business editors?'' he summed up. ''Well,
let me tell you, brothers and sisters, if there is a nuclear
accident or war it will be very bad for business.''
</P>
<P>
   McColl, who used his lunch speech on banking technology to
outline his company's concerns about online privacy regulation,
said consumers have somewhat divergent desires from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make a new global community out of the Internet and
World Wide Web, but we worry about who will come to know us in this
new community -- and what they will do with their knowledge,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The industry also worries about states passing individual
privacy laws that differ from federal requirements, McColl said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The administrative structures we would have to erect to serve
customers across the country with different privacy rules in every
state would be untenbable,'' he said. ''And, of course, at the end
of the day, customers would bear the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of customer data has become a hotly debated topic in
Congress and among state legislatures. In January, Chase Manhattan
agreed to stop sharing customer information after consumer
complaints prompted New York officials to file a lawsuit over the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Congress approved legislation allowing banks,
insurance companies and brokerages to get involved in each other's
business.
</P>
<P>
   The law also gave consumers the right to block financial
companies from providing their personal data to outside firms, such
as telemarketers. But companies can share customers' data with
affiliated financial companies under the same corporate roof.
</P>
<P>
   That ability is critical to the industry's success, he said,
advocating an ''opt-out'' system in which consumers must declare
they don't want their data shared among a company's affiliates over
an ''opt-in'' system where people consent to such sharing.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, 99.8 percent of Bank of America's
customers have decided to allow free access to their information
across the company, he said.
</P>
<P>
   McColl, 64, sidestepped a question about when he plans to retire
and declined to express his preference between Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and Vice President Al Gore about which ought to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's one piece of privacy we got left, isn't it?'' McColl
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: SABEW, http://www.sabew.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
