<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Father of Microcredit' Worried  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN ALT POWELL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For nearly a quarter of a century, Muhammad
Yunus of Bangladesh has been the champion of ''microcredit,'' tiny
loans that have helped thousands of impoverished families start
small businesses and improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he's increasingly worried that the world's poor -- some
1.5 billion people who live on less than a dollar a day -- could be
set back even further if they are left out of the computer
revolution that is changing how the world works.
</P>
<P>
   ''Computers and the Internet are creating the New Economy,'' he
said in an interview Tuesday during a pause in a U.S. speaking
tour. ''This same information technology can bring unprecedented
opportunities to the poorest person in the world. E-education.
E-commerce. E-health care. E-jobs. Or it can leave that person
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   To try to make sure that the poor are included, Yunus is urging
governments, academics and aid groups to unite to create an
international center that would try to figure out how to get
computers -- and the resources they can carry -- to the developing
countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Yunus sees it as an uphill battle, but he is not one to shrink
from challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Yunus, who earned a Ph.D. in economists from Vanderbilt
University in Nashville, Tenn., first got into the business of
fighting poverty during a 1974 famine in his homeland Bangladesh,
one of the poorest countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''There I was, teaching elegant theories of economics at the
university, and I'd come out of the classroom and see people dying
of hunger,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly discovered that just a tiny loan could make a huge
difference in a poor person's ability to survive. His first loan,
he recalled, was $27 from his own pocket to a woman who made bamboo
furniture, which she sold to support herself and her family.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 he founded the Grameen Bank to make loans to poor
Bangladeshis that mainstream institutions considered too risky for
credit. Since then the Grameen has loaned more than $3 billion to
some 2.4 million borrowers, with most loans averaging between $75
and $200. And there are almost no defaults on the repayments.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five percent of his ''customers'' are women, and they
typically start with a loan of just $75. If they prove they can
handle credit by paying the money back on time, they can borrow
more.
</P>
<P>
   He says that a third of Grameen borrowers ''have passed over the
poverty line'' in Bangladesh, where per capita income among the
nation's 130 million people is just $300 a year. They've used the
funds not only to create cottage industries and expand their
farming output but also to repair their houses and send their
children to universities.
</P>
<P>
   Yunus, known to many as ''the father of microcredit,'' has
worked hard to spread the idea. There are now microcredit banks in
at least 40 developing countries, from the Philippines to Vietnam,
Uganda, China and Mexico. There are even Grameen-style lending
programs in New York City and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Yunus, who is 59, has been using his bank's
credit to underwrite the introduction of modern technology to
Bangladesh's rural villages.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks fondly of his ''telephone ladies,'' the 1,400 village
women who have borrowed about $500 each from the bank to lease
Grameen-provided mobile phones. Other villagers then pay the
telephone ladies to make calls.
</P>
<P>
   Yunus said that some of his telephone ladies earn as much in a
month as the average Bangladeshi does in a year.
</P>
<P>
   He's also setting up cyber kiosks -- ''the Bangladesh equivalent
of the cyber cafe'' -- where villagers can, for a small fee, log on
and surf the Internet or send e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But Yunus believes that more has to be done to bring the
Internet and its services to the poor of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be especially helpful,'' he said, ''if there was a
computer-like device available for a really low price, like $20 or
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he's working with the Hewlett-Packard Co. to develop
an electronic health care system; he's working with the Nippon
Electric Co. to create and online educational system that would
provide ''knowledge on demand'' for whole families; he's working
with media experts at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology to
seek voice-operated systems that would be accessible to the world's
illiterate people.
</P>
<P>
   He's excited about the possibilities: ''Think of a poor village
woman. She's down, she's depressed. But maybe she can talk to the
computer and it will talk back. It will be a friend, a philosopher,
a business consultant.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Yunus believes that information technology will
help create a level playing field so the poor can join in the
fruits of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology is an empowering thing,'' he said. ''It's now
coming to businesses. Next, we hope, it will come to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Grameen Bank: www.grameen.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
