<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bestfoods Nixes Unilever Bid  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A U.S. buying spree by international consumer
products conglomerate Unilever has hit a snag, with Bestfoods'
rejection of an $18.4 billion takeover offer.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods, the maker of such household food products as Skippy
peanut butter and Hellmann's mayonnaise, said Tuesday its board had
unanimously rejected the $66 a share bid.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, whose brands include Lipton teas, Vaseline and
Pepsodent toothpaste, agreed last month to purchase Vermont gourmet
ice cream company Ben &AMP; Jerry's for around $326 million and diet
foods company Slim Fast Foods for $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It's offer for Bestfoods represented a 31 percent premium over
the Englewood Cliffs, N.J.-based company's closing price of $50.56\
in trading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bestfoods said its board had determined the offer
was ''financially inadequate and not in the best interests'' of the
company and its shareholders ''given Bestfoods' successful business
strategies and growth prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement late Tuesday, Unilever said it ''is
disappointed with Bestfoods' response and their unwillingness to
discuss with Unilever any aspect of its proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Unilever believes that Bestfoods should reconsider its
proposal and remains available for constructive dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Unilever officials did not immediately return messages left at
their London headquarters Tuesday. The company also has
headquarters in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods initially learned of Unilever's interest in acquiring
the company April 20, according to the Bestfoods' statement. At the
time, Unilever offered between $61 and $64 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods' officials agreed to study the proposal and said its
board would vote at a special meeting Tuesday. Unilever increased
the offer at the last minute but was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter from Bestfoods' chairman and chief executive C.R.
Shoemate to Unilever's chairmen Niall FitzGerald and Antony
Burgmans, Shoemate stated; ''We view your interest in acquiring
Bestfoods as validation of Bestfoods' global strategy in the
consumer food industry.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Shoemate wrote that Bestfoods would no longer consider
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever had 1999 sales of $43.7 billion. Under a reorganization
plan announced in February, Unilever said it plans to slash 25,000
jobs over five years as it tries to reverse a slump in profits and
its share price.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods reported 1999 sales of $8.6 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 0022 </TRAILER>
