<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Binghamton University expels one, suspends one in attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- One student was expelled and another was
suspended from Binghamton University following an assault that
later ignited protests of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas W. Richetti, 19, of Waverly was expelled and Chad
Scott, 18, of Walton suspended for two years. Scott will not be
eligible for reinstatement until fall 2002.
</P>
<P>
   A third student, Christopher M. Taylor, 20, of Seaford was
cleared. All three were members of the BU wrestling team.
</P>
<P>
   Richetti and Scott also were ordered to pay for medical claims
not covered by victim John E. Lee's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   School officials also have called for a separate investigation
into the university's wrestling program and the FBI has begun its
own investigation into whether the fight may have violated federal
civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 27 assault outside a dorm left Lee with a fractured
skull and roused ethnic tensions on campus. The three suspects, all
of whom are white, were arrested March 3 and ordered off the campus
March 6 pending the administrative review.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-American students said the attack was racially motivated
and called for apologies from school officials and more recognition
on campus. As many as 200 students from as far away as Washington,
D.C., protested on campus last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Ronnie Han, a Korean-American from Queens who has
followed the case closely, said Monday night he accepted the
university's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's maybe not quick, but at least they came up with
something. I understand that they cannot move too quickly,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The university's three-member disciplinary board of school
administrators ruled Richetti violated the university's rules of
student conduct, specifically two counts each of causing injury to
another person; striking, shoving, or kicking another person; and
harassing conduct that limits or denies equal treatment of another
person ''because of race, color, sex, sexual orientation, religion,
age, disability, veteran status, marital status, national origin or
ancestry.''
</P>
<P>
   The board found Scott guilty of one count each of the same
offenses. The two can appeal to a university hearing officer.
</P>
<P>
   They still face a separate criminal prosecution by the Broome
County District Attorney's Office, which has charged them with
second-degree gang assault, a felony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 0024 </TRAILER>
