<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genesee Brewing Buyout Collapses  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- The owner of Genesee Brewing Co., which
has made beer in Rochester since 1878, has canceled an agreement to
sell the nation's fifth-largest brewery to a New York investment
company.
</P>
<P>
   Genesee Corp. had struck a deal in December with Platinum
Holdings, owner of City Brewing Co. in La Crosse, Wis. But ''we
believe that the interests of our shareholders will be better
served by terminating the agreement,'' chief executive Tom Hubbard
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Genesee, which also operates food processing, real estate and
equipment leasing businesses, said it ended the purchase deal
because unspecified terms weren't met. It is exploring alternatives
for its brewery subsidiary, including a management-led buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Genesee produces 1.6 million barrels of beer and ale a year and
had revenues of $103.3 million in the 1998-99 fiscal year. Its
brands include a line of regional beers -- Genesee Beer, Genny Light
and Genny Cream Ale -- as well as high-end specialty beers such as
J.W. Dundee Honey Brown Lager and Michael Shea's Irish Amber.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-sized breweries have been battling for survival in a
cutthroat market dominated by Anheuser-Busch Cos., Miller Brewing
Co. and Adolph Coors Co., which account for more than 80 percent of
domestic beer sales. In recent years, small craft and specialty
brewers, plus imported brands from Canada, also have plundered
Genesee's sales.
</P>
<P>
   Platinum Holdings bought the former G. Heileman Brewing Co. in
La Crosse, Wis., from Stroh Brewery Co. for $10.5 million last
summer, then started City Brewing Co., a privately owned company
whose brands include La Crosse Lager and City Lager.
</P>
<P>
   The Genesee buyout was to have been completed by mid-March.
Under the deal, Genesee Brewing would continue operating here under
a new name, possibly City Brewing-Genesee, and with most of its 470
workers retaining their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Genesee said it has saved about $8 million after a turnaround
program it started last summer. In December, it reintroduced its 12
Horse Ale brand and is aiming to reinvigorate its Genesee line with
promotional campaigns during the peak summer seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Wehle family owned a controlling interest in the voting
stock of Genesee Corp., a publicly traded company, for nearly 70
years. John Wehle Jr., who had succeeded his father and grandfather
as chief executive, died of lung cancer March 10 at age 53. He was
replaced by Hubbard, who had been appointed the company's president
last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 0028 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to complete state swing  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT EDWARD, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton was kicking off
a two-day foray across northern New York today that at its end will
mean she has visited all 62 of New York's counties in her 10 months
on the Senate campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party Chairwoman Judith Hope noted Tuesday that
was not accomplished by Democratic Sen. Charles Schumer until late
last year, a full year after he defeated Republican incumbent
Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton is in the process of redefining New York state
politics, throwing traditional formulas out the window with her
relentless attention to counties that heretofore have been
ignored,'' Hope said. ''Clearly, upstate New York will be
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hope said the first lady's visit to all 62 counties was
not aimed at helping her overcome charges that she is a
carpetbagger, aides to Senate rival Mayor Rudolph Giuliani pressed
that point.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton can travel to as many counties, as many times as
she wants,'' Giuliani campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum said
Tuesday. ''It will not change the fact that she's never lived in
New York, never worked in New York and she has absolutely no
connection to New York. There's only one real New Yorker in this
race, Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton moved to the suburbs north of New York City in January.
She planned stops today in Washington, Hamilton and Franklin
counties.
</P>
<P>
   While the first lady was preparing Tuesday for her trip,
Teitelbaum tapped a veteran Republican operative to bolster the
mayor's upstate campaign effort.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City mayor, who learned last week that he has
prostate cancer, has been criticized by some fellow Republicans for
not spending enough time in traditionally more conservative upstate
New York while the first lady has been crisscrossing what is
expected to be a major electoral battleground this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''He knows this state like the back of his hand,'' Teitelbaum
said as he announced that state GOP executive director Brendan
Quinn will become director of statewide field operations for the
Giuliani campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gov. George Pataki continued to brush off questions
about whether he would take up the GOP Senate banner if the mayor
drops out of the race. ''I believe he will continue to run,''
Pataki said. Beyond that, the governor said, ''I'm not going to
speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have shown Pataki is the top choice among
Republican voters to take on Clinton if Giuliani drops out of the
race. The mayor said he will make his decision before the end of
May.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the campaign trail, aides to Giuliani were working
on setting up a meeting for later this week between the mayor and
state Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long. The two have been
at odds over the mayor's refusal to come out for a ban on what
critics call ''late-term abortion'' and his strong ties to the
Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, with Long's encouragement, former U.S. Rep. Joseph
DioGuardi announced he would seek the nominations of the
Conservative, Right to Life and Independence parties. A DioGuardi
candidacy could drain conservative votes away from the mayor, a
liability in a close race. Polls show the race is close.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Long said that ''at this stage of the game'' he did
not see Giuliani being the Conservative Party's candidate and
believed the nomination would go to DioGuardi. But Long cautioned
that could change before the party's June 3 state convention.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani said he would court the Conservative Party,
Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said the first lady would
ask the Liberal Party for its support although party boss Raymond
Harding is one of Giuliani's top political advisers. Both Giuliani
and Clinton are scheduled to meet with the Liberal Party's policy
committee Saturday in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
count the votes they receive on third-party ballot lines, a factor
in close races. In New York, no Republican has won statewide office
since 1974 without the Conservative Party line. Conversely, no
Democrat has been elected U.S. senator or governor without the
Liberal Party line since the party's founding in 1944.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 0029 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki, legislative leaders make deal on debt reform  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki and state legislative
leaders say their agreement on New York's borrowing practices means
the Legislature can adopt a $77.5 billion state budget that has
been delayed for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal reached by Pataki, Senate Majority Leader Joseph
Bruno and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, $3 billion would be set
aside in ''rainy day'' reserves, including tripling the debt
reserve fund from $250 million to $750 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers would also pass a bill limiting how much debt the
state can take on. The borrowing cap of new debt would be set at 4
percent of the state's personal income. A cap on how much the state
could pay for debt service would be established at 5 percent of all
funds.
</P>
<P>
   New York, which currently does not have such caps, now borrows
at 6 percent of its personal income and pays 5 percent of all funds
for debt service. The 4 percent cap would be phased in over the
next 10 years, Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would be retroactive to April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an excellent budget,'' said Pataki, who had been
pushing for debt reform programs.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators also agreed on a $3.8 billion transportation bond
act, which Pataki said would be subject to the new borrowing
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bruno and Silver, the starting date for the state's
prescription drug program for senior citizens, would be pushed back
to Jan. 1, 2001. Legislators had initially settled on an Oct. 1
starting date for the Elderly Pharmaceutical Insurance Coverage
(EPIC) program.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki had originally called for adoption of a state
constitutional amendment that would limit how much the state could
borrow. Silver and Bruno said they agreed to that two weeks ago,
but thanks to what Bruno called an honest misunderstanding, Pataki
said he also thought the legislative leaders pledged at the same
time to pass a law establishing the same caps while a
constitutional amendment was moving toward passage.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest a constitutional amendment could be in place would
be November 2001 while Pataki argued that the state should improve
its borrowing practices sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said Tuesday that in the two weeks since -- which included
a vacation by lawmakers for the Passover-Easter holiday --
legislative staffers and those for Pataki's Budget Division
approached Wall Street bond rating agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''They indicated something that was more immediate would be more
significant to raising the rating of bonds in New York state,''
Silver said. ''After that information was made available to the
leaders by the staff, we said, 'Let's do something that's more
immediate.'''
</P>
<P>
   Silver said he hopes the borrowing changes will ''warrant a
significant upgrade in the bond rating of New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has about $37 billion in accumulated debt and its bond
rating is the lowest in the country or near to it. A bond upgrade
would save the state millions of dollars in lower interest costs
when it borrows money.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and Bruno said a constitutional amendment instituting the
debt reform steps is still possible. Silver sounded less hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and legislative leaders said they hoped final
budget adoption could come late this week. This is the 16th
straight year the budget will be adopted after the April 1 start to
the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Silver said it has not been a bad budget-adoption
process. Last year's budget wasn't put into place until Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did it,'' Silver said. ''We did it quicker than we usually
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although bills are still being printed and there is still room
open for discussion, Bruno said this budget agreement won't fall
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have now a clear understanding as to what we've agreed on
and I don't believe there is any question,'' he said. ''There isn't
any issue, really, that's a deal breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's proposal for homeowners to receive their tax rebate
checks directly from the state instead of having reductions
credited to their school taxes by districts under the ''STAR''
property was defeated in the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 0029 </TRAILER>
