<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYSEG files complaint over wholesale market  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUILDERLAND, N.Y. (AP) -- A power utility has asked federal
regulators to help stabilize prices on New York's new wholesale
electricity market.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Electric &AMP; Gas Corp. has filed a federal petition
critical of the New York Independent System Operator, which was
launched in November to monitor the state's electricity system. The
utility claims software and design problems have led to dramatic
price fluctuations on wholesale electricity sold through the ISO.
</P>
<P>
   Those higher wholesale costs cannot be passed along to consumers
buying power through regulated utilities.
</P>
<P>
   NYSEG president and chief operating officer Michael German said
the ISO's problems ''could strangle the nascent competitive retail
electricity market in New York state.'' The utility recently asked
the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission to correct these
''start-up'' problems before electricity demand peaks this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO last year replaced the utility-operated New York Power
Pool in watching over the state's power grid. The ISO took on the
power pool's role, along with additional duties of administering
the wholesale market adopted as part of electricity deregulation in
New York state
</P>
<P>
   The ISO is run from the pool's old headquarters in the Albany
suburb of Guilderland.
</P>
<P>
   The utility hopes the FERC can put a temporary cap on wholesale
prices. German said the utility is seeking the same sort of action
from the FERC that the agency has taken to protect evolving
competitive power markets in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ISO spokesman Ken Clapp said he could not address the Binghamton
utility's complaint while a response for federal regulators is
being drafted. Clapp said there were some ''growing pains'' at the
ISO as the complicated venture started out. But he said the ISO was
well prepared for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   NYSEG is not the only utility with concerns about ISO pricing.
Niagara Mohawk spokesman Gerald Rockower said some ISO charges seem
to be out of sync with the market. He said Niagara Mohawk could
possibly seek refunds if the ISO does not address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are right now looking at this as a start-up problem that
will be overcome,'' Rockower said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
