<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted cop-killer freed five months ago on parole is arrested  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- After serving 25 years in prison, a
convicted cop-killer who was freed in December, has been taken into
custody for violating parole.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Victory, 59, who was convicted in 1970 along with another
man of murdering New York City Police Officer John Varecha, was
apprehended April 7 in a Syracuse establishment where alcohol is
served and sent to the Onondaga County Justice Center, Division of
Parole spokesman Thomas Grant said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Victory had a preliminary hearing April 26 at the jail, and
probable cause was found, Grant said. A final hearing was being
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Police Commissioner Howard Safir, who called
Victory's release a ''disgrace'' when it was announced, was not
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ''Albert Victory is an individual who should never have been
paroled,'' Safir, who wants New York to abolish parole, said. ''The
fact that he's violated his parole underscores that he should never
have been let back out on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory, who had been serving a sentence of 25 years to life,
left Attica state prison in Wyoming County a free man in December
and went to live in Utica. Conditions of his release were strict.
He could not consume alcohol, could not travel outside Otsego and
Oneida counties, had to follow a 9 p.m.-7 a.m. curfew, and had to
be under electronic monitoring by parole officers.
</P>
<P>
   A tangled web of bureaucratic and legal rulings had preceded
Victory's release.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1999, a state Parole Board said Victory had earned
it. But two months later the board reversed itself and rescinded
his parole, saying that ''new information'' had come to light in
the case. The board said it had been unaware when granting him
freedom that Victory had escaped in 1978 and spent three years on
the lam before being caught.
</P>
<P>
   Victory's lawyers countered that the board was well aware of
Victory's escape and that it rescinded his parole on flimsy grounds
after Gov. George Pataki's office complained.
</P>
<P>
   Victory and another prisoner bribed guards to let him meet his
girlfriend in a hotel room while the guards drank in the hotel bar,
and when the guards returned to take him back into custody, Victory
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Acting state Supreme Court Justice Mark Dadd ruled Dec. 15 that
the board had erred by taking back its decision to free Victory,
and he ordered Victory's release.
</P>
<P>
   Dadd found that the parole files in Victory's case included
''many references'' to the 1978 escape and ruled parole officials
could not reopen the matter based on ''new information.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's appeal of Dadd's ruling is still before the
Appellate Division of state Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 0031 </TRAILER>
