<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syracuse students will track bombing trial for victims' families  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Syracuse University is forever linked to
the Pan Am Flight 103 bombing. Now, the university is providing a
link for the victims' families so they can follow the murder trial
of the accused bombers on a special web site.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Syracuse University law students will provide daily
summaries and explanations to the victims' families and relatives
as part of a project funded by the U.S. Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea was the families needed better access to the
information that was going to be coming out at the trial than they
would get just through the general media,'' Andrew Greenberg, the
project's associate director, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, most of them are not going to be there. There was
no other resource for the families to get the detailed information
they want,'' said Greenberg, adding that project is unprecedented
but could open the way for future coverage of transnational trials.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Wednesday, Libyan nationals Abdel Basset Ali
al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah go on trial in a Scottish court
holding session in The Hague. The two are accused of murder,
conspiracy to commit murder and violations of international safety
laws in the Dec. 21, 1988 bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The 270 people killed in the bombing represented 21 nations.
Among the dead were 35 students studying overseas under a Syracuse
University program.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Syracuse has maintained a close association with
the victims' families. The university started a scholarship program
in honor of the Lockerbie victims and built a memorial wall on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   It was the close relationship with the families that prompted
the U.S. Justice Department to ask Syracuse to set up the web site,
said Donna Arzt, director of the university's Center for Global Law
and Practice and the project director. The justice department
provided a $100,000 grant to help create the site, called the
Lockerbie Trial Families Project.
</P>
<P>
   Though a university-created web site with information on the air
tragedy is available to the public, the comprehensive trial
coverage will be exclusively for the families, who were issued
special passwords by the justice department to gain access to the
site.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an intranet site rather than an Internet site,'' said
Arzt, who is attending the first two weeks of the trial. A total of
about 700 victims' relatives worldwide will have access to the
family site, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The justice department arranged with the Scottish court for
daily transcripts, which will be unofficial and uncorrected. A
dozen law school students, with the assistance of a handful of
professors, will process the transcripts and post them on the web
site, Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse will receive the transcripts around 11 a.m. every day,
when the court is ending at 5 p.m. in the Netherlands. Greenberg
said the goal is to get a summary written and posted within 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Syracuse group also will provide explanations of legal
procedures and legal language.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need to be able to understand why certain information is
coming out, and why it's coming out in certain forms, and why
certain information is not coming forth,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   An interactive component will allow families to ask questions,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The public site has been up since November and usage has been
growing steadily. In March, there were 10,000 hits by 445
individuals, Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Families of U.S. victims also can view the trial on closed
circuit television at four special sites around the country. The
video will be shown on a tape-delay basis.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the net:
http://www.law.syr.edu/academics/centers/glap/+lockerbie+.shtml
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 0031 </TRAILER>
