<DOCNO> APW20000503.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commission: Hungary trips did not violate ethics laws  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The funding of Gov. George Pataki's trips to
Hungary in 1995 and 1996 did not violate state ethics laws.
</P>
<P>
   But the trips have prompted a change in how the state Ethics
Commission will regard such corporate-sponsored forays in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The state Ethics Commission said Tuesday that funding for the
trip by such corporate entities as Philip Morris, Pfizer and
PepsiCo raises ''ethical concerns'' for the group that paid for
Pataki's trip. Those companies either do business with the state or
are regulated by New York.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said it will alter the way it regards the
propriety of future trips by statewide elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission also said it found no wrongdoing by Pataki or
those close to him in arranging and executing the two trips to the
governor's ancestral homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we have said all along, what we did was right and proper,''
Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said Tuesday. ''The commission has
now clarified that.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said Pataki's office sought and received clearance for
both trips with the Ethics Commission and otherwise ''played by the
rules.'' Those guidelines were established when travel costs for a
trip to Japan in 1991 by former Gov. Mario Cuomo were paid for by
the Japanese Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
   In Pataki's case, the travel costs and other expenses were paid
by the Hungarian American Chamber of Commerce (HACC).
</P>
<P>
   According to the commission's determination, close Pataki
adviser Charles Gargano approached the HACC asking whether it
wanted to sponsor Pataki's trip in 1995. In 1996, Pataki himself
asked the group whether it wanted to sponsor a return trip of the
governor to participate in ceremonies marking the 40th anniversary
of the 1956 Hungarian uprising against the Soviet Union, according
to the Ethics Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Following both requests, the HACC solicited contributions from
corporations to pay for the trips. In 1995, sponsors included
Philip Morris ($10,000), ATT Hungary ($10,000), Pfizer ($5,000) and
PepsiCo ($5,000). The next year, Philip Morris contributed $20,000,
Bristol-Myers Squibb $10,000 and price Waterhouse $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ethics Commission executive director Donald Berens Jr. noted
that the commission approved the trips after determining that the
Hungarian American Chamber of Commerce did not have official
business before Pataki or his administration. But Berens said the
commission should have requested the list of companies who were
solicited by the chamber of commerce to underwrite the trip to
determine if they were ''disqualified'' by their business before
the state.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Berens said the commission will demand to know
whether the group organizing trips will be soliciting money from
others and for the names of contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The ''ethical concerns'' raised by the Pataki trips was in the
Hungarian American Chamber of Commerce's solicitation of companies
to help pay for them, Berens said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A corporation may respond to the solicitation in the hope of
currying favor with the state and thereby advancing its own private
interests,'' Berens said. ''Whatever the corporation's motives, its
sponsorship of a trip in such circumstances may create an
appearance of impropriety and adversely affect public confidence in
the integrity of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Berens said there is no evidence that the companies paying for
the Hungary trips got special access to Pataki or that the governor
or his inner circle knew the Hungarian American Chamber of Commerce
was soliciting money from corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's determination came in response to a challenge
to the funding of the Hungary trips by the New York Public Interest
Research Group, Common Cause New York and the League of Women
Voters.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Horner of the New York Public Interest Research Group said
that accepting corporate money via the Hungarian American Chamber
of Commerce showed how ''ethically tone deaf'' the administration
was in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not like the Ford Foundation called up the administration
and said, 'We're holding this conference in Budapest. Please
come,''' Horner said. 'This is something the administration thought
up and it solicited the Hungarian-American Foundation to pay for
part of the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Horner said the investigation also shows how ''weak and
ineffective'' the state's ethics laws are and he renewed his
group's call for a complete ban on gifts to legislators and
government officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 0032 </TRAILER>
