<HEADLINE> Padres 8, Marlins 3  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Damian Jackson had a two-run homer among his
three hits, scored three runs and made an acrobatic play at
shortstop as the San Diego Padres beat the Florida Marlins 8-3 on
Tuesday night to stop a four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Clement allowed three runs and five hits in eight innings
to win his eighth straight decision since last Sept. 5. It figured
that the Padres would support Clement (4-0). They've scored 52 runs
in winning all six of his starts. He struck out seven and walked
three.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Padres found out that starting pitcher
Woody Williams has an aneurysm near his right armpit and that
doctors have recommended surgery. The Padres say it's similar to
when New York Yankees pitcher David Cone had an aneurysm in his
right shoulder in 1996 and missed four months.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Nevin homered for the first time in 50 at-bats and Al
Martin also connected.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson hit a two-run homer to left off Vladimir Nunez with two
outs in the fourth, his third of the year. Jackson also doubled and
singled, falling a triple short of hitting for the cycle, which no
Padres player has ever done.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who beat out Chris Gomez to win the starting shortstop
job in spring training, made a spectacular play in the second
inning. He went to his left to field Alex Gonzalez's grounder,
leaped, spun around and threw him out at first to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin hit a two-run homer to highlight the third-run third, his
seventh. He hadn't homered since April 16 against Houston. Ryan
Klesko had an RBI double and Bret Boone an RBI single in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Martin homered with two out in the sixth, his fifth.
</P>
<P>
   All three of Florida's runs came on homers. Mark Kotsay homered
to center on Clement's first pitch of the game, his second leadoff
homer of the year and his fourth overall.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Nunez, who came in with a 10.07 ERA, hit bitter than he
pitched, connecting for a two-run homer in the fifth, the first in
his big league career. Paul Bako was aboard on a one-out walk.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez (0-3) allowed eight runs and 10 hits in six innings,
struck out six and walked one.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Williams' aneurysm was discovered a day after he pitched 8
1-3 innings in a 5-2 loss to Florida. ... Klesko tied his
career-high with his sixth stolen base in the first inning. ... San
Diego's Eric Owens singled in the third to extend his hitting
streak to 11. He had a 13-game hitting streak earlier in the year.
If CF Ruben Rivera is activated on Friday as expected, Owens will
move to RF to take the spot of Tony Gwynn, who's on the DL with a
sore left knee. Owens has started 22 straight games in center.
</P>
</TEXT>
