<HEADLINE> Storms Rip Texas for Second Night  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas (AP) -- Tornadoes touched down in south
Texas on Tuesday, ripping the roof off at least one house and
overturning about 25 mobile homes on South Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   No major injuries were reported, Cameron County Fire Marshal
Desi Najera said, but power was out to about 5,000 residents.
Fearing the mix of fallen power lines and wet roads, officials
closed state Highway 100.
</P>
<P>
   The roof was ripped off a home east of Rio Hondo around 8 p.m.
An hour later, witnesses said a tornado touched down on Padre
Island and parts of Laguna Madre.
</P>
<P>
   While the tornadoes touched down, the winds weren't anything
like the tornado that struck Fort Worth, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''These aren't the kind of tornadoes you get up in Tornado
Alley,'' said Ken Newman, senior forecaster for the Brownsville
office of the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, repair crews worked into the night to restore power
to homes affected by heavy rain and wind that pounded the Houston
area early Tuesday and shut down at least one area school.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, about 238,000 homes were without power. That
number had been reduced to 28,000 by late Tuesday, Houston Lighting
and Power spokeswoman Leticia Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are shooting for getting everyone back up tonight,'' Lowe
said. ''It could be late, but that's our goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
