<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Divided Over Missile Plan  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Pressure from the United States to support its
proposed missile defense plan has Canadian officials arguing over
whether to go along for the sake of North American unity or resist
to protect Canada's role as a champion of non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have visited Canada and held special briefings
with journalists to make sure their message gets across: Opposing
the National Missile Defense program could leave Canada vulnerable
to a rogue missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Adm. Herbert Browne, deputy commander of the U.S. Space
Command, said Tuesday in Alabama that if Canada refuses to
participate, the United States might be forced to let an incoming
missile hit Ottawa rather than compromise the security of U.S.
targets.
</P>
<P>
   It was the strongest indication so far of how Canada could
jeopardize its traditional joint defense arrangement with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians, however, are divided about whether the country should
join the U.S. system.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy says the plan could
spark a new arms race, either by provoking Russia to drop
non-proliferation agreements or inspiring smaller states to try
harder to develop nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''The law of physics is that every action has a reaction,'' he
told a parliament committee recently. ''And if you put a unilateral
system in place, I can assure you, other countries will not simply
stand still and say 'That's it.' They will undertake alternate and
optional actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Judson Corey, a spokesman for Veterans Against Nuclear Arms,
also said that joining the system would undermine Canada's history
of promoting non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would lose our credibility among other nations as a
negotiator for disarmament and for liberation from the nuclear
threat,'' Corey said.
</P>
<P>
   Art Hangar, the opposition defense spokesman in Parliament,
urged the government to sign on to the plan to preserve traditional
U.S.-Canada defense ties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our membership in this alliance will be severely compromised
if we don't support the U.S. national missile defense system,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Defense Minister Art Eggleton said the plan should be
studied and debated.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is simply a matter of prudence that our joint institution
is capable of responding to new security challenges,'' he said last
month. While stopping short of a direct endorsement, he made it
clear that the U.S. view mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Americans believe there is a threat there,'' he said. ''We
certainly need to look at that.''
</P>
<P>
   More telling was the position offered earlier this year by
Daniel Bon, acting assistant deputy minister for policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Canada has not been opposed in principle to a national missile
defense system,'' he said, ''provided it was deployed in a
cooperative international political environment, complementary to
arms-control and non-proliferation regimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureaucratic language touched on a key issue -- Canada's role
in setting up and implementing the $20 billion plan intended to
defend all 50 U.S. states against attack from a small number of
intercontinental ballistic missiles. Missile interceptors would be
based in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   If Canada backs the plan, it would be run by the North American
Aerospace Defense Command, the joint U.S.-Canadian operation in
Cheyenne Mountain, Colo., where the two countries have defended
North American airspace for five decades, Browne said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a Canadian role, the system would be commanded
by the U.S. Space Command, he said. That means deployment decisions
would be based solely on U.S. concerns, rather than joint
consideration for Canada, Browne warned.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to decide by fall whether to
proceed with the system, which could begin operating as soon as
2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 0129 </TRAILER>
