<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gene May Affect Response to Chemo  </HEADLINE>
By JACQUI PODZIUS COOK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A genetic mutation that makes women more likely
to develop ovarian cancer may also make the body more responsive to
chemotherapy, according to a study in today's Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that women who carry the gene mutation live
about two years longer after receiving chemotherapy in the advanced
stages of the disease than women who do not have the flaw.
</P>
<P>
   The study analyzed tissue samples from 189 Jewish patients
treated during a 12-year period at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center in New York. All of the women had ovarian cancer in it most
advanced stages.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers focused on Jewish women because they more often
carry the defective BRCA1 and BRCA2 genes, which are linked to
higher rates of ovarian and breast cancer. About 10 percent of all
ovarian cancer cases are hereditary.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 189 studied, 88 had the inherited BRCA mutations and 101
did not.
</P>
<P>
   The median time from the first chemotherapy treatment until
death for the hereditary cancer group was about five years,
compared with about three years for women without the mutated gene.
</P>
<P>
   The median time for recurrence of the disease -- the time between
the start of the first round of chemotherapy and beginning of the
second -- was 14 months for the hereditary group and seven months
for the other group.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers took into account such variables as the patients'
age and lifestyle, and still found a connection between the mutated
genes and longer survival, said Jeff Boyd, director of
Sloan-Kettering's Gynecology and Breast Research Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ''The survival is significantly longer,'' he said. ''If you
control for everything else, then BRCA status alone predicts better
survival.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason may be that the gene defect that makes women more
susceptible to ovarian cancer also weakens cells so much that they
are more receptive to chemotherapy, Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the findings could put researchers on the path to
understanding the type of cell damage caused by the BRCA mutation
and possibly replicating it in cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly there's something very different about these tumors,''
he said. ''They are clearly responding more favorably to the same
types of treatment, and the women are surviving longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lynn Hartman, a Mayo Clinic oncologist who was not involved
in the study, said it is difficult to draw conclusions about
chemotherapy sensitivity from findings based on the three specific
mutations found in Jewish women.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we can extrapolate from findings in that group
for all BRCA cancer,'' she said. ''There are hundreds of different
mutations. We don't know that they all behave the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Journal of the American Medical Association:
http://jama.ama-assn.org
</P>
<P>
   Society of Gynecologic Oncologists: http://www.sgo.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
