<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Struggles With Competing Forces  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott had just
wrapped up a difficult session with Janet Reno and knew that many
of his colleagues were steaming about the attorney general's
decision to order a military-style seizure of young Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   So three days after the April 22 raid, Lott rushed to announce
that the Senate Judiciary Committee would hold hearings on the
incident -- and hinted that the panel's chairman, Sen. Orrin Hatch,
might want to consider calling the 6-year-old refugee's Cuban
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Lott called him ''an interesting witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing -- originally set to begin today -- has since been
postponed, with Hatch, R-Utah, blaming the Justice Department for
dragging its feet on a request for documents.
</P>
<P>
   It was an announcement that has come to haunt Lott -- the latest
in a series of difficulties he's encountered and another example of
how difficult it is to lead the Senate during an election year.
</P>
<P>
   ''An enormous wave of emotion swept over conservatives. This
evoked for them everything bad about Bill Clinton and Janet Reno,''
said Norman Ornstein, an analyst with the American Enterprise
Institute. ''Lott not only felt that, but saw it from his base --
and immediately reacted.''
</P>
<P>
   The job of majority leader is always difficult, but it may be
especially so for Lott ''because we have rampant individualism
dominating the Senate now,'' Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also tentatively agreed recently to leave on the back
burner a bill to boost U.S. military ties with Taiwan, according to
some Senate Republicans close to the legislation, to keep it from
getting tangled with legislation to give China permanent trade
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He omitted the Taiwan bill from a list of measures he hoped to
see passed this year.
</P>
<P>
   But that upset some Senate conservatives, including Foreign
Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who wants the
Taiwan bill to come up as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Lott was quick to spread the word that he hadn't really decided
one way or the other on timing for the Taiwan measure.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, a proposed compromise Lott helped broker to
increase trade benefits for Africa and Central America appeared to
be falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've done about all I'm going to do on this issue, let me just
put it real blunt, point blank. You know, there are other people
that need to quit being obstinate and bring this to a conclusion,''
he groused on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Elian Gonzalez hearings, Lott on Tuesday sought to
clarify his position.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was never intended to be a long, drawn out, protracted
hearing,'' Lott said. ''It was always thought to be something that
could be handled in a day or two at the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown that most Americans supported the predawn raid
on the Miami home of Elian's great-uncle and the return of the boy
to his father -- and don't want to see congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans in both the House and the Senate don't want to
be drawn into what they see as a political minefield
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., a Foreign Relations subcommittee
chairman, has been among the most outspoken Republicans in urging
the Senate not to hold the hearings -- saying Congress should leave
the matter alone.
</P>
<P>
   But some others want to press ahead full speed.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch is suggesting the Justice Department's refusal to provide
his committee with documents is why hearings have been postponed.
But Democrats see that as a cover.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are very few people in this city who believe
that their postponing of the hearing has anything to do with
documents arriving on the Hill,'' said White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The panel still hopes to hold a limited hearing into the raid,
Hatch indicated Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has always been challenged in attempting to run the Senate
while keeping his credentials intact with the chamber's more
conservative members. He also knows that others have designs on his
job if he should stumble -- including Majority Whip Don Nickles,
R-Okla., and Rules Committee Chairman Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The usual snail's pace of Senate proceedings and the pressure of
election-year politics has made it increasingly difficult for Lott
to move legislation, even bills that he deems as essential.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said on Tuesday that he's still ''very enthused'' about
holding hearings into the Elian Gonzalez matter. ''But you know,
there are other people, including the Judiciary Committee, that has
to make the final call on that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Tom Raum covers national and international
affairs for The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
