<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recovery Continues After Tornadoes  </HEADLINE>
By RENEE RUBLE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- One year ago, Sara Ruiz was huddling with
her two grandchildren under a mattress when the sky attacked,
peeling away the roof, sucking up the walls and chewing it all to
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz said she plans to look into the sky today and thank God for
what remains.
</P>
<P>
   ''My tragedy has been made into a miracle,'' said Ruiz, who is
returning to a new home near Tuttle that was paid for by donations
and built by volunteers after the tornado of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Across the state, Oklahomans are celebrating their survival and
remembering the victims of May, 3, 1999, when a tornado up to a
mile wide went on a 60-mile destruction path, leaving 44 people
dead, almost 800 injured and more than 8,000 homes damaged or
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The F5 twister, the strongest on the Fujita Tornado Scale, tore
through a quarter of the state, starting near Chickasha. It cut
through rural Bridge Creek, hit Moore, crossed southwestern
Oklahoma City and roared into the suburbs of Midwest City and Del
City.
</P>
<P>
   It was the costliest tornado in U.S. history, causing about a
billion dollars in damage. Mail boxes still stand in front of
vacant lots and scrunched cars sit in driveways.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the anniversary is a time to celebrate a community that
rebuilt together, said Kay Norman, principal of the elementary
school in Bridge Creek, where 12 people died.
</P>
<P>
   The school, one of the only things in town that withstood the
318 mph winds, planned a carnival today with games and inflatable
jumping toys -- and counselors, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have fun,'' Norman said. ''We don't want to
forget what happened, but we do want to recognize the community
spirit around here. We're building. We're back. We're stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mental recovery has just begun for many, said Gwen
Allen, director of Project Heartland, a mental health program
created after the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's after the rebuilding and getting back into a new home
that people may realize the impact of the tornado,'' Allen said.
The agency has provided services to 82,740 people in 19 Oklahoma
counties.
</P>
<P>
   While the removal of debris is officially done and 75 percent of
rebuilding finished, the human scars linger.
</P>
<P>
   Memorials and moments of silence were planned in Bridge Creek
and at Rose State College, while the congregation of Beth Haven
Independent Baptist Church in Moore planned to meet in the parking
lot to worship. A new, almost-finished sanctuary stands near the
old church the tornado destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really haven't lost anything when you look at it, the Lord
has returned it all,'' Pastor Ivan Casteel said Monday. ''We're
still moving strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennie Rogers is one example.
</P>
<P>
   Toppled trees, plywood, tin, shingles and other rubbish blown
from more than 20 miles away has kept a small group of men cleaning
his yard near Perry busy.
</P>
<P>
   But the most challenging part has been living in a mobile home
until his homestead is rebuilt. Rogers boasted of recently cooking
enough chicken, potatoes and pecan pie to feed the 25 worker who
helped one day.
</P>
<P>
   ''You just do what you have to do,'' he said. ''God is still
smiling down on us and that's about all you can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Project Heartland: http://www.odmhsas.org
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Department of Civil Emergency Management:
http://www.onenet.net/(tilde)odcem
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 0150 </TRAILER>
