<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philippine Military Disputes Report
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- Rebels said two foreign hostages died during a
pre-dawn clash Wednesday between military troops and Muslim guerrillas holding
21 people on Jolo island in the southern Philippines. But military officials
expressed skepticism about the claim, saying they had no knowledge of any
fatalities among the hostages captured last week from a Malaysian resort. Nur
Misuari, the government's hostage negotiator, later said he had conflicting
reports about whether the two hostages were dead or only injured.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Puerto Ricans Wait To Be Expelled
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Puerto Rican protesters waited for U.S. federal
authorities to expel them from the U.S. Navy's prized training ground -- even as
several U.S. lawmakers and a religious leader promised to come show their
support. Some 50 protesters on several campsites in the bomb-littered range and
dozens more in front of its main gate say authorities will have to arrest them
to clear the range, which has been idle since stray bombs killed a civilian
guard in April 1999. A few have threatened to scatter into the bomb-strewn bush,
endangering themselves and any pursuers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
ABC Back on Time Warner for Now
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The chairman of the Federal Communications Commission
scolded Time Warner and the Walt Disney Co. for taking ABC off the air for 3.5
million customers, saying viewers shouldn't be held hostage to their dispute.
''This should never happen again,'' William Kennard said Tuesday, shortly after
ABC's signal was restored following a 27-hour blackout. Kennard's warning came
after the corporate warriors put off, but didn't settle, their quarrel over what
Disney would be paid to provide its cable channels to Time Warner customers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N. Carolina Gubernatorial Race Set
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Democratic state Attorney General Mike Easley and
former Charlotte Mayor Richard Vinroot, a Republican, won their party
nominations for governor Tuesday in a race to succeed popular Gov. Jim Hunt.
Thirteen candidates in all jumped into the race when Hunt, a Democrat who served
four terms over the past 25 years, was barred by law from seeking another term.
In Indiana, conservative Rep. David McIntosh won the GOP nomination to challenge
first-term Democratic Gov. Frank O'Bannon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arkansas Woman Executed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VARNER, Ark. (AP) -- A former nurse who asked for the death penalty for
drugging and suffocating her two children was executed by injection Tuesday in
Arkansas' first execution of a woman in more than 150 years. Christina Marie
Riggs, 28, was the fifth woman executed in the United States since the Supreme
Court lifted a ban on capital punishment in 1976. She had maintained throughout
that she wanted to die and her last words reflected her grief. ''There is no way
no words can express how sorry I am for taking the lives of my babies,'' she
said. ''Now I can be with my babies, as I always intended.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nuclear Pledge Called Inadequate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A coalition of countries said Tuesday that a new
pledge by the key five nuclear powers to work to eliminate their nuclear
arsenals falls short of demands that they actually get rid of them. ''We stress
that the total elimination of nuclear weapons is an obligation and a priority
and not an ultimate goal,'' said a statement by Mexico, Ireland, South Africa,
Egypt, Sweden, New Zealand and Brazil. The statement was a response to a joint
position paper issued Monday in which the United States, Russia, China, France
and Britain pledged their ''unequivocal commitment to the ultimate goals of
complete elimination of nuclear disarmament.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Down 172; Dow Ends Down 80
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell broadly Tuesday after AT&AMP;T delivered a cautious
profit outlook and investors took profits from a three-day rally in technology
shares. Worries about rising interest rates hung over the market, keeping volume
low and buyers scarce. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 80.66 to close at
10,731.12. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,696-1,293. The Nasdaq
composite index fell 172.63 to 3,785.45, its first decline in four sessions. In
Japan, financial markets were closed on Wednesday for Constitution Day, a
national holiday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suns Eliminate Spurs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Jason Kidd came back, Tim Duncan didn't and the Phoenix Suns
knocked the defending NBA champion San Antonio Spurs out of the NBA playoffs.
Penny Hardaway and Rodney Rogers, winner of the NBA's Sixth Man Award, scored 23
points apiece as the Suns won the best-of-five series 3-1 with an 89-78 victory
Tuesday night. Rogers, who also had 10 rebounds, scored eight points and
Hardaway seven in the fourth quarter as Phoenix fought off one last San Antonio
challenge to advance past the first round for the first time in five years. The
Suns play the winner of the Los Angeles Lakers-Sacramento series in the Western
Conference semifinals.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
