<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Carolina Gubernatorial Race Set  </HEADLINE>
By DENNIS PATTERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Democratic state Attorney General Mike
Easley and former Charlotte Mayor Richard Vinroot, a Republican,
won their party nominations Tuesday in a race to succeed popular
Gov. Jim Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen candidates in all jumped into the race when Hunt, a
Democrat who served four terms over the past 25 years, was barred
by law from seeking another term.
</P>
<P>
   With 85 percent of precincts reporting, Vinroot had 126,963
votes, or 47 percent, to defeat state Rep. Leo Daughtry, who had
96,967 votes, or 36 percent. Former state Rep. Chuck Neely had
42,840 votes, or 16 percent. Easley drew 268,632 votes, or 59
percent, to defeat Lt. Gov. Dennis Wicker, who had 161,822 votes,
or 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a runoff, the winning candidate in each party had to
get more than 40 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana, conservative Rep. David McIntosh won the GOP
nomination to challenge first-term Democratic Gov. Frank O'Bannon.
With 80 percent of precincts reporting, he had 234,455 votes, or 72
percent of the vote. He defeated John Price, a lawyer who toured
the state in a red school bus, and drew 92,493 votes, or 28
percent. O'Bannon had no opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional races in both states drew heavy competition.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout, however, appeared light with the Republican and
Democratic nominees for president all but final. George W. Bush and
Al Gore already have won the necessary number of delegates, and
they won more Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana, Gore drew 75 percent of the Democratic vote, while
former rival Bill Bradley won 22 percent. Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr.
had 3 percent. Bush drew 81 percent and former rival John McCain
drew 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, Bush drew 78 percent, while former rivals
McCain drew 11 percent and Alan Keyes drew 8 percent. Gore had 70
percent, while Bradley drew 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, D.C., Gore drew 96 percent of the Democratic
vote. Bush had 75 percent, and McCain had 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, North Carolina's governor from 1975 to 1983 and re-elected
to two more terms starting in 1993, is one of the state's
best-known politicians, with approval ratings exceeding 70 percent.
He did not endorse any of the 13 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Wicker and Easley argued over how best to
strengthen education programs with money from a not-yet-approved
state lottery. Easley, a 50-year-old former state prosecutor, ran
unsuccessfully for Senate in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Vinroot, who ran unsuccessfully for the GOP nomination for
governor in 1996, and Daughtry criticized each other's conservative
record on spending and abortion, while debating whether to use
attack ads.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there were seven Democrats, four Republicans and two
Libertarians running.
</P>
<P>
   A recount appeared likely in the North Carolina district of
Democrat Rep. Mel Watt. With 99 percent of precincts reporting
early Wednesday, Republican history teacher Chad Mitchell led a
tight race with 4,711 votes, or 41 percent, against gourmet coffee
shop owner John Cosgrove's 4,614 votes, or 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The lines of Watt's district, which runs from Charlotte to
Greensboro, are being challenged in federal court by critics who
allege it was drawn with an unconstitutional emphasis on race. In
1992, Watt became one of the state's first two black congressional
representatives in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Also in North Carolina, both parties fielded woman candidates
for the lieutenant governor's race for the first time -- state Sen.
Beverly Perdue for the Democrats, and state Sen. Betsy Cochrane for
the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana, former radio talk show host Mike Pence defeated a
crowded field to win the GOP nomination for the seat for McIntosh's
east-central district. Attorney Robert Rock won the Democratic
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Indiana, faced no primary opposition. In
the fall, he will go up against Democratic attorney David Johnson,
an adviser to O'Bannon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 0203 </TRAILER>
