<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group names Sankoh, Khamenei, Milosevic as press enemies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A rebel leader from Sierra Leone, the supreme
leader of Iran and the president of Yugoslavia head the list of
''10 Enemies of the Press,'' which was scheduled for release today
by the Committee to Protect Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Foday Sankoh, the Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Slobodan Milosevic and
the others on the list ''use methods that range from outright
torture and murder to more subtle techniques aimed at keeping
uncomfortable truths from being told,'' said Ann Cooper, the
committee's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The annual list from the New York-based press freedom group also
includes the leaders of Cuba, China and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, of Sierra Leone, led the list. He is the leader of the
Revolutionary United Front, a rebel movement that CPJ accused of
killing at least eight journalists during the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   He is new to the list, as is Khamenei, of Iran, who came in
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The CPJ said that Khamenei has created a repressive atmosphere
for reformist newspapers and that 16 newspapers were forced to
close after a speech he made last month.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, of Yugoslavia, was cited on the list for the second
consecutive year. According to the CPJ, authorities in Yugoslavia
have ''intensified their crackdown on the independent Serb media
with an almost daily barrage of attacks on press freedoms in the
first few months of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In Yugoslavia and Iran, threats are so severe that independent
media are in grave danger of becoming extinct in the near future,''
said Cooper, the CPJ official. ''Elsewhere, in China and Cuba,
opposition voices have used new technology to circumvent
restrictions, prompting new reprisals from leaders determined to
control information.''
</P>
<P>
   The others on the list are:
</P>
<P>
   --Jiang Zemin, president of China, who CPJ alleges had 18 Chinese
journalists in jail at the beginning of this year and uses secret
police to monitor the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   --Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, president of Tunisia, who has
''brought Tunisia's press to its knees with newspaper closures, the
prosecution of reporters, economic pressures against publications
and intimidation by security forces,'' CPJ said.
</P>
<P>
   --Nursultan Nazarbayev, president of Kazakstan, who promised
freedom of the press when the country gained independence in 1991
but has a Soviet Union-like stranglehold on information, CPJ said.
</P>
<P>
   --Fidel Castro, president of Cuba, accused by CPJ of keeping four
independent journalists in jail because of stories critical of the
Cuban system.
</P>
<P>
   --Jose Eduardo dos Santos, president of Angola, who allegedly has
made public mention of the rebel organization UNITA a crime.
</P>
<P>
   --Alberto Fujimori, president of Peru, described by the CPJ as
pooling his resources to cripple the thriving and vigorous press
that existed five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   --Mahathir Mohamad, prime minister of Malaysia, accused by CPJ of
controlling most major media in the country for nearly 20 years and
pressuring his country's small opposition press.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, Castro, Ben Ali, Fujimori and Mahathir have appeared on
the list before.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Committee to Protect Journalists: http://www.cpj.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 0222 </TRAILER>
