<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tower Air shuts down passenger service  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tower Air was known by travelers for its
no-frills approach, discounted airfares and delays. Now the airline
that filed for bankruptcy protection earlier this year has stopped
its passenger service.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are still operating charters and military flights but not
passenger flights,'' Pam Buoninconcri, director of corporate
relations for Tower, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger flights were discontinued Monday night, leaving some
ticketholders scrambling to find space on other carriers. The
airline had been flying to Los Angeles; Miami; San Juan, Puerto
Rico; Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic, and Tel Aviv, Israel.
Flights to San Francisco; Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; Athens, Greece,
and Paris were dropped as problems mounted in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300 Tel Aviv-bound passengers first learned the bad news
when they arrived Monday at John F. Kennedy International Airport
for their 11:30 p.m. flight.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those of us who had tickets already, who bought the tickets,
paid for them,'' said Andre Joseph, interviewed on the cable
television station New York 1. ''And finding out right now, in the
rain, that you're stuck here, that's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoninconcri said she did not know how many other flights had
been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Morrison, a spokesman for the Port Authority of New York
and New Jersey, said Port Authority staffers at Kennedy were
helping the stranded passengers book flights on other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mosley, a spokesman for the U.S. Department of
Transportation in Washington, said other carriers are not required
to honor Tower tickets but may do so.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Bishop-Cross, a spokeswoman for TWA, said the airline
would not accept Tower tickets but added: ''If someone has a Tower
Air ticket we will sell them a ticket and we will work with them to
get them the best deal possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoninconcri said passengers with Tower tickets could ask either
their travel agents or their credit card companies for refunds. She
said Tower could not provide refunds at this time ''because of our
bankruptcy position.''
</P>
<P>
   Tower Air Inc. filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in
February in the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   The same month, the airline, based at Kennedy Airport, said it
intended to cut 300 jobs, or 19 percent of its work force, and
reduce the size of its fleet by returning planes to their lessor.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Nachtomi, the company's president, chief executive and
chairman of the board, holds 77.2 percent of Tower's voting
securities, according to the bankruptcy filing. Nachtomi is the
managing general partner of the Nachtomi Family LP, which holds the
vast majority of those shares.
</P>
<P>
   Tower was known for low fares -- less than $400 round trip from
New York to Los Angeles, for example -- and spotty service. Delays
were routine, and Tower's fleet of aging Boeing 747s required
frequent maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the wrong airplanes with the wrong routes with the
wrong pricing,'' said Julius Maldutis, an airline industry analyst
with CIBC World Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Maldutis said other airlines have successfully emerged from
bankruptcy reorganization but that Tower would need ''a clear-cut
management strategy to turn the company around.''
</P>
<P>
   David Stempler, president of the Air Travelers Association, a
Washington D.C.-based organization that represents airline
passengers, said a number of factors contributed to Tower's
apparent woes, including fuel price increases and competition from
other low-priced carriers such as JetBlue and Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he noted, the leisure travelers whom Tower targeted
can now shop for low fares at Web sites like Priceline.com and
Lowestfare.com.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of places for people to go in the marketplace
to find low fares,'' Stempler said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Tower would resume passenger service at some
point, Buoninconcri said, ''I can't predict the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said the majority of Tower's employees have been let go,
adding, ''We will retain the services of the staff that will be
required to maintain our reduced operation and comply with
regulatory requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.towerair.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
