<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Rebukes Gene Therapy Researcher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- In a sharply worded warning letter, federal
officials accused a gene therapy researcher of failing to follow
key patient safeguards or properly report the death of a volunteer
patient.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged violations were outlined in the nine-page letter
dated April 28 and sent by the Food and Drug Administration to Dr.
Jeffrey Isner, a Tufts University scientist who headed the trials
at St. Elizabeth's Medical Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   One patient was included in a trial even though he had cancer, a
fact the FDA said could have been exacerbated by the treatment
which encourages blood vessel growth that in turn can feed tumors.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA said the patient's lung tumor doubled in size within
three months of being treated.
</P>
<P>
   The research team, whose trials were halted by the FDA in March,
also allegedly failed to investigate and properly report the death
of another patient.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the therapy caused her death 4{ months
after she received an injection of genetic material directly in her
heart. But the FDA said Isner only told hospital overseers of
complications despite being ''well aware'' of the death.
</P>
<P>
   ''Deviations in these studies appear to be the result of a
serious lack of knowledge of your responsibilities as principal
investigator including supervision of personnel,'' the FDA letter
said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said the enrollment of ineligible subjects, such as
the cancer patient, ''can be a serious protocol deviation.'' It
said such patients may have faced ''an unreasonable and significant
risk of illness or injury'' and that their inclusion may have
tainted the results of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Isner has 15 days to respond with a plan to correct the
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Gene therapy attempts to repair or replace abnormal genes in
seriously ill patients by transferring synthetically manufactured
genes into the body.
</P>
<P>
   The therapy has been under close scrutiny since the death of an
18-year-old volunteer in an experiment at the University of
Pennsylvania in September. The patient died of liver failure after
he received an injection of genes designed to correct a genetic
liver disease.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators have concluded that the experiment was not in
compliance with federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston trials sponsored by Vascular Genetics of Durham,
N.C., were aimed at growing new blood vessels around blocked heart
and leg arteries in patients who could not undergo traditional
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Isner could not be located for comment by The Associated Press
late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   St. Elizabeth's spokeswoman Sonia Hagopian said the hospital is
taking the letter seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ''It raises some questions about some aspects of care and
record-keeping and the medical center is in the process of putting
together a thoughtful and thorough response,'' Hagopian said in
today's Boston Herald.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 0505 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 09:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to complete state swing  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT EDWARD, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate
campaign was unveiling its first television ad today, a 30-second
spot that will air statewide beginning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said the ad was ''a
positive, biographical'' ad that doesn't mention the first lady's
Senate rival, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The ad focuses on the work Clinton has done over the 30 years in
public life.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani has already been advertising on television off
and on for several months, the Clinton spot is the first to be paid
for by her campaign. Late last year, the Democratic state committee
with money from the federal Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee ran an ad boosting Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   She was kicking off a two-day foray across northern New York
today that at its end will mean she has visited all 62 of New
York's counties in her 10 months on the Senate campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party Chairwoman Judith Hope noted Tuesday that
was not accomplished by Democratic Sen. Charles Schumer until late
last year, a full year after he defeated Republican incumbent
Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton is in the process of redefining New York state
politics, throwing traditional formulas out the window with her
relentless attention to counties that heretofore have been
ignored,'' Hope said. ''Clearly, upstate New York will be
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hope said the first lady's visit to all 62 counties was
not aimed at helping her overcome charges that she is a
carpetbagger, aides to Senate rival Mayor Rudolph Giuliani pressed
that point.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton can travel to as many counties, as many times as
she wants,'' Giuliani campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum said
Tuesday. ''It will not change the fact that she's never lived in
New York, never worked in New York and she has absolutely no
connection to New York. There's only one real New Yorker in this
race, Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton moved to the suburbs north of New York City in January.
She planned stops today in Washington, Hamilton and Franklin
counties.
</P>
<P>
   While the first lady was preparing Tuesday for her trip,
Teitelbaum tapped a veteran Republican operative to bolster the
mayor's upstate campaign effort.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City mayor, who learned last week that he has
prostate cancer, has been criticized by some fellow Republicans for
not spending enough time in traditionally more conservative upstate
New York while the first lady has been crisscrossing what is
expected to be a major electoral battleground this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''He knows this state like the back of his hand,'' Teitelbaum
said as he announced that state GOP executive director Brendan
Quinn will become director of statewide field operations for the
Giuliani campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gov. George Pataki continued to brush off questions
about whether he would take up the GOP Senate banner if the mayor
drops out of the race. ''I believe he will continue to run,''
Pataki said. Beyond that, the governor said, ''I'm not going to
speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have shown Pataki is the top choice among
Republican voters to take on Clinton if Giuliani drops out of the
race. The mayor said he will make his decision before the end of
May.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the campaign trail, aides to Giuliani were working
on setting up a meeting for later this week between the mayor and
state Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long. The two have been
at odds over the mayor's refusal to come out for a ban on what
critics call ''late-term abortion'' and his strong ties to the
Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, with Long's encouragement, former U.S. Rep. Joseph
DioGuardi announced he would seek the nominations of the
Conservative, Right to Life and Independence parties. A DioGuardi
candidacy could drain conservative votes away from the mayor, a
liability in a close race. Polls show the race is close.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Long said that ''at this stage of the game'' he did
not see Giuliani being the Conservative Party's candidate and
believed the nomination would go to DioGuardi. But Long cautioned
that could change before the party's June 3 state convention.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani said he would court the Conservative Party,
Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said the first lady would
ask the Liberal Party for its support although party boss Raymond
Harding is one of Giuliani's top political advisers. Both Giuliani
and Clinton are scheduled to meet with the Liberal Party's policy
committee Saturday in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
count the votes they receive on third-party ballot lines, a factor
in close races. In New York, no Republican has won statewide office
since 1974 without the Conservative Party line. Conversely, no
Democrat has been elected U.S. senator or governor without the
Liberal Party line since the party's founding in 1944.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
