<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers pushing $12.3 billion budget through General Assembly  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- With a midnight deadline looming, the
House was poised to give final legislative approval today to a
$12.3 billion budget that cuts taxes, boosts spending and plugs
holes in program shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate unanimously passed the spending side of the
budget Tuesday. The Senate then passed a $171 million tax cut
package to the House. The General Assembly must finish its business
by the time the legislative session ends at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts are in addition to $123 million in tax breaks approved
by the Legislature last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new breaks, drivers would get some relief at the pumps
with a 7-cent gas tax cut, and shoppers would keep some extra cash
in their pockets under increased clothing tax exemptions and a week
of tax-free shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also includes $75 million in tax breaks to the
state's hospitals and $54 million in cuts for industry and
broadcasters, of which $15 million goes to Bristol-based ESPN. The
sports broadcasting giant is planning a $500 million expansion of
its world headquarters that could mean up to 1,000 new jobs in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.3 billion budget is about $150 million more than what
the Legislature agreed to spend last year for the 2001 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   About $40 million of the increase is going to new programs; the
rest is needed to make inflation adjustments and cover agencies and
programs running in the red.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Medicaid program, Department of Correction and
Department of Children and Families needed cash infusions.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also earmarks $3 million for enhancements at the
state's three juvenile detention facilities in Bridgeport, Hartford
and New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   About $4.4 million is slated to ease prison overcrowding by
creating more treatment programs. Since last year, 484 Connecticut
inmates have been transferred to a Virginia prison to thin the
state's prison population.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could have nonviolent offenders in treatment center and
free up needed beds,'' said Sen. Donald Williams, D-Killingly.
</P>
<P>
   About $1.5 million is being used to expand eligibility
requirement for the state's ConnPace prescription drug program.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted more, but that's palatable enough for now,'' said
Rep. James Amann, D-Milford. ''It will be able to help some
individuals this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to budget expenditures, lawmakers were poised to
carve up about $250 million of surplus money.
</P>
<P>
   About $20 million of that is earmarked for a bailout of
deficit-plagued University of Connecticut Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   Another $34 million of the surplus would be doled out to towns
in one-shot grants. Municipalities would be able to decide how best
to use the grant money, which ranges from $22,000 for Union to $3.3
million for New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus also will sink $43 million into school construction
and $10 million into getting classrooms wired for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We care about schools because we have provided money for
school construction,'' said Rep. William Dyson, D-New Haven. ''We
care about the schools because we're making sure the digital divide
doesn't get any wider.''
</P>
<P>
   While the budget intends give students a leg up in the
classroom, it also gives their parents a break in paying for school
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic backed measure pushed the clothing tax exemption
from $50 to $75. In return, the GOP won out on a one week-long
sales tax exemption on clothing priced up to $300.
</P>
<P>
   The gas tax cut is expected to save $85 to $140 a year for a
family that drives 30,000 miles. In addition, lowering the tax
would keep Connecticut drivers from crossing state lines to fill
their tanks at cheaper prices, supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   Although the budget represents a series of compromises between
Democrats and Republicans, the two sides failed to agree on a
tuition tax credit plan proposed by Republican Gov. John G.
Rowland. The budget will not include the proposal to give families
up to $500 to send their children to private schools. Opponents of
the tax credits say they're too much like vouchers that would drain
money from public education.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also dropped a proposal to whittle adults out of the
state's HUSKY health care plan -- a program they had argued is too
costly and could have saved the state about $32 million. The
program was originally designed to provide health care for
uninsured children, but was expanded to include their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.3 billion budget stays about $51 million under the
state's mandatory spending cap. But expenditure of the surplus
breaks the spending cap by about $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature also is expected to approve a package of bonding
projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
