<HEADLINE> Report: grand juror to look into dispute over murder evidence  </HEADLINE>
sfnhrdsrh
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- A grand jury will investigate a dispute
between North Haven and New Haven police involving a murder
investigation, the New Haven Register reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting unnamed sources, the newspaper said a panel of three
judges has approved a request for a grand jury to consider whether
New Haven police supervisors criminally withheld evidence from
North Haven authorities in a 1996 murder case.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also reported that the New Haven State's
Attorney's Office, which launched the investigation earlier this
year, transferred the case to the chief state's attorney in Rocky
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Michael Dearington and Police Chief Melvin H. Wearing
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Dearington began investigating the New Haven
detective bureau's handling of evidence in the 1996 murder of North
Haven resident Phillip Cusick.
</P>
<P>
   Dearington applied for a grand jury when his investigation
stalled, the Register reported. A grand jury's investigative powers
are stronger than the state's attorney's.
</P>
<P>
   Cusick's body was found Nov. 6, 1996, in front of his home in
North Haven, but police suspect he was shot in New Haven and dumped
there. North Haven police have made no arrests in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, two New Haven detectives took a statement from an
informant that allegedly implicated a suspect, but there is some
dispute over whether that evidence was given to North Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives Stephen G. Coppola and Edwin Rodriguez taped the
statement and brought it to their supervisors, who allegedly told
them to drop the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
