<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Wednesday, May 3, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   London, German Exchanges To Merge
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The London and Frankfurt stock exchanges plan to
merge, creating Europe's largest stock market and a powerful
regional counterweight to Wall Street. Under the plan announced
today, the London exchange and Germany's Deutsche Boerse would each
own 50 percent of the new entity, which is to be called iX, for
International Exchanges. Headquarters will be in London. Shares in
blue-chip companies would be traded in London, while shares in
high-tech firms would be traded in Frankfurt, the London Stock
Exchange said. The Anglo-German union includes a joint venture
agreement with Nasdaq Europe Ltd., the European subsidiary of the
technology-heavy U.S. Nasdaq market, to create a European market
for high-growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Factory Orders Rebound Strongly
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New orders to American factories bounced back
in March, rising a bigger-than-expected 2.2 percent, led by the
largest jump in demand for electronic equipment in more than two
years. The Commerce Department reported today that factory orders
rose to a seasonally adjusted $383.2 billion after showing no
change in February and declining in January. March's 2.2 percent
increase in factory orders was the best showing since a 3.8 percent
gain in December and was stronger than the 1.6 percent rise many
analysts were anticipating. The Federal Reserve has boosted
interest rates five times since June 30 in an effort to slow the
red-hot economy and keep inflation under control. But the hikes
have not done much to cool demand.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Down 98; Nasdaq Down 72
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks are mostly lower this morning as
interest-rate worries weigh on traders seeking direction in a quiet
market. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average
was down 98.35 at 10,632.77. Decliners on the New York Stock
Exchange outnumbered advancers 1,470-893. The Nasdaq composite
index was down 72.42 at 3,713.03.
</P>
