<P>
   Bestfoods Nixes Unilever Bid
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A U.S. buying spree by international consumer
products conglomerate Unilever has hit a snag, with Bestfoods'
rejection of an $18.4 billion takeover offer. Bestfoods, the maker
of such household food products as Skippy peanut butter and
Hellmann's mayonnaise, said yesterday its board had unanimously
rejected the $66 a share bid. Unilever, whose brands include Lipton
teas, Vaseline and Pepsodent toothpaste, agreed last month to
purchase Vermont gourmet ice cream company Ben &AMP; Jerry's for around
$326 million and diet foods company Slim Fast Foods for $2.3
billion. It's offer for Bestfoods represented a 31 percent premium
over the company's closing price of 50 9/16 in trading yesterday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Coke Executives Unveil Morale Plans
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola Co.'s top executives have announced
plans to boost employee morale by improving compensation, closing
on Friday afternoons in the summer and offering a new paid holiday.
Chairman Doug Daft and president Jack Stahl spoke to employees
yesterday in separate meetings, spokesman Ben Deutsch said. The
attempt to improve morale at Coke comes more than three months
after the soft drink giant announced a reorganization that will
result in the loss of 5,200 jobs worldwide. The cuts include 2,500
in Atlanta, 40 percent of the workforce at the company's
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch Daughter To Start New Co.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Media tycoon Rupert Murdoch's daughter Elizabeth
announced today that she will leave the satellite TV operation
British Sky Broadcasting this summer to set up her own company. A
statement on BSkyB's Web site said she would step down in June as
managing director of Sky Networks, in which her father's News Corp.
owns a 40 percent stake, to set up her own British-based company
specializing in television, film and new media programs. It was not
immediately clear whether her father would have any connection to
the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann Postpones Book IPO
</P>
<P>
   GUETERSLOH, Germany (AP) -- Europe's biggest media conglomerate,
Bertelsmann AG, said Wednesday it was postponing indefinitely the
initial public offering of its online bookstore because of the
recent decline in Internet stocks. Bertelsmann said in March it
hoped to sell off 23 percent of its bol.com unit in an IPO
scheduled for sometime in the next few weeks. Management board
member Klaus Eierhoff said the retreat of high tech stocks on
Germany's Nemax 50 Index could unjustifiably depress the value of
bol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Oil Cos. Commit $100B to Saudi
</P>
<P>
   JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Western oil companies have committed
to invest $100 billion over the next 20 years in Saudi Arabia's oil
and gas sectors, the official who oversees oil policy said today.
Prince Saud al-Faisal, who is foreign minister as well as head of
the Supreme Petroleum Council, did not name any of the companies
but said they were among the industry's ''super-giants.'' Saudi
Arabia is the world's No. 1 oil producer and exporter. He said no
specific agreements had yet been signed and that a negotiating
committee would be formed over the next few weeks to work out the
details. He said he expected negotiations to be finalized by the
end of the year. Saud said that the national oil company Aramco
will participate in the execution of the projects.
</P>
