<HEADLINE> Euro Sinks Below 90 Cents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The euro sank below 90 cents today for the first
time as the U.S. dollar gained against most other key currencies in
European trading. Gold prices rose.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted as low as 88.90 cents this morning, down
from 90.66 cents late Tuesday. It bounced back to 89.24 cents by
early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The previous low since the euro began trading in January 1999 as
the single currency of 11 European nations was 90.30 cents set last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only if the market loses faith in the Fed (U.S. Federal
Reserve Board) will the dollar crumble against the euro,'' said
Steve Barrow, currency strategist at Bear Stearns. ''At the moment,
there is no sign of that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates included 108.78 Japanese yen, up from 108.63;
1.7250 Swiss francs, down from 1.7181, and 1.4861 Canadian dollars,
up from 1.4855.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound was quoted at $1.5619, up from $1.5582.
</P>
<P>
   Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth 2.1763 German marks, up
from 2.1557; 7.2884 French francs, up from 7.2322; 2.4486 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.4297, and 2,151.41 Italian lire, up from
2,134.81.
</P>
<P>
   Gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price of $277.60 per
troy ounce, up from $275.20 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Zurich the bid was $276.80, up from $274.65.
</P>
<P>
   Gold rose $2.40 in Hong Kong to $277.55.
</P>
<P>
   Silver opened in London at $5.01 per troy ounce, down from
$5.02.
</P>
