<HEADLINE> Female Sex Dysfunction Device OK'd  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Women with sexual problems can now try the
first government-approved medical device to help them achieve
orgasm by pumping blood into the clitoris.
</P>
<P>
   While Viagra and penile devices have revolutionized impotence
treatment for men, women's sexual problems haven't fared as well.
In fact, women's sexual dysfunction has largely been considered a
psychological problem.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Food and Drug Administration has approved a medical
device called Eros that treats a physical problem behind ''female
sexual arousal disorder.'' The rationale behind the device is that
blood flow into the clitoris is as important for women's sexual
arousal and satisfaction as blood flow into the penis is for men.
</P>
<P>
   Eros, made by UroMetrics Inc. of St. Paul, Minn., consists of a
soft suction cup to be placed over the clitoris. A tube attaches it
to a handheld, battery-operated vacuum device. Users need only to
switch on the vacuum, turning it up or down as needed, for a few
minutes until the clitoris feels engorged. They then turn it off
and remove the suction cup.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA approved Eros to be sold by prescription only, for women
diagnosed with ''female sexual arousal disorder'' or FSAD, the
female equivalent of impotence. UroMetrics said the device is
available immediately, but did not reveal a price.
</P>
<P>
   Female sexual dysfunction is characterized by the inability to
achieve orgasm, painful intercourse because of vaginal dryness,
lack of clitoral sensation or diminished interest in sex.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how many women suffer the problem, although some
estimates suggest half of all women experience sexual dysfunction
at some point in their lives, said Dr. Diane Mitchell, an FDA
gynecologist who reviewed Eros.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, estrogen therapy and vaginal lubricants, to counter
dryness, were women's main options. Viagra, the little blue
anti-impotence pill taken by thousands of men, is being tested in
women with mixed results so far.
</P>
<P>
   Eros becomes the first FDA-approved product to address clitoral
dysfunction. In a study of 15 women diagnosed with FSAD, 80 percent
reported increased sexual satisfaction and some reported orgasms.
The study also included 10 normal women, some of whom reported more
sexual satisfaction as well.
</P>
<P>
   But Eros did not help every women, Mitchell warned. ''This
device is not going to be a panacea,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1155 </TRAILER>
