<DOCNO> APW20000503.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Lily King  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA NOONAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Lily King's gentle debut novel, ''The
Pleasing Hour,'' centers on a young American au pair who becomes
part of the emotional life of a French family.
</P>
<P>
   The coming of-age tale set in Paris has been compared by critics
to the fiction of Henry James and Jane Austen and to the 1997
postmodern comedy, ''Le Divorce,'' by Diane Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The novel has also become something of a first-time author's
success story, generating a bidding war between several publishers
before Atlantic Monthly Press agreed to pay nearly $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The novel has a first printing of 45,000 copies, more than twice
the average for a literary debut. Scribner has reportedly paid a
six-figure sum for paperback rights, and ''The Pleasing Hour''
enjoys prominent display in Barnes &AMP; Nobles stores nationwide as
the chain's most recent recipient of the Discover Great New Writers
Award.
</P>
<P>
   It's all been quite a reception for an easygoing 35-year-old
author who still enjoys membership in a book club, filling in as a
substitute high school English teacher and taking care of her
infant daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But King says she's not fazed. ''I try not to put too much
pressure on myself,'' she says with a laugh, during an interview at
a local bakery cafe.
</P>
<P>
   While King herself spent time as a part-time au pair for a
''wonderful'' French family shortly after college, the story of
Rosie, who skips out on college to go to Paris to work as an au
pair, is decidedly nonautobiographical, King says.
</P>
<P>
   The book's heroine is a thoughtful and sensitive young woman
running from a very real demon: the recent surrender of an infant
son to her infertile older sister.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie escapes to the Tivot family -- parents Marc and Nicole, and
their three children, Odile, 16, Lola, 12, and Guillaume, 9.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Rosie finds herself in a strange competition with
beautiful, judgmental Nicole, and is quickly waved aside by Odile
and Guillaume, too old and too young -- respectively -- to need her.
</P>
<P>
   But Lola and Marc both crave the closeness and acceptance they
can't get from the emotionally unavailable Nicole, and gravitate
toward Rosie's warmth.
</P>
<P>
   King, a graduate of the University of North Carolina, said the
inspiration for ''The Pleasing Hour'' didn't come until the final
semesters of graduate school at Syracuse University, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Outlines of Rosie and the Tivots emerged in two, unsuccessful
short stories she wrote at Syracuse. The stories weren't well
received by her creative writing classmates, but the author was
positive there was something special.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody liked them,'' King recalls with a laugh. ''But I didn't
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried about letting the material fade away, King vowed to keep
up with the novel after leaving Syracuse to teach high school
English in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrical, almost poetic writing in ''The Pleasing Hour'' was
a departure from the trends King had witnessed in graduate school,
where short, terse sentences, a la Raymond Carver, were the rage.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was trying to put a lot more care and attention into my
language,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the long gestation of ''The Pleasing Hour,'' the
hardest character to flesh out was Nicole, the Tivot's cold,
enigmatic mother, a figure who stayed distant until the final
drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ''She wasn't turning into anything but an ice queen,'' recalls
King. ''It was very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the author drew on the memory of female friend of her
host family as a model for developing the character of Nicole. It
worked.
</P>
<P>
   After the manuscript was accepted, and a publication date was
finalized for early 1999, King learned she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing she couldn't manage a 16-city book tour in the latest
stages of pregnancy, the publication date was pushed back until
September. Then, King and her 6-month-old daughter, Calla, went on
the tour together, met by friends and family in almost every city.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pleasing Hour'' fans are predominantly women, but middle-aged
men and Francophiles also are drawn to the story. So, King was not
surprised to see a considerable cadre of men showing up at book
signings for a novel about women.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is an underappreciated, unexplored population of
men reading and liking (so-called women's) literature that focuses
on language and history,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   King has no plans for a ''Pleasing Hour'' sequel, but has
embarked on a novel about a mother who teaches English at the her
son's high school. Tentatively set in the late 1970s, the book will
deal with themes of alcoholism and loss, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Massachusetts, King cites as her literary influences
Shirley Hazzard's ''Transit of Venus'' and ''Evening of the
Holiday,'' as well as Virginia Woolf's ''To the Lighthouse'' and
Marilyn Robinson's ''Housekeeping.''
</P>
<P>
   She now lives in Cambridge, just a few miles from Harvard
University, with her husband Tyler Clements, an Internet
entrepreneur and writer, and their baby daughter.
</P>
<P>
   King says she continues to enjoy teaching English from time to
time, and is in the middle of ''War and Peace'' for her book club.
</P>
<P>
   The club, a collection of friends who love writing and reading,
recently chose ''The Pleasing Hour'' as a selection. The group had
nothing but positive comments.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were very supportive,'' King recalls, smiling. ''They
knew I was very vulnerable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1204 </TRAILER>
