<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Recall Painting With O'Keeffe  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Two men a generation apart have similar
stories to tell about painting with Georgia O'Keeffe.
</P>
<P>
   John Poling, a philosophy professor at St. Olaf College in
Northfield, Minn., and Jacobo ''Jackie'' Suazo, a retired state
employee in Santa Fe, each recall being welcomed by O'Keeffe at her
Abiquiu home, doing chores and, ultimately, being allowed to paint
with her.
</P>
<P>
   Poling has written a bittersweet memoir, ''Painting With
O'Keeffe,'' and Suazo has filed copyright claims for at least three
paintings once attributed to O'Keeffe. Those three paintings are
part of the so-called Canyon Suite of 28 watercolors challenged by
experts associated with the National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Both men say they were hired to do chores -- the 9-year-old
Suazo, to water O'Keeffe's trees in the 1940s, and Poling, to paint
the wooden trim on her house in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Poling says he worked with O'Keeffe when she was 88 and her
eyesight was failing. He said he helped her paint three canvases --
two of them views of the Washington Monument and one of a patio
door at her house.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident that O'Keeffe could barely see, he says in a book
that paints a poignant portrait of the artist as an elderly woman
dependent on her assistant, Juan Hamilton. It shows her wanting to
create but unable to execute the works she could see so clearly in
her mind's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Poling says he followed her explicit instructions in laying out
those paintings for her, with O'Keeffe standing beside him while he
painted. O'Keeffe herself added some touches, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The patio door painting was shown as her work at a dinner party
with several of her friends, Poling said, and one of the Washington
Monument paintings was presented in an ARTnews magazine article as
new work by O'Keeffe without noting Poling's assistance, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Poling said the article made him feel as though he were part of
a deception, and he asked O'Keeffe to set the record straight. The
confrontation ended their relationship on a bitter, painful note.
</P>
<P>
   His book quotes O'Keeffe as accusing him: ''You're just after
something for yourself, aren't you?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the dispute landed with a splash in a Santa Fe weekly
newspaper, The Reporter. It carried two articles including comment
by O'Keeffe, Hamilton and Poling. Hamilton suggested Poling write a
letter noting his concerns to the Beinecke Library at Yale
University, where the O'Keeffe papers are kept for scholars.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe was quoted as saying in the newspaper: ''He was nothing
but a tool. ... He had no thought, no part in the painting, except
that he could do what I told him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Minnesota, Poling recalled:
''O'Keeffe said I was the equivalent of a palette knife.''
</P>
<P>
   He said she misunderstood his intentions and, had he been able
to explain his feelings better, she would have understood.
</P>
<P>
   Poling's assistance on the Washington Monument paintings is
acknowledged in the just-released ''Catalogue Raisonne'' of
O'Keeffe's work jointly issued by the National Gallery of Art and
the Georgia O'Keeffe Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Poling says he was told the painting of the patio door was
destroyed because of technical problems that arose with the work,
and there is no mention of it in the ''Catalogue Raisonne.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe continues to be an inspiration for Poling, who teaches
a course called ''Georgia O'Keeffe: Philosophy and Art.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It uses O'Keeffe's life and her art, what it is to be an
artist, what it is to be successful as a human being and how
O'Keeffe in many ways brought those things together in a striking
way,'' he says of the course. ''She said so many on-target things
about art.''
</P>
<P>
   Poling met O'Keeffe partly through the connection of his father
-- the Rev. David Poling, a Presbyterian minister -- with the
neighboring Presbyterian Church-owned Ghost Ranch. He knew little
about the artist back in 1976 but has done much study about her
since.
</P>
<P>
   He believes ultimately in her integrity, he says.
</P>
<P>
   And he sometimes imagines what it would have been like if things
had ended differently for the friendship between him and O'Keeffe.
He would have liked to have helped her paint additional canvases,
for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have liked to see the other things that would have
happened with that collaboration,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Suazo, on the other hand, claims he lived with O'Keeffe -- almost
as a foster child -- with the approval of his mother, who lived
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ''These arrangements my mother didn't like very much, but later
she realized the association between me and Miss O'Keeffe was very
good for me,'' Suazo says. ''Miss O'Keeffe started helping me all
the time on how to do art work.''
</P>
<P>
   He did oil, acrylic and watercolor paintings as well as drawings
with charcoal, pencils and pastels.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess we had 100 paintings that I did,'' he says, and they
were kept in a large storage room, or ''salita,'' at O'Keeffe's
adobe home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, when Suazo joined the Marine Corps, he left the
paintings with O'Keeffe. He never saw any of them again -- until, he
contends, he saw one of them printed last fall along with a
newspaper article about the Canyon Suite.
</P>
<P>
   In the final years of O'Keeffe's life, he said, he tried to get
the paintings back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried going over there, but they would never let me in. I
didn't know whether my paintings were even still there or they had
thrown them away,'' says Suazo, a retired investigator with the
state Human Rights Division.
</P>
<P>
   When she died, he received $30,000 from the estate but no
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   After the Canyon Suite story broke, Suazo went to Kemper Museum
officials in Kansas City and claimed some of the watercolors were
his.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Washington lawyer Ernie Sanchez filed a copyright
claim on behalf of Suazo. It asserts copyright claims to 13 of the
28 Canyon Suite watercolors Suazo says he collaborated on with
O'Keeffe and an additional three of them he claims he did all by
himself, according to Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   Suazo is looking for reproduction rights, in the event anyone
wanted to make prints or posters.
</P>
<P>
   Suazo's claims came after the National Gallery excluded the
works from the ''Catalogue Raisonne.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of how the paintings surfaced in 1988, two years after
O'Keeffe died, is well known in Canyon, Texas, where O'Keeffe had
been head of the art department from 1916-18 at West Texas Normal
College, now West Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, longtime O'Keeffe friend and confidant Ted
Reid of Canyon gave a packet of watercolors to his granddaughter's
father-in-law. The father-in-law, Emilio Caballero, a prominent
watercolorist and former art chairman at West Texas A&AMP;M, turned the
paintings over to his son and daughter-in-law, who sought to
determine if they were O'Keeffe's.
</P>
<P>
   Once authenticated, Santa Fe dealer Gerald Peters purchased them
for $1 million, then sold them to the Kemper Museum for $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Then the authentication started to come apart. As work
progressed on the ''Catalogue Rainsonne,'' additional information
surfaced about the paper used in some of the paintings. Such paper
could not have been used by O'Keeffe during her time in Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Peters refunded the money to Kemper, and the paintings were
returned to Peters, who is currently having additional research
done on them.
</P>
<P>
   Suazo said in an interview that he never met Reid and cannot
explain how pictures he painted in the 1940s in Abiquiu could get
mixed in with pictures that supposedly originated 30 years earlier
-- before he was born -- in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He says he was saddened when he saw the paintings but that he
would always love O'Keeffe for all she did for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll love her until I meet her again, I guess,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
