<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Re-Animator' Back From the Dead?  </HEADLINE>
By DOUGLAS J. ROWE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''Re-Animator'' is just the kind of trippy movie
people high on pot would talk and giggle about -- just as they do in
the latest best-picture Oscar winner, ''American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're in the cult that remembers the 1985 film about
bringing people back from the dead, you probably didn't catch what
the Kevin Spacey and Wes Bentley characters were riffing about when
they're smoking marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the Oscar-winning ''American Beauty'' -- which
comes out on video May 9 -- doesn't necessarily translate into
renewed life for ''Re-Animator.'' (And it certainly shouldn't for
its sequel, ''Bride of Re-Animator''.) That's according to Patrick
Mathewes, a researcher at Screenplay, which provides movie trailer
reels for video store use.
</P>
<P>
   ''The average person is less likely to take out a film like
'Re-Animator,''' says Mathewes, whose business is linked to Rain
City Video, a Seattle store specializing in offbeat and
hard-to-find tapes. ''They have sort of a prejudice against it, for
whatever reason.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more than a bias against the genre in this case, he says:
''Some people don't want to see someone walking around without
their head.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, based on an H.P. Lovecraft story, a mad-genius
medical student named Herbert West invents a re-animating serum
that brings the dead back to life. An older doctor wants to take
credit for it, so West lops off his head with a shovel.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the young man finds the doctor isn't letting his
decapitation interfere with his sex life, he says: ''I'm very
disappointed in you. You steal the secret of life and death and
here you are trysting with a bubbled-head coed. You're not even a
second-rate scientist ...
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll never get credit for my discovery. They'll never
believe a talking head. Get a job in a sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie anticipated ''Scream'' and ''I Know What You Did Last
Summer'' by having such a sense of humor about itself.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Stuart Gordon, ''Re-Animator'' stars Jeffrey Combs
as West, Bruce Abbott and Barbara Crampton -- all of whom have
recurrently made B horror movies.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Vrieling, owner of Rain City Video, noted that
''Re-Animator'' was checked out of the store as he spoke and had
gone out more than usual recently -- but there was no way of telling
if that's from the ''American Beauty'' reference or not.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Dennis, owner of the Movie Place in New York, hasn't seen
any spike in rentals of ''Re-Animator.'' And there usually isn't
when a movie just makes a passing reference to another movie, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to ''King Kong'' in ''The Cider House Rules''
didn't result in any uptick of rentals, either.
</P>
<P>
   But in that case, Mathewes said, ''People assume they know all
about that movie even though they haven't seen it in years or may
not have ever seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   The one way that a movie inevitably gets a rush of rentals is
when there's a remake, Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It happens all the time,'' he said. ''When 'The Talented Mr.
Ripley' came out, people started renting 'Purple Noon,' which is a
French version of the same story.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that last year's redo of ''The Thomas Crown Affair''
created a call for the original, and he's going to stock another
copy of the original ''Shaft'' in anticipation of this summer's
reprise that'll star Samuel L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ''American Beauty'' on video could spark renewed interest
in ''Re-Animator,'' Mathewes said.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings to mind some dialogue from the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dead?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Not anymore!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1205 </TRAILER>
