<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Unfortunate Events' Books Praised  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Try pitching this as a series of children's
novels: Three young siblings -- handsome, clever and rich -- lose
their loving parents in a fire that destroys their mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Too gloomy? It gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the shell-shocked trio are bounced between a series
of clueless caregivers as a diabolical distant cousin -- an
audacious count who heads a roguish troupe of actors -- relentlessly
pursues the tots, scheming to get his hands on their inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Not half bad.
</P>
<P>
   And the pitch seems to have worked as well. Volumes of the bleak
little books, published under the title ''A Series of Unfortunate
Events,'' have sold more than 100,000 copies, with a feature-length
film and television series in the works. ''The Bad Beginning,'' the
first book in the series, is in its sixth printing and plans are
under way to translate the series into four languages.
</P>
<P>
   Written by an enigmatic, pseudonymous author named Lemony
Snicket, the tales are earning high praise and a fierce following
among adults as well as children. The series is illustrated by
Brett Helquist.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Pettid, owner of Reading Reptile, an independent children's
bookstore in Kansas City, Mo., says ''The Bad Beginning'' is her
top-selling book. Pettid read a copy of the manuscript last summer,
just before its September publication.
</P>
<P>
   ''It blew me away,'' she says. ''I loved it. It was so different
from any other fiction I'd read. It was so fresh and so clever --
and dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine ''Oliver Twist'' meets ''Matilda,'' with illustrations
by Edward Gorey. The books are ''very gothic'' and more
sophisticated than most marketed for 10-year-olds, the series'
target audience, says Jennifer Brown, children's forecasts editor
for Publishers Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The series -- four books so far, with a fifth due in August --
have yet to appear on Publishers Weekly's best-seller list, but
have been well received by the magazine's critics, who gave the
first two books a starred review.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Snelson, editor of children's books at Amazon.com, says
the books are among the best-selling titles for older children at
the online retailer's site. She picked ''The Bad Beginning'' as one
of Amazon.com's top 10 middle-grade books of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''I definitely wanted it to get some attention because I thought
it was a lot of fun,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The book this month ranked among the retailer's top 1,500
sellers, Snelson says. ''That's a pretty high rank, especially for
a middle-grade novel.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest volume, ''The Miserable Mill,'' released in April, is
selling nearly as many copies online as ''The Bad Beginning,''
Snelson says. ''They definitely are gaining momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   The books' wry humor has made them particularly popular in
Canada, where mainstream humor looks more like Americans'
alternative humor, says series editor Susan Rich.
</P>
<P>
   While no one expects the series -- or any series -- to match the
stratospheric sales of J.K. Rowling's ''Harry Potter'' books,
Snelson and others say Snicket's books are following the same
word-of-mouth path to popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will just be more kids sharing them with each other,
librarians spreading the word and so on,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Pettid and other booksellers are ''hand-selling'' the books,
recommending them highly to customers and promoting the series
through readings and promotional events -- much as booksellers
spread the gospel of Harry Potter. And the books' low price -- $8.95
for the tiny hardcovers -- makes them an appealing commodity.
</P>
<P>
   One Amazon.com customer noted on the company's Web site: ''My
second-grader and I despaired of ever finding a series that we'd
enjoy reading together as much as we enjoyed Harry Potter. We found
it!''
</P>
<P>
   But the series may be most noteworthy for the ways in which it's
not like Harry Potter. There's not a whiff of magic between the
covers -- the wee heroes rely upon their wits, period. Outside,
there are no glowing reviews or airy cover illustrations. Instead,
Snicket's books offer dark, moody portraits and dire warnings to
potential readers. Each book features a blurb that gives readers
the impression they're picking up a bottle of drain cleaner instead
of a children's book.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you are interested in stories with happy endings, you would
be better off reading some other book,'' the first volume begins.
''In this book, not only is there no happy ending, there is no
happy beginning and very few happy things in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   In that unhappy first chapter, Violet, Klaus and Sunny
Baudelaire ride a rickety trolley to Briny Beach one gray day,
unaware that a fire has killed their parents and destroyed their
home and all their lovely belongings. The tiny orphans are taken in
by Mr. Poe, a distracted, consumptive banker and family friend who
packs them off to live with the scabrous Count Olaf. The count, who
forces the children to cook and clean for his friends, a menacing
troupe of actors, wants nothing more than to get his hands on the
children's fortune.
</P>
<P>
   After narrowly escaping the villain in the first book, the
children are sent to live with a series of adults, each of whom
puts the children in harm's way again and again. In each volume,
Count Olaf reappears, thinly disguised, with another plan to grab
the Baudelaires' inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, only the children recognize him each time, and it
often seems as if the only thing standing in the way of their
liberation is an excruciating case of good manners.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Violet, an inventive 14-year-old, her bookish
12-year-old brother Klaus and their baby sister, Sunny (her
strength is in the exceeding sharpness of her four baby teeth) fend
for themselves, enduring knives, falling lamps, lightning storms,
poisonous snakes, man-eating leeches, hook-handed henchmen and a
hypnotic optometrist, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the series' mystique, the books offer virtually no
information about Snicket, a dogged, mournful storyteller forever
on the run, leaving his manuscripts in unlikely places for his
editor to retrieve.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Snicket is ''represented'' by a 30-year-old
novelist named Daniel Handler.
</P>
<P>
   Handler's first book for adults, a dark comic novel titled ''The
Basic Eight,'' was published last year by St. Martin's Press. His
second, ''Watch Your Mouth'' -- which he describes as ''an incest
comedy'' -- will appear this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Handler, a 1992 graduate of Wesleyan University, grew up in San
Francisco. The son of an accountant and a college dean, Handler
started out writing poetry, but soon switched to fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ''My poems were getting longer and longer, and more and more
proselike,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Handler wrote short stories and ''most of a novel that I ended
up throwing away.'' Then in 1993, he won an Olin fellowship, which
enabled him to write ''The Basic Eight.'' He later spent two years
writing comedy for ''The House of Blues Radio Hour,'' a syndicated
radio show based in San Francisco. After moving to New York City,
he wrote free-lance movie reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Unfortunate Events'' books took shape after Handler
pitched the proposal -- ''small children placed in despicable
circumstances'' -- to Rich, a children's books editor at
HarperCollins.
</P>
<P>
   Handler had been toying with the idea of a ''mock gothic novel''
and was tired of chipper stories in which the bully gets his
comeuppance at the end. Why not let the bad guy go? he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Daniel first shared the idea with me, my first fear was
that we might be the only two in the world who thought it was so
brilliant,'' Rich says.
</P>
<P>
   Together they developed the series, striking what Rich calls
''the perfect balance between delight and despair.''
</P>
<P>
   The dark tone grew out of Handler's taste in reading as a child.
He avoided books in which ''everybody goes to camp and has a good
time,'' he says. ''I really preferred books in which a troll came
to town and cut off everybody's head.''
</P>
<P>
   Handler dreamed up the odd pseudonym Lemony Snicket under
duress, during a telephone conversation five years ago. While
researching radical right-wing groups for ''The Basic Eight,'' he
found himself on the phone with a member of one group, who asked
for Handler's name.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to be on their mailing lists,'' he says. The
name Lemony Snicket ''just popped into my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, someone pointed out that the name sounds a lot
like ''Jiminy Cricket,'' which pleases Handler, since Snicket and
Cricket seem similar in important ways.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always hated that snively, overly moralistic insect,'' he
says. ''It pleases me that my name has been an inadvertent
perversion of him.''
</P>
<P>
   At readings, the 6-foot-tall Handler appears nattily dressed,
apologetically announcing that Snicket, bitten by a bug and
paralyzed from the armpits down, couldn't attend. During the
reading, Handler clumsily slips up. Little by little, children
figure out that he is Snicket.
</P>
<P>
   Handler also has been known to strap on an accordion and deliver
a ballad, Tom Lehrer-style, telling just how evil Count Olaf really
is.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Count Olaf treads a fine line between super-villain
and supreme bumbler. His schemes tend to get more desperate each
time -- in the newest book, he appears in drag, wearing a blonde wig
and pale lipstick, posing as a stubbly-legged receptionist named
Shirley.
</P>
<P>
   ''His profit margin gets slimmer and slimmer with each plan,''
Handler says.
</P>
<P>
   But the relentless count clearly has unsavory thoughts. In fact,
Snicket's scheduled appearances last fall at an elementary school
and bookstore in Decatur, Ga., were canceled after school officials
protested his use of the word ''damn'' in the second book, ''The
Reptile Room,'' and a strange plot twist in ''The Bad Beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   In that story, Olaf stages a play in which he forces Violet to
play his bride. The scheme -- to marry the girl for real in order to
steal the family fortune -- collapses when Violet comes up with a
way to wiggle out of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur school officials found the plot a bit distasteful,
Handler says. He waved off criticism of the mock wedding, pointing
out that Violet's cleverness gets her out of the bind.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, not everyone loves the dry satire of the series,
which also includes ''The Wide Window,'' ''The Miserable Mill'' and
''The Austere Academy,'' which will be released in August.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Sutton, editor in chief of The Horn Book Magazine, a
Boston-based children's book review, said he read the first two
books but didn't plan to review them.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not to my taste,'' he said. ''I think the humor is
adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Brooks, the children's book buyer for the three-store
Anderson's Bookshop chain in Chicago, said she enjoyed the series,
but added, ''I just wish he'd shake it up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most series, the books have worked themselves into a
well-worn groove -- in most of the stories, an adult meets a cruel
end, while the three orphans survive, ready to be packed off to
some other gloomy-sounding spot such as Lake Lachrymose or
Paltryville.
</P>
<P>
   But the series manages to stay strangely uplifting, even through
the march of misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're comforting, in an odd sort of way,'' Pettid says.
''The kids are clever, they're all good at something, they rely on
each other and they're reasonable. Books can be reassuring in a way
that's not sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins has contracted for eight Snicket titles, with
plans to release three per year. Rich says the series' arc will be
complete by the end of the 13th book, with more details emerging
about Snicket's quest to detail the Baudelaire children's fate.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher promoted the first three books with a small book
tour and a ''Magnets for Misfortune'' poetry contest, sending out
sheets of tiny magnetic words and printing the winner's poem in the
dedication to ''The Miserable Mill.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicists also sent out eerie ''chain letters'' threatening
dire consequences if retailers didn't spread the word on the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Handler is on a seven-city book tour this month. Meanwhile,
Nickelodeon is negotiating for the series' film and television
rights, with plans for Handler to write the first screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   As for what readers can expect in the next several volumes, Rich
says, simply: ''More misfortune.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet: http://www.harperchildrens.com/lsnicket/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1205 </TRAILER>
