<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Catatonia a Saucy Import From Wales  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cerys Matthews' reputation precedes her.
</P>
<P>
   It arrives via dozens of British magazine covers, which have
pictured the rock band Catatonia's lead singer decked out in a
white bustier, a skintight rubber suit slit nearly to her belly
button, or posed like a tiger about to pounce.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this 29-year-old Welshwoman enjoys life. She was in a
London cab when she heard Catatonia had its first No. 1 single, and
she ordered the driver to stop, hopped into the street with a whoop
and began guzzling champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually no one in the United States knows her music yet, but
the American magazine Details was smitten enough to put Matthews on
its April cover. It didn't hurt that the black-rooted blonde wears
a midriff-baring tank top, white pants partially unzippered and a
sultry stare.
</P>
<P>
   Details calls her ''the next Courtney Love -- only better.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a stretch, but one thing is certain: Cerys (pronounced
CARE-iss) Matthews is no Spice Girl. So it seemed somewhat odd to
find her in a conference room, dressed demurely in a black and gray
pantsuit that made her look like thousands of other Manhattan
office workers.
</P>
<P>
   Is she really the wild woman that the British press have made
her out to be?
</P>
<P>
   ''That gets dangerous, doesn't it?'' Matthews replied.
</P>
<P>
   Catatonia's drummer, Aled Richards, won't let Matthews off so
easily. ''It's something you have to live up to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can never live up to it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth a try; rock 'n' roll can use more colorful
personalities. Atlantic Records is giving Catatonia a big push in
America, hoping to buck a trend. Despite a rock renaissance in
Great Britain, few of its new bands have made a dent across the
ocean, except for the occasional Oasis single.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews' thick Welsh accent lends a certain drama to
Catatonia's catchy pop-rock nuggets. Their first hit, ''Mulder &AMP;
Scully,'' used the two characters from ''The X-Files'' as a hook
for her urgent lamentation of lost love.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic has released Catatonia's third album, ''Equally Cursed
and Blessed,'' with two earlier British hits added on, ''Mulder &AMP;
Scully'' and ''Road Rage.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, Catatonia played the bars of its native
Cardiff, hardly a musical hotbed. By writing and singing songs
mostly in English, instead of Welsh, they at least showed more
ambition than many of their contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews was busking on the streets in 1992 when she was
approached by guitarist Mark Roberts, who already had a band
together.
</P>
<P>
   ''He came over and started chatting because he liked my voice,''
she said. ''He said he didn't want to be a singer anymore. He
wanted to get a thick, blond bimbo to stand up for the band and do
the work.''
</P>
<P>
   ''And you obliged,'' Richards added drolly.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and Matthews commenced a four-year relationship that has
since ended, but it didn't end the band. Catatonia's dry years,
spent scuffling for small gigs, gave the quintet the perspective to
deal with its seemingly sudden burst of success.
</P>
<P>
   Being on magazine covers ''is actually quite uncomfortable,''
Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You go into a shop and you're faced with your own face, so you
walk out again,'' she said. ''I used to read the articles, but I
think it's better not to read them anymore, because they can go
around and do funny things in your mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''Imagine being somebody like Christina Aguilera, who's really
young, and being all over the world,'' she said. ''I'm at least a
little older and have been around for awhile. It's a very strange
concept, celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Their experience in the United States has been quite the
opposite. Catatonia was briefly placed on the bill for the
H.O.R.D.E. tour a couple of summers ago, playing with bands like
Blues Traveler and Bare Naked Ladies.
</P>
<P>
   In a musical setting that worshipped the 10-minute guitar solo,
Catatonia played three-minute pop songs. Matthews wore stiletto
heels, jewelry and glittery clothes -- and stared out at a sea of
khaki shorts and t-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Catatonia is willing to go through those experiences, and even
laugh in retrospect. Not every British act feels the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once you get to a certain stage, you have to do America,'' she
said. ''And we think that America is no different than anywhere
else -- if you can go somewhere and be accepted for who you are and
people smile at your songs, all the old cliches.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bands say that, but they're not prepared to do the work. They
say, 'I'm not going to do this. I'm not going to play to 20 people
in the Midwest. I want to go home and play arenas.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of Catatonia's new songs, ''Londinium,'' pokes fun at
Britain's capital. ''London never sleeps, it just sucks,'' Matthews
sings, pausing wearily for dramatic effect before starting again.
''...The life out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   The band still calls Wales home. Richards was taken aback one
day recently when his daughter told him that they were singing one
of Catatonia's songs, ''International Velvet,'' in her school.
</P>
<P>
   The song's one-line chorus -- ''every day when I wake up, I thank
the Lord I'm Welsh'' -- is a counterpoint to verses that outline
some of the country's weaknesses. The irony is lost on most
listeners, since the verses are in Welsh. Richards' daughter and
her classmates are singing it to brush up on their language skills.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews reacts to that news with a mixture of horror and pride.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the death of us,'' she said, ''if we've become school
fodder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1205 </TRAILER>
