<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corporate War Deprived ABC Viewers  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- By the time it ended, few could recall exactly
why it began.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone knew this: It had gone on too long and exacted a
dreadful human toll. Three and a half million cable subscribers
went 39 hours (give or take) without ABC.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City and other trouble zones, many viewers still
remember the day their hardship began -- May 1, 2000. They turned on
their TVs expecting to find Regis Philbin and Susan Lucci, Diane
Sawyer and Bill Maher. But where ABC had burned brightly only a day
before, without warning, darkness had descended.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly darkness. For those millions of bereft
subscribers to Time Warner Cable, the channel on their tuner box
that had once brimmed with ABC fare now glowed a chilly blue.
Inscribed on the screen were these bitter words: ''Disney has taken
ABC away from you.'' Nothing could be heard but a withering
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers wondered if this blackout (blueout?) was an April
Fool's Day trick a month late. (It wouldn't have been the first
time the cable company missed a date.)
</P>
<P>
   Others mistook the blue screen for new specialty programming:
The Disney-Has-Taken-ABC-Away-From-You Channel. They watched it.
They liked it. Here, years after ''Seinfeld,'' was really a show
about nothing!
</P>
<P>
   Then the awful truth sank in. Some terrible dispute was raging
between the cable company's parent, Time Warner, and the Walt
Disney Co., owner of ABC. It had something to do with Disney
wanting more money to let Time Warner Cable carry Disney-owned
channels, and with Time Warner Cable not wanting to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Caught helpless in between were those 3.5 million customers in
New York, Houston, Raleigh-Durham, N.C., Philadelphia, northwest
Ohio and Racine, Wisc., as well as Los Angeles and Fresno, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   They were ordinary people from coast to coast, now united by
mutual adversity. And facing sacrifices they would someday tell
their grandchildren about.
</P>
<P>
   By then, this sort of corporate clash will likely seem quaint,
even barbarian. By then, the merger of TimeWarnerAOLDisneyViacom
with SonyNewsCorpBertelsmannGE will mean just one global
conglomerate (along with the two Microsofts). There'll be no one
left to fight with.
</P>
<P>
   But back on May 1, 2000, the Old Capitalism was still in play.
Under that brutal paradigm, competing companies sometimes butted
heads. And customers got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, subscribers were heartened by an added on-screen
message in which Time Warner Cable declared, ''We're not going to
let Disney force our customers to 'walk the plank.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's a blessing, they told themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Time Warner Cable helpfully proposed that they buy a
TV antenna to receive ABC over the air. Of course, this was the
sort of thing viewers used to do without being told. And without
subscribing to cable. And without losing their picture in the
fourth quarter of a championship sportscast. And without taking a
day off from work to wait for a cable repairman who never showed
up.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, they were grateful for the tip.
</P>
<P>
   But in a New York newspaper advertisement, Disney-owned WABC-TV
countered that Time Warner Cable wasn't really the subscriber's
best friend: ''They violated your trust as a viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   It got worse.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about extorting money from cable customers,'' a Time
Warner spokesman stormed, while a Disney exec charged that ''some
deranged individual has deprived all of these people of ABC.''
</P>
<P>
   And the hours of deprivation dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   ''How did 'Arabian Nights' come out?'' viewers wondered. ''Who
won on 'Who Wants to be a Millionaire'? What's Ted Koppel up to? Is
it true he's turning 'Nightline' over to Leonardo DiCaprio?''
</P>
<P>
   Before too long, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani surely would
have taken steps to calm the situation. Drawing inspiration from a
predecessor who read comic strips on the radio during a 1940s
newspaper strike, Hizzoner might have recited scenes from ''NYPD
Blue'' on subway platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Cassettes of ''The Drew Carey Show'' and ''Dharma &AMP; Greg'' could
have been air-dropped to viewers in the worst-affected areas.
</P>
<P>
   Support groups would have sprung up on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But, happily, it didn't come to that. Tuesday afternoon, the
warring parties agreed to lift the blackout, extend the deadline
and negotiate a truce.
</P>
<P>
   ABC was back as viewers, grateful but still shaken, began
putting their lives back together. Once, things had been normal. It
seemed like only yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   '20/20': With Texas governor George W. Bush all but anointed as
the Republican nominee for president, ABC News' Barbara Walters
this week talked with him and his wife, Laura. Taking place at the
Bush ranch in Crawford, Texas, Walters' interview touches on both
personal and political matters. It airs on ''20/20 Friday'' at 10
p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ''at''
ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
