<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Producers Want Apology From Stewart  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Shubert Organization is demanding that actor
Patrick Stewart apologize for complaining at curtain calls that
producers weren't doing enough to promote the Broadway play ''The
Ride Down Mt. Morgan.'' They've also complained to the Actors
Equity union.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint filed with the union alleges unprofessional
conduct by the star of the Arthur Miller play.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought the matter should be brought to Equity's
attention,'' said Gerald Schoenfeld, chairman of the powerful
Shubert Organization, one of the producers. Schoenfeld also wants a
written apology from Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The union had no comment, spokeswoman Helaine Feldman said
Wednesday. She said she did not know if the union had ever
disciplined an actor for curtain call comments.
</P>
<P>
   The show's producers and its chief publicist, Michael Hartman,
said about $1 million had been spent on advertising for ''Mt.
Morgan,'' more than for two comparable plays last season, ''The
Blue Room,'' starring Nicole Kidman, and ''Amy's View,'' featuring
Dame Judi Dench.
</P>
<P>
   More publicity would be forthcoming, Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, best known for television's ''Star Trek: The Next
Generation,'' made his complaints during curtain calls for
Saturday's matinee and evening performances.
</P>
<P>
   Other cast members, through a secret ballot, elected not to join
Stewart on stage during the speeches, The New York Times reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and producers will be invited to speak before an Equity
hearing committee, the Times said. No date was set.
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old actor could be expelled from the union,
reprimanded or fined if the union sides with the producers.
Expulsions are rare and do not bar actors from Broadway
productions.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mt. Morgan,'' which opened three weeks ago and is scheduled to
run through July 23, has enjoyed positive reviews and has done well
at the box office. Producers, however, would not say how much
revenue the show is taking in or if it is making money.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart accepted a lower salary than usual for ''Mt. Morgan''
and is to receive a cut of the play's profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mt. Morgan'' is the story of a bigamist whose wives learn of
each other when they visit him in the hospital after he's injured
in a car crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
