<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 172; Nasdaq Off 106  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks staged a broad retreat today as
interest-rate worries weighed on the market and investors punished
companies that warned of slowing earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 172.50 to 10,558.62.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also falling. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 27.17 to 1,419.12, and the Nasdaq
composite index was down 106.83 to 3,678.62.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell for a second session as interest-rate fears kept
many buyers on the sidelines. The Federal Reserve is widely
expected to raise interest rates on May 16 in its continuing bid to
slow the economy enough to keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists are expecting a quarter-percentage point
increase, but worries that the Fed could boost rates by as much a
half-percentage point are rattling the market.
</P>
<P>
   The next key piece of economic data will hit the market on
Friday, when the Labor Department releases employment data for the
month of April. Until then, analysts say, investors will continue
to move cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is looking for some comfort in the numbers to come
on Friday,'' said Rao Chalasani, chief investment strategist at
First Union Securities in Chicago. ''Especially for investors in
the Old Economy stocks, interest-rate worries are there.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, AT&AMP;T fell 1 15/16 to 40, hurting the blue-chip Dow.
PaineWebber and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette downgraded the stock a
day after company officials warned that full-year operating profits
will likely come in below previous estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Also, software maker Novell fell after warning Wall Street that
it will miss financial targets in its fiscal second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods rose 10 11/16 to 61\. Late Tuesday, the maker of
Skippy peanut butter and Hellmann's mayonnaise rejected an $18.4
billion takeover offer from multinational consumer products
conglomerate Unilever.
</P>
<P>
   The offer valued Bestfoods at 66 per share, a 31 percent premium
to Bestfoods' closing price Tuesday. But Bestfoods said the offer
was not financially adequate and not in the best interest of
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever fell 2 3/16 to 22 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Several other food companies rose today as investors anticipated
that any or all could come into play. Heinz rose 3 5/16 to 37\ and
Campbell Soup rose 2 3/16 to 28 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Retail stocks were mostly lower after Goldman Sachs removed
several prominent retailers from its list of recommended stocks.
Kohl's fell 4{ to 47 5/16, Target fell 4 15/16 to 63 15/16 and
Costco fell 3 5/16 to 51 7/16. All were downgraded from
''recommended'' to ''market outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman also lowered its rating on Dow component Wal-Mart,
sending its shares down 4 5/16 to 53 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 450.38 million shares
at midday, slightly ahead of Tuesday's pace. On the Nasdaq,
decliners led by a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 11.35 to 494.00.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
