<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Bodies OK Greece Euro Bid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Central Bank and the
European Commission have each endorsed Greece's bid to join the
European Union's single currency and replace its drachma with the
euro.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Solbes, EU commissioner for economic and monetary affairs,
told the European Parliament's economic committee on Wednesday that
Greece met all necessary requirements on inflation, deficit and
debt for entry into the euro-zone.
</P>
<P>
   Greece is now expected to join the single currency in January
2001, pending final approval by EU leaders in June.
</P>
<P>
   Solbes rejected criticism that Greek membership would further
drag down the euro-zone's single currency which was traded at a new
low of under 89 cents Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said Greece's bid was based on the same economic criteria as
the other 11 members, which began using the currency in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that this will bring any difficulty to the
euro,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Solbes warned however that Greece still faces the risk of high
inflation due to high interest rates and its exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be necessary for the Greek government to maintain its
stability-oriented strategy, in particular, a tight budgetary
policy stance and a continuation of wage moderation.'' Solbes said.
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank also gave its approval to Greek
membership in the euro-zone on WEdnesday, but echoed concerns that
Greece must keep its inflation in check and said that it must
reduce debt.
</P>
<P>
   Yiannos Papantoniou, Greek finance minister, welcomed the
endorsement and said the reports were ''the justification, the
reward of an economic policy which was exercised with insistence,
with stability, with punctuality for six years.''
</P>
<P>
   The country was kept out of the euro's 1999 launch because it
failed to meet the requirements for entry at that stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
