<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Percent of Rwandans Have HIV  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- AIDS is running rampant in Rwanda and its
victims are swamping the country's hospitals and overtaxing its
medical workers, Rwanda's health minister said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 500,000 Rwandans, or 6 percent of the population, are
infected with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, Health Minister
Ezechias Rwabuhihi said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Women from 25-29 years of age are most at risk and 21.5 percent
of them have contracted HIV, compared to 13.9 percent of men in the
same category, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are facing a silent and devastating epidemic which
threatens national security,'' Rwabuhihi told a U.N. conference in
the capital Kigali. ''Our hospitals are overwhelmed, the staff is
overwhelmed, some services of the internal medicine are
overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of patients in Kigali's main hospital were
suffering from AIDS-related illnesses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of 8.2 million people, Rwanda is one of
Africa's most densely populated countries. It is also one of its
poorest.
</P>
<P>
   Large migrations related to the 1994 genocide of more than
500,000 people are thought to have contributed to the high
HIV-infection rate. Rape and promiscuity spread the disease in the
refugee camps, while many widows of the genocide have been forced
to turn to prostitution to survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
