<HEADLINE> Europe: Euro Falls Below 89 Cents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The euro stumbled to yet another low against the
dollar in European trading today, not only falling below 90 cents
for the first time, but also slipping below 89 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless the European Central Bank performs a miraculous rescue
mission, anyone on board the euro may as well be on board the
Titanic,'' said Neil Parker, senior European economist at Royal
Bank of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar was mostly higher against major currencies. Gold
prices rose.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, the single currency of 11 European nations, fell as
low as 88.90 cents in early European trading, down from 90.66 cents
late Tuesday. It recovered some lost ground to reach 88.97 cents in
late trading in Europe. Later, in midday trading in New York, the
euro was worth 89.36 cents. The previous low was 90.30 cents,
reached during trading Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates in Europe today, compared with late Tuesday,
included 109.11 Japanese yen, up from 108.63; 1.7348 Swiss francs,
up from 1.7181; and 1.4914 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4855.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound was quoted at $1.5612, up from $1.5582.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 109.17 yen, and
the pound was worth $1.5575.
</P>
<P>
   Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth 2.1971 German marks, up
from 2.1557; 7.3695 French francs, up from 7.2322; 2.4758 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.4297; and 2,175.34 Italian lire, up from
2,134.81.
</P>
<P>
   Gold closed in London at $276.70 bid per troy ounce, up from
$275.20 on Tuesday. In Zurich the bid price was $275.50, up from
$274.65. Gold rose $2.40 in Hong Kong to $277.55.
</P>
<P>
   Silver closed in London at $5.01 bid per troy ounce, down from
$5.02.
</P>
</TEXT>
