<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War Heroes Honored With New Stamp  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon on Wednesday unveiled
commemorative postage stamps honoring four American war heroes,
including Sgt. Audie Murphy, the most decorated World War II
soldier and later a movie actor.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of each of the four attended a ceremony in the
Pentagon courtyard hosted by Army Secretary Louis Caldera.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-cent stamps feature black-and-white photographs of the
four men.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, of Kingston, Texas, was awarded the Medal of Honor for
saving the troops in his company by breaking up a German attack in
France in 1944. He later starred in movies, including ''To Hell and
Back.'' Murphy died in a plane crash in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Also honored was Sgt. Alvin York, of Pall Mall, Tenn., who was
awarded the Medal of Honor for heroism in World War I. As a member
of the 82nd Division, York captured 132 German soldiers in the
battle of the Argonne forest in France on Oct. 8, 1918. In his
diary, York summed up the fight in which he killed more than 20
Germans: ''So we had a hard battle for a little while.'' York died
in Nashville, Tenn., in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the stamps is in memory of General of the Army Omar
Bradley, of Clark, Mo., who commanded a million-man U.S. Army group
in Europe and later served as Army chief of staff and as the first
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. He is the last U.S. general
to hold the five-star rank. He died in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth hero is Gen. John Hines, who was from a distinguished
military family. He rose from the rank of major to major general
during a 16-month period in World War I. He was awarded the
Distinguished Service Cross and the Distinguished Service Medal for
bravery and leadership in combat. He went on to become Army chief
of staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
