<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Approve Alcoa-Reynolds Merger  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department approved Alcoa Inc.'s
$5 billion acquisition of Reynolds Metals Co. on Wednesday after
requiring Alcoa to sell a Reynolds refinery in Texas and Reynolds'
controlling interest in a state-of-the-art Australian refinery.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust concerns raised by the merger of the nation's two
largest aluminum producers would be resolved by divestiture of the
two refineries, which produce alumina, a powder used in aluminum
and other products, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   Together with divestitures required earlier Wednesday by the
European Commission, the agreements require Alcoa to sell all of
the alumina capacity owned by Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   With the European and U.S. antitrust approvals in hand, the
companies announced Wednesday that they had completed their merger,
which Reynolds shareholders had approved Feb. 11. Each outstanding
Reynolds share will be converted into 1.06 shares of Alcoa common
stock.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will rapidly integrate Reynolds and thereby create
additional value for Alcoa and Reynolds customers and other
stakeholders,'' Alcoa President and chief executive officer Alain
Belda said. ''Proceeds from the sale of the divested assets will
contribute significantly to investment in further profitable growth
for Alcoa.''
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in Pittsburgh, Alcoa is the largest aluminum
company in the world with 1999 revenues of more than $16 billion.
Reynolds, based in Richmond, Va., is the second largest U.S.
aluminum company and third largest in the world, with 1999 revenues
of more than $4.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies mine and refine bauxite into smelter grade and
chemical grade alumina and smelt alumina into aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   ''The aluminum industry produces a wide variety of important
commercial and consumer products and is dependent upon ample
supplies of alumina at competitive prices,'' said Joel I. Klein,
assistant attorney general in charge of the department's antitrust
division. ''These divestitures will protect against a loss of
competition for the aluminum producers, businesses that use
aluminum to manufacture products and American consumers who buy
these products.''
</P>
<P>
   Alumina refineries produce two grade of alumina from bauxite
ore. Smelter grade alumina is a critical input in the production of
aluminum metal, used for such products as aluminum foil, beverage
cans, building materials and aircraft skin. Chemical grade alumina
is used to produce numerous industrial and consumer products,
including detergents, countertops and flame retardants.
</P>
<P>
   The government filed a civil lawsuit in U.S. District Court here
to block the original deal and simultaneously filed the agreement
that would resolve that lawsuit. The agreement must be approved by
the court.
</P>
<P>
   The suit said that the original acquisition would have
substantially reduced competition in refining and sale of both
grades of alumina, resulting in higher prices to aluminum
manufacturers and their customers, including consumers who buy
products containing alumina.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Alcoa will sell Reynolds' controlling
interest in high-volume Worsley refinery, located in Western
Australia's Darling Range. Worsley is one of the world's lowest
cost alumina refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also calls for the sale of Reynolds' Corpus
Christi, Texas, refinery, which produces both grades of alumina.
</P>
<P>
   Without the divestitures, the government said, Alcoa would have
owned or controlled about 38 percent of the world market for
smelter grade alumina and 59 percent of the North American market
for chemical grade alumina.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier today, the European Commission announced that it also
would require divestitures of the companies, including the sale of
Reynolds' refining operation in Stade, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department consulted extensively with antitrust
authorities at the European Commission during their respective
investigations of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an excellent example of how international cooperation
between antitrust agencies can lead to harmonious resolutions that
benefit consumers around the world,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies announced that their agreements with antitrust
enforcers also will require the sale of a 25 percent interest in
Reynolds' Longview, Wash., aluminum smelter.
</P>
<P>
   They said the revised merger would give Alcoa the Reynolds'
brand name, its packaging and consumer products businesses,
smelting operations with a capacity of one million metric tons,
manufacturing operations serving the construction and
transportation markets, bauxite reserves in Brazil, Guyana and
Guinea and two petroleum coke plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
