<HEADLINE> 3rd Iranian Jew Confesses to Spying  </HEADLINE>
By AFSHIN VALINEJAD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIRAZ, Iran (AP) -- Two more Iranian Jews confessed today to
spying for Israel, even as defense lawyers cast doubt on an earlier
confession by one of the 13 defendants in the espionage trial.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers also criticized the Islamic revolutionary court
in which the judge acts as prosecutor and jury -- echoing Western
concerns whether the judiciary, controlled by Iran's fundamentalist
Muslim faction, will dispense justice.
</P>
<P>
   The trial takes place amid a power struggle between reformers
who are trying to improve ties with the outside world and Islamic
hard-liners who want to scuttle those hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, one of the accused, Shahrokh Paknahad, a religion
teacher, told reporters outside the court that he had confessed to
organizing a spy network for Israel in Isfahan, 200 miles northwest
of Shiraz. A stalwart of the small Jewish community in Shiraz, he
said he had used his position to recruit more agents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I completed four successful missions for them (Israel),''
Paknahad, 30, said.
</P>
<P>
   Another defendant, Ramin Nematizadeh, also told the court today
that he had passed to Israel defense information he gathered during
his stint of military service mandatory for all Iranians, his
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Esmail Naseri, told reporters that he would argue to
the court that no classified information had changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has denied that the 13 Jews were spying for the Jewish
state, which Iran fiercely opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The accusations against them are cruel lies, once again we are
in a situation where Jews are imprisoned just because they are
Jews,'' Israel's Diaspora Affairs Minister Michael Melchior said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the defendants could be sentenced to death, the
maximum penalty for passing secret information that damages
national security. Two Jews were hanged three years ago on similar
charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Provincial judiciary chief Hossein Ali Amiri said that the
young age of the defendants would be taken account when verdicts
are handed down. ''All I can predict is that their sentences may
not be execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the first defendant to confess, Dani Tefilin, told
journalists outside the court today that he had not been under
psychological pressure and he repeated his admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am well in every respect,'' he said, appearing calm before
his lawyer made his final arguments today. Tefilin was unshackled,
wearing a gray prison suit.
</P>
<P>
   Tefilin, the first defendant to be arrested more than a year
ago, made his admissions Monday on state television -- also
controlled by the hard-line Islamic clergy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been spying for Israel. In my trip to Israel in 1994, I
was trained for my activity in Iran,'' he said. He later told state
radio he spied for money.
</P>
<P>
   Naseri said Tefilin refused to retract his confession when Judge
Sadeq Nourani gave him the opportunity. Nourani told Tefilin he
could change his statement ''if you are influenced by any matter,
(or) if someone has made promises to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Iran's Islamic laws, a confession by a person who has
spent a year or more in prison has no value, Naseri, who represents
three of the 13 and is a spokesman for the defense team, said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The accused may have been sick and tired of his condition and
prison and may be willing to say anything to get his ordeal over
with one way or another,'' Naseri said.
</P>
<P>
   Shirzad Rahmani, Tefilin's lawyer, said he had ''absolutely no
access to classified information and he lacked the necessary
intelligence to try to gather such information.''
</P>
<P>
   About 80,000 Jews lived in Iran before the 1979 Islamic
revolution; 25,000 remain today. Jews are generally allowed to
practice their religion freely, but cannot travel to or have any
contact with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 defendants are being tried without a jury in a
revolutionary court where the judge is also the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Naseri said the whole trial, which began last month and was
expected to last a few more weeks, was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The judge accuses the defendants, then proceeds to defend the
accusation. On top of that, he also wants to pass sentence. How can
this be?'' Naseri said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The judge makes the accusation of espionage, but when we ask
for evidence he remains silent,'' Naseri said, adding the
confessions seen by the lawyers were very general.
</P>
<P>
   Several countries, the United Nations and human rights groups
have either condemned the arrests or called on Iran to ensure that
the proceedings are fair.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, President Mohammad Khatami, the leader of reformists
who seek better ties with the West, promised a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami's faction is under assault by the hard-liners, who have
used the judiciary to close down 16 pro-democracy newspapers
recently and arrest or question about a dozen reformist journalists
and activists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
