<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRS To Test Reforms for Next 2 Yrs.  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The next two years will be critical in
determining whether reforms intended by Congress to make the
Internal Revenue Service more taxpayer-friendly and modern become
permanent, the IRS chief said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think we know what needs to be done,'' IRS Commissioner
Charles Rossotti told a House-Senate panel that reviews the agency
each year. ''We are at a crossroads where we will show either this
will happen or it won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, who is about halfway through his five-year term, said
the IRS has implemented most of the provisions of the 1998 reform
law, including massive training programs for its thousands of
employees. Examples of the many changes include additional steps in
all IRS seizure cases to satisfy unpaid taxes, new due process
rights for taxpayers and new relief for innocent spouses of
taxpayers who run afoul of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 18 to 24 months, Rossotti said the IRS must make
the new system work better and ensure employees' attitudes undergo
a permanent change. A key to success, he added, would be approval
by Congress of a $769 million budget increase for fiscal 2001 to
help the IRS improve service and slow a steep decline in audits and
other enforcement actions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our first priority was implementing the taxpayer rights. This
did stretch our capacity to the limit,'' Rossotti said. ''We have
several years of work ahead to make these provisions work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, agreed that Congress ''must
provide appropriate funding'' but added that the IRS must do a
better job of managing its existing resources and be held
accountable for not straying from the 1998 reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''Funding is part of the answer, but with most things, just
throwing money at a problem won't fix it,'' Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers said the IRS must not allow the drop in audits
and enforcement actions to become permanent, lest honest taxpayers
begin to question the fairness of the system and cheating becomes
more rampant.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the IRS is in the throes of this enormous restructuring,
it must continue to collect taxes,'' Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   IRS: http://www.irs.gov
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
