<HEADLINE> Town leaders head to camp to learn environmental lessons  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   With development pressures creeping into even the most rural
corners of Connecticut, environmental leaders are holding a
first-of-its-kind camp to help volunteer town officials do their
jobs better.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty officials from small eastern Connecticut towns are
gathering at a YMCA camp in Woodstock this weekend to learn the
basics of soil, water and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   They'll also make contacts and learn the preferred ways to
develop housing and business while minimizing the impact on the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Members of inland wetland commissions, planning and zoning
boards, economic development boards and conservation commissions
are scheduled to attend the free, three-day camp.
</P>
<P>
   Since most people on these boards are volunteers, they may not
have the experience necessary to make the best decisions about land
use, said Steve Broderick, a forester with the University of
Connecticut Cooperative Extension System who is helping teach the
weekend camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our hope is to raise the background level of people who are
making such key decisions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Lanzit, a first selectman from Chaplin who is attending
the camp, hopes to learn how small-town leaders can work together
to keep the area's character intact.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've really got a great area here. My goal is to work in
partnership with some of the surrounding towns to try and preserve,
maintain, promote. I think we can have it all, but we need to work
together,'' Lanzit said.
</P>
<P>
   The towns participating are part of the Quinebaug-Shetucket
Heritage Corridor -- a 35-town region formed around the Quinebaug
and Shetucket riversheds north of Norwich, to the Rhode Island
border and into Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're the last large tract of undeveloped land in coastal
sprawl extending from Boston to Washington,'' said Charlene Cutler,
executive director of the corridor group.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the most remote and rural parts of Connecticut, but
it is seeing more development pressures as suburbs expand from
Providence, R.I., Worcester, Mass., Hartford and the casino areas,
Broderick said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As an area grows and changes with time, we're not just talking
about conservation and open space protection. We're also talking
about the need for economic growth,'' he said. ''The issue is, how
do we balance those things, build what needs to be built and
protect what needs to be protected?''
</P>
<P>
   Cutler said the program fits with the corridor's federal mandate
to preserve the natural, historic and cultural resources of the
area. Congress has established 18 such corridors around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The group hopes to integrate preservation goals with local
economic development needs to revitalize communities, Cutler said.
People who attend the camp are urged to share their knowledge with
other town officials.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick said he hopes to make the camp an annual event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 1503 </TRAILER>
