<HEADLINE> Transportation Safety Needs Listed  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- You've heard it before and you'll hear it
again but experts say it's still the most important safety message
out there: Buckle up!
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to lose 40,000 of our citizens on our nation's
highways'' annually, National Transportation Safety Board Chairman
Jim Hall said Wednesday. ''We as a nation need to change our
culture to stop this carnage and we can do it most effectively with
seat-belt laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall's comments came as the board held its annual review of what
it considers the most important transportation safety needs in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Among those are the so-called primary seat-belt laws which allow
police to stop drivers and issue tickets for failure to wear a seat
belt. Many states require belts, but list it as a secondary law
under which police can't act unless they have already stopped the
car for some other reason.
</P>
<P>
   As if to emphasize Hall's point, the Journal of the American
Medical Association published a report on drunken-driving accidents
showing that most children younger than 15 who were killed in such
crashes were riding unrestrained.
</P>
<P>
   The board's wish list grew a bit, expanding from 10 last year to
11 now, with the a call for improvements in commercial truck and
bus safety.
</P>
<P>
   The agency added proposals for easier opening emergency exits on
buses, performance standards for buses, on-board recording devices,
tighter school bus crashworthiness standards and new hours of
operation limits for bus and truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Another item that the board has long pursued is installing a
system to keep railroad trains from colliding.
</P>
<P>
   Called ''positive train separation,'' such electronic systems
are used in some subways and on European railroads, officials said.
They have been pressing both the nation's railroads and federal
regulators to develop similar systems.
</P>
<P>
   With positive train separation, electronic systems can take
control and stop one or both locomotives if they approach each
other too closely. ''The system is a backup to the human being so
that a single mistake won't lead to disaster,'' explained Robert
Lauby, director of the board's office of railroad safety.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was created in 1967, the safety board, which does not
have to consider the cost of what it recommends, has sent 11,485
proposals to government regulators and transportation industries.
Hall said nearly 83 percent have been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues on their safety want list -- in no particular order
-- included:
</P>
<P>
   --Reducing the presence of explosive mixtures in aircraft fuel
tanks, such as by cooling the tanks and filling empty areas with
inert gas like nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   --Improving ways of eliminating ice buildup on airplanes on the
ground and in flight.
</P>
<P>
   --Increasing recreational boating safety, such as with boat
operator training, requiring life preservers and outlawing drinking
and boating.
</P>
<P>
   --Preventing pipeline accidents, including requirements to check
with utilities before digging.
</P>
<P>
   --Reducing the number of incidents of aircraft interfering with
one another on runways.
</P>
<P>
   --Reducing human fatigue in operating all types of
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   --Installing automatic recording systems -- like those black boxes
used in airliners -- on other transportation modes such as trucks
and locomotives.
</P>
<P>
   --Increasing child and youth safety in traveling with booster
seats, graduated driving license systems for young drivers, limits
on youths driving at night and zero tolerance of alcohol use by
youths.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board: http://www.ntsb.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1503 </TRAILER>
