<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton unveils first television ad; blasts Buchanan again  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT EDWARD, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton unveiled the
first television advertisement of her Senate campaign on Wednesday,
telling New Yorkers she is ''more than a first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, during a stop in the Washington County village of Fort
Edward, also defended herself against an attack from Pat Buchanan
that she wasn't acting much like a lady.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, during a forum for Senate candidates in Buffalo
hosted by the New York wing of the Reform Party, Clinton told party
members that she would not run on a ticket headed by Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the New York Daily News published
Wednesday, Buchanan fired back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that kind of inflammatory language comports with
being a first lady,'' he said. ''I think the first lady ought to
always try to be a lady even if she falls short. She certainly did
in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Buchanan's comments, Clinton said the conservative
commentator ''has a history of making prejudiced, anti-Semitic and
intolerant comments and that's why I said last Saturday that I
wouldn't run on a ballot with him. I took the position that anyone
who wants to represent all of New York and all New Yorkers should
be taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Senate rival, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
who also attended Saturday's Independence Party forum, had also
been critical of Buchanan, but has stopped short of saying he
wouldn't share the ballot with him.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's comment was the closest she came to criticizing
Giuliani. Since the mayor announced last week that he was battling
prostate cancer, Clinton has virtually eliminated criticism of him
during her appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the first TV ad her campaign has paid for, Clinton
doesn't mention Giuliani, or her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ''It never crossed my mind,'' she said when asked about not
having the president in her ad. She then laughed. ''I'm using this
opportunity to introduce myself and what I've done for 30 years to
the majority of New Yorkers. There's so much that I want to
communicate to people ... that the real challenge was to put into
30 seconds everything that I wanted to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been running TV ads off and on for several months
and the state Democratic Committee ran pro-Clinton TV ads late last
year. Aides said Clinton's biographical ad would begin running
immediately all across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Both the first lady and her campaign aides have made it clear
that she believes she must establish her identity independent of
the president if she is to win the New York Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, she said Wednesday that it is still uncertain if
he will attend New York's Democratic state convention on May 16
when she will be nominated. Nonetheless, she said ''I hope he'll be
able to campaign with me.''
</P>
<P>
   And, taking note of a humorous video President Clinton used at
the White House Correspondents Association dinner on Saturday night
in which he is shown chasing after her limousine with a bag lunch
he had made for her, she added: ''To put your mind at rest, he gave
me my lunch today as I was leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady did reiterate her disagreement with her husband's
administration over Vieques Island. She said she wanted a quick
referendum by local residents on the future of the island off
Puerto Rico. The administration has said a referendum should be
held by 2002. She also called for the Pentagon to continue
negotiations with protesters on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani today ridiculed the notion of a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know, maybe we should not have a president and we
should have polls and referendums to decide things,'' Giuliani
said. ''And what we can do is, we can save the money for a
president, and we can hold a poll and then the automatic whatever
will execute whatever the poll says.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's stop at a tourist center in Fort Edward, where she was
greeted by more than 100 local residents, marked the 59th of New
York's 62 counties that she has visited. Clinton plans to complete
the full tour of the state on Thursday when she makes campaign
stops in Clinton County near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has traveled much less frequently across the
state, planned to be in Rochester on Wednesday night for a college
forum hosted by MSNBC's ''Hardball'' show hosted by Chris Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's visit took her to heavy Republican country in
both Fort Edward and Indian Lake in Hamilton County, the heart of
the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   But she picked up some Republican support in Fort Edward.
Leonard and Clara Bradway said that while they were Republicans,
they planned to vote for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she's a very great lady,'' Clara said. ''She's endured
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans were not swayed.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a threat to New York state,'' said Dwayne Swanson a
machine operator from South Glen Falls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
