<DOCNO> APW20000503.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jets Bomb Iraqi Air Defenses  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHIGNTON (AP) -- U.S. warplanes bombed Iraq's air-defense
system Wednesday in the northern no-fly zone after coming under
fire. ''If there is a threat to our forces, we will respond,'' the
State Department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi forces targeted allied planes with radar and fired
anti-aircraft artillery from a site near Bashiqah, 250 miles north
of Baghdad, according to a statement from the Germany-based U.S.
European Command.
</P>
<P>
   The official Iraqi News Agency said three people were injured
during the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   All allied planes left the area safely, it added.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition aircraft have been enforcing no-fly zones in northern
and southern Iraq since shortly after the 1991 Persian Gulf War to
protect Kurds and Shiites from the forces of Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam says the zones violate Iraq's territorial integrity. He
has been challenging the patrols since December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Boucher, in his first briefing as James P. Rubin's
successor as spokesman, said the State Department works on Iraqi
problems ''every single one of them, every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's a threat to our forces, they're going to respond,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're actively working to prevent Saddam's illegal oil exports
and as well as to make the oil-for-food program work. We're
patrolling the Persian Gulf. We're taking diplomatic action. We're
working with opposition forces every day of the year,'' Boucher
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
