<P>
   Factory Orders Rebound Strongly
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Five interest rate hikes by the Federal
Reserve since June of last year haven't daunted would-be buyers in
the United States. Orders to U.S. factories rose a
bigger-than-expected 2.2 percent in March, led by the largest jump
in demand for electronic equipment in more than two years. The
Commerce Department reported today that factory orders rose to a
seasonally adjusted $383.2 billion after showing no change in
February and declining in January.
</P>
<P>
   Feds Approve Alcoa-Reynolds Merger
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department approved Alcoa Inc.'s
$5 billion acquisition of Reynolds Metals Co. today after requiring
Alcoa to sell a Reynolds refinery in Texas and Reynolds'
controlling interest in a state-of-the-art Australian refinery.
Antitrust concerns raised by the merger of the nation's two largest
aluminum producers would be resolved by divestiture of the two
refineries, which produce alumina, a powder used in aluminum and
other products, the department said. Together with divestitures
required earlier today by the European Commission, the agreements
require Alcoa to sell all of the alumina capacity owned by
Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods Nixes Unilever Bid
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bestfoods' shares surged today after the maker
of Skippy peanut butter and Hellmann's mayonnaise disclosed it had
rejected an $18.4 billion buyout offer from the international
consumer products conglomerate Unilever. Bestfoods said in a
statement late yesterday that its board had unanimously rejected
the $66 a share cash bid from Unilever, the owner of Lipton teas,
Vaseline and Pepsodent toothpaste. The offer represented a 31
percent premium over the Englewood Cliffs, N.J.-based Bestfoods'
closing price yesterday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Founder of Pleasant Co. Retiring
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLETON, Wis. (AP) -- The founder of the Pleasant Company,
which made its name selling American Girl dolls and books, will
retire July 7. Former educator Pleasant Rowland started the
Middleton, Wis.-based company in 1985 with the vision of making
dolls that provided an alternative to Barbie and Cabbage Patch
Kids. Its American Girl line became a worldwide sensation, selling
more than 50 million books and four million dolls mostly through
mail order. In 1998, it opened its first and only retail store in
Chicago, which has become a popular tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Sets Debt Buyback Schedule
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Flush with cash from a booming economy, the
Treasury Department is setting a regular schedule for buying back
portions of the national debt, officials said today. The success of
four buybacks already carried out led it to set a regular schedule
for buying back the debt through July, Treasury officials said.
Buybacks will be held in the third and fourth weeks of each month,
with the next one to occur on May 18. In a buyback operation, the
government offers investors cash to turn in certain securities
before they mature.
</P>
<P>
   Coke, AOL Form Marketing Alliance
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola Co. and America Online Inc. announced a
wide-ranging marketing alliance today, designed to support each
other's brands online and off. Coke said the ''multiyear'' venture
with AOL was its first foray into online marketing. The financial
terms and length of the deal were not disclosed. The Wall Street
Journal reported that Coke will pay AOL $24 million, and each
company will spend $20 million over the next two years to support
the marketing effort, which may be extended to a third year.
Coca-Cola Co.'s stock was up 2{ at 58} in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   EU Bodies OK Greece Euro Bid
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Central Bank and the
European Commission have each endorsed Greece's bid to join the
European Union's single currency and replace its drachma with the
euro. Greece is expected to join the single currency in January
2001, pending final approval by EU leaders in June.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Ends Medication Policy
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Health maintenance organization Kaiser
Permanente has ended a policy that requires psychiatrists to
prescribe depression and anxiety medications for patients they
haven't examined. Kaiser psychiatrists must now rely on their own
examination of patients before writing prescriptions, the HMO
announced yesterday. Kaiser is the nation's largest not-for-profit
HMO, serving 8 million members in 11 states and the District of
Columbia. Almost 6 million of its patients are in California. A
former Kaiser psychiatrist, who said he was fired for not following
the old policy, filed a lawsuit last month that drew national
attention and prompted the state Department of Corporations to
begin investigating the drug practice.
</P>
