<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German 'Green Cards' Criticized  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- An agreement on Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's plans for a U.S.-style ''green card'' system intended
to open borders to foreign high-tech experts came under scrutiny
Wednesday, with economists saying it doesn't go far enough to
entice workers.
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions on who qualifies for work permits are so tight,
economists said, that even Bill Gates would be barred because he is
a college dropout. At the same time, a five-year limit on how long
they can stay in the country could also keep workers from ever
feeling at home in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which could bring in up to 20,000 workers from Eastern
Europe and India, has been praised by German high-tech businesses
who have pushed Schroeder to help them keep pace with U.S.-based
rivals who routinely poach workers from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a step in the right direction,'' said Heidi Sherman,
chief economist with the Munich-based economic institute Ifo. ''But
it's still on an experimental level. We still have to see who will
want to come to Germany and how many will apply. There are a lot of
question marks surrounding this.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative Christian Democrats have loudly opposed the
plan, arguing it would be better to promote education rather than
bring in foreign workers. To make the point, the party's candidate
for governor in North Rhine-Westphalia state has campaigned under
the controversial slogan ''Kinder statt Inder,'' or ''Children
instead of Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   Such attitudes have raised concerns over whether foreign workers
let into Germany under the plan will be able to overcome the
country's lingering reputation for being less-than-welcoming to
foreigners -- despite the fact that more than 7 million already live
here.
</P>
<P>
   Germany also lags behind the United States in incentives such as
stock options, a fringe benefit sought-after technicians have come
to expect. And it has the disadvantage of slapping professionals
with weighty taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people we are trying to attract are not just sitting there
waiting for green cards from Germany,'' said Ulrike Hasbargen, a
senior analyst with Arthur Andersen. ''There are a lot of countries
vying for these experts and just giving green cards is not
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives hammered out the details with
government officials late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which applies only to employees in the
information technology sector, workers can receive a five-year work
permit after they prove they have completed a university degree or
have an annual salary of at least $46,500.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, 10,000 workers will be let in, followed by as many as
10,000 more later. Their family members will also be allowed to
move to Germany. None will be eligible for citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies have urged the government to help ease what
they say is a shortage of 75,000 qualified workers. But many said
Tuesday's deal is too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under this proposal, even Bill Gates would never have been
allowed,'' said Josef Siegers, a board member of the German
Employers Association, referring to the fact that Gates dropped out
of Harvard to found Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats also criticized the plan for opening the
floodgates to demands from other industries which have begun
clamoring for equal access to foreign workers -- particularly in the
health care and manufacturing sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's Cabinet defended the plan, saying information
technology was not like other sectors because its rapid growth has
outstripped the country's ability to fill the demand for workers.
</P>
<P>
   Top chancellery aide Hans-Martin Bury said the Cabinet would
approve the proposal later this month, with approval expected from
parliament's upper house in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   At that pace, officials said workers could begin coming to
Germany as soon as Aug. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1522 </TRAILER>
