<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Risks in Helping Ex-Soviets  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Spending $240 million to steer Russian
biological weapons experts into peacetime research may bolster the
work of still-secretive former Soviet military institutes, a
congressional report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said any risk is far outweighed by
the program's benefits, with U.S.-supported scientists of at least
15 Russian institutes rejecting approaches from other nations to
conduct ''questionable research.''
</P>
<P>
   The report by the General Accounting Office provides no evidence
that Moscow is working on germ weapons, but says it is dangerous to
improve the skills of scientists who have worked on such deadly
pathogens as anthrax, plague and smallpox.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the United States has provided $20 million to fund
alternative pursuits by Soviet-era scientists who worked in
biological weaponry programs.
</P>
<P>
   The administration proposes to spend $220 million over the next
four years expanding the effort to redirect the work of former
Soviet biological weapons institutes, some of which are still
off-limits to foreigners, according to a General Accounting Office
report released Wednesday by the House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We found that expanding the program will pose certain risks to
the United States,'' by sustaining Russia's existing biological
weapons facilities and advancing Russian war scientists' skills for
conducting offensive research, said the report by the GAO,
Congress' investigative arm.
</P>
<P>
   The report said nothing prevents scientists assisted by the U.S.
program designed to lower the risk of weapons proliferation from
engaging in offensive activities at Russian military facilities or
from selling their skills to rogue states or terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, in responding to the report, said there is
no evidence that Moscow is developing germ warfare weapons and
danger of U.S.-assisted Russian scientists helping terrorists or
rogue nations is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   It acknowledged some risks but said they have been reduced to an
acceptable level and ''the benefits far outweigh the remaining
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest anthrax production facility is being
dismantled and Russians are conducting new research that may help
combat some of the world's deadliest diseases, said the State,
Energy and Defense departments in a joint statement accompanying
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, ''Congress must carefully evaluate the risks and
benefits of this program to ensure that it does not have unintended
consequences that could jeopardize the national security,'' said
Rep. Floyd Spence, Armed Services Committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that some officials who ran Moscow's
clandestine biological weapons programs during the Cold War remain
in place.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although Russia has generally allowed the United States access
to its nonmilitary institutes that receive U.S. nonproliferation
assistance, Russia has consistently rebuffed U.S. efforts to
inspect its military institutes currently managed by the Ministry
of Defense,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO's conclusions were based on unclassified documents and
on interviews with officials running the U.S. program, with experts
from nongovernmental organizations and with former and current
Russian scientists. Investigators also visited six former Soviet
nonmilitary biological weapons facilities currently receiving U.S.
assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1522 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rep.: Mother's Day in Jeopardy  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mother's Day in America could be abolished if
the United States ratifies an international treaty on women's
rights, Rep. Christopher Smith contended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement caused a stir at the House International Relations
Committee, where witnesses urged lawmakers to pass the 20-year-old
U.N. Convention on Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination
Against Women.
</P>
<P>
   One fellow committee member challenged Smith's interpretation of
the treaty and another joked about it.
</P>
<P>
   But it was no laughing matter for an anthropologist and women's
rights activist from Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to get up and slap him,'' Zieba Shorish-Shamley said
later. ''But then I wouldn't be able to come here again.''
</P>
<P>
   Shorish-Shamley was one of three women who never got to tell the
committee Wednesday how systematic discrimination in their
homelands has hurt them. No discrimination victims were scheduled
to testify, so three spoke afterward at a news conference scheduled
by Rep. Lynn Woolsey, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Shorish-Shamley said she lost her 56-year-old sister to cancer
because access to health care is denied to women in Afghanistan,
along with education, jobs, or even the right to leave their homes
unaccompanied by a man.
</P>
<P>
   Meme Akoko of Nigeria said her genitals were cut with an
unsterilized razor blade when she was 3 months old, under a tribal
practice aimed at keeping women sexually faithful to their
husbands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been to many doctors and none have been able to undo
what damage the circumcision has cause,'' she said, adding that an
aunt, younger sister and a cousin died because of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''The brave women ... who tell their personal stories know just
how much ratifying CEDAW will mean to women everywhere,'' Woolsey
said.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty, adopted by the U.N. General Assembly in December
1979, requires that women have equal rights to work, pay, benefits
and safe working conditions and prohibits discrimination against
women in political activities. So far, 165 nations have ratified
it.
</P>
<P>
   At the committee hearing, Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., called
it an ''an absolute embarrassment'' that the United States has not
ratified the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the convention promotes abortion, could override
the U.S. Constitution and could force social engineering by
dictating the roles husbands and wives will have in their own
families.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many countries have come under the scrutiny of CEDAW and been
encouraged, admonished, and even compelled to change their laws,''
said Smith, R-N.J., calling the treaty ''controversial and
fundamentally flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Do our constituents ... really want a group of international
bureaucrats telling them that the day set aside to honor our
mothers must be abolished,'' he said. ''I think not!''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., came in for harsh criticism at the
hearing and the press conference. The chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, Helms for years has refused to
schedule hearings or submit the treaty to the full Senate for a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is trying to stonewall crucial protection for women's
rights around the world,'' Woolsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Helms was not immediately available for comment, but said on
International Women's Day March 8: ''This treaty is not about
opportunities for women -- it's about denigrating motherhood and
undermining the family.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Women's Alliance for Peace and Human Rights in Afghanistan
http://www.wapha.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1527 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
