<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish clothier sparks frenzy on Fifth Avenue  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Shopping on ritzy Fifth Avenue never used to
mean standing in line. On the priciest stretch of this famous
street, a bulging wallet has always been more important than a
patient heart.
</P>
<P>
   Until a Swedish invader turned things upside down, drawing
throngs of shoppers with low prices in a neighborhood better known
for high-end names like Tiffany and Versace.
</P>
<P>
   Hennes &AMP; Mauritz, or H&AMP;M, began its American expansion in
midtown Manhattan a month ago, and has quickly become the hottest
Swedish import since the 1970s supergroup Abba.
</P>
<P>
   Frugal, fashionable shoppers mob the three-floor store daily for
$11 stretchy shorts, $35 shimmery purple pants and $17 bikini
swimsuits. Security guards often ask bargain-seekers to wait
outside until the crowd ebbs, and lines frequently twist down the
block and around a corner.
</P>
<P>
   What's all the fuss about?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's cute, trendy clothes for low prices,'' said shopper
Malaika Elcock, 27, of Brooklyn. ''It's more fashion-forward than a
lot of other stores. For basics, I would go to the Gap, but for
trendy stuff I would come here first.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockholm-based H&AMP;M ventured across the Atlantic in March and
now has three U.S. stores -- on Fifth Avenue, in West Nyack, N.Y.,
and Paramus, N.J. -- with at least one more planned for Manhattan
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fashion-conscious, word is traveling fast.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Hoppins, of Los Gatos, Calif., said she heard about the
store from friends at home and decided to visit during a recent
trip to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were just saying, 'You've got to go see it,' so that's
why I'm here,'' she said as she stood on a short line waiting to be
admitted. ''I just came out of the cab and said, 'Oh, my God, you
have to wait on line to get in?' Unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the megastore, hundreds of shoppers, mostly teens and
twenty-somethings, had to squeeze past each other on a recent
afternoon to browse through clothes, outerwear and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Long cash register lines snaked through the showrooms as
customers snatched up the stylishly retro merchandise, including
1970s-esque items like flared brown-and-orange pants and crocheted
purple ponchos.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a phenomenon because the prices are very attractive, and
because the fashions are so different from what has been shown here
before,'' said Walter Loeb, who runs the retail consulting firm
Loeb Associates.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;M -- which now has stores in 14 countries -- says it's thrilled
with the response it's gotten in the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's over what we expected,'' said Christian Bagnoud, a
company spokesman. ''What we tried to do is exactly what we have
done in Europe. We haven't changed anything in the variety, the
garments.''
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;M announced a profit drop just before the Fifth Avenue store
opened, but it was believed to be mainly a result of the expensive
U.S. expansion, not serious financial problems. Stock prices
plunged when CEO Fabian Maansson resigned around the same time, but
they have since regained most of the loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish newcomer's biggest draw is its low prices, but the
chain also keeps its stock varied, selling most styles only briefly
and replacing them quickly with new ones to keep customers
interested.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you find something that you like, you have to buy today,
because tomorrow it might be that you can't find it anymore,''
Bagnoud said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers seem to like the high-turnover approach, which
eliminates the worry -- common among shoppers at some clothing
chains -- of ending up dressed just like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a much larger variety,'' said shopper Brenda
Singleton, 37, of Raleigh, N.C. ''The Gap is really basic, they
hone in on a few things. Here they have a little bit of
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Singleton, loaded down with an armful of tops and pants, called
them ''play clothes'' and said she knew they might go out of
fashion quickly, but didn't mind because she wasn't paying much.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't come here for work clothes. But it's good prices
for stuff I know I might wear only for (one) summer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others were less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sort of lower quality,'' said a woman who came to make a
return and gave her name as Tammy. ''Disposable things. ... It's
cute stuff but it doesn't look like it's made that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Loeb, the retail analyst, said the excitement around the Fifth
Avenue store is likely to quiet down. But if H&AMP;M expands
aggressively in the United States, he said, it could pose a real
challenge to chains like the Gap, Old Navy and Kohl's.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't expect to have lines around every store, but I see
the (H&AMP;M) stores crowded around every part of Europe, so why
shouldn't it'' be the same here, he said. ''I think it will be
strong competition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 1550 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carpenter ants symptom of bigger problems  </HEADLINE>
By RIK STEVENS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- If Amy Howansky sees evidence of a carpenter
ant invasion, the first call she makes isn't to an exterminator.
</P>
<P>
   It's to a contractor. Or a plumber.
</P>
<P>
   The exterminator can kill the ants that wreak $750 million worth
of havoc on buildings every year nationwide, but at the root of
their presence is a leaky pipe, broken screen, cracked foundation
or other condition that's letting them in.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like a headache,'' said Howansky, consumer horticulturist
for Cornell Cooperative Extension of Albany County. ''When you have
a headache, the headache isn't the problem, it's a sign of a
problem. When you have ants, it's a sign that you have a leak maybe
somewhere you didn't know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Extermination, she said, is only a short-term fix, she said.
''You're going to kill the ants but not get rid of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ants like houses for the same reasons people do. They're warm,
dry and, even with a meticulous housekeeper, usually good sources
of food in the form of crumbs and spills.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, the ants find comfortable cavities between walls,
under floors, even in the hollow of the shower curtain rod and set
up colonies, which can grow to 100,000 individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter ants are one of the largest of the species living in
North America, growing up to 3/4-inch long. They are generally
black but can be brown, red or red and black. They will eat any
kinds of food but prefer sweets and will travel up to 300 feet from
the nest in search of a meal.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter ants don't eat wood. They burrow through it, carrying
out a smooth and clean sawdust -- and the corpses of fallen workers
-- as they tunnel into a house. Piles of sawdust and ant bodies are
a good sign of infestation. They prefer wet or decayed wood and
they can seriously damage a house. The sandy soils and pine trees
of upstate New York are an inviting habitat for the creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Recent warm winters may mean more ants this spring, said David
Swann of Terminix International.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the chance of infestation:
</P>
<P>
   -- Inspect doors, windows, plumbing, the roof and other points of
entry, repairing even small holes, leaks or cracks.
</P>
<P>
   -- Store firewood off the ground at least 15 feet away from the
house.
</P>
<P>
   -- Remove dead trees and stumps and trim branches that hang over
or touch the house.
</P>
<P>
   -- Keep cupboards clean.
</P>
<P>
   -- Store garbage in dry places, empty often and keep the bin
clean.
</P>
<P>
   If the house is infested, there are over-the-counter poisons
available or the homeowner can call an exterminator.
</P>
<P>
   Exterminators may need to repeat applications to get rid of the
persistent pests, Swann said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One thing that is for sure, when people built their houses,
they built them on top of ants,'' Swann said. ''The ants were here
first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 1552 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatian Ship Captain Arrested in U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- A tanker captain has been charged with failing
to report a leak in his ship, after an investigation that began
when a member of his crew slipped a note to Coast Guardsmen who had
come aboard for a routine inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Davor Maric of Croatia was arrested and released on $30,000 bail
Tuesday. His passport was confiscated and his movements were
restricted to metropolitan Baltimore and the Croatian Embassy in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from an incident March 22, when Maric attempted
to unload part of the Norwegian tanker's cargo of liquid ammonium
nitrate in Baltimore before proceeding to Tampa, Fla., prosecutors
said. Ammonium nitrate is used in fertilizer and other products.
</P>
<P>
   When a Coast Guard team boarded the ship that day, a crew member
slipped an inspector a handwritten note that read, ''THIS IS
CONFIDENTIAL. ''DON'T SHOW TO THE C/E SIR.'' ''C/E'' stands for
''chief engineer.''
</P>
<P>
   The note said the tanker had a crack in its hull. Another crew
member then told an inspector the ship was taking on water and was
in danger of sinking.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors found a large, hastily patched 12-by-18-inch hole in
the engine room of the 6,379-ton Freja Jutlandic. They later
uncovered records indicating the ship's operator had asked the
captain to keep quiet about the damage, first discovered March 12
en route from Europe to Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   The ship initially leaked about 105 gallons of oily water per
hour. The crew later estimated the ship leaked about five times
that amount.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Maric stem from the safety hazard of not
reporting the structural damage to the ship, not from environmental
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, Coast Guard inspectors said they ''observed a
cascade of water flowing into the bilge from a square cement patch
on the side of the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   The ship was later placed in dry dock, repaired and allowed to
leave for Tampa, returning to Baltimore with a cargo of molasses on
April 23. The ship was searched again on April 25. That search
uncovered the documents that led to Maric's arrest Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Maric faces charges of violating federal laws that require
reporting hazardous conditions to the Coast Guard and with creating
false entries in the ship's record to conceal the dumping of
untreated oily waste. Both violations carry possible five-year
prison sentences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1553 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece-Turkey Relations Improving  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou said
Wednesday that relations with Turkey have improved, partly the
result of cooperation in earthquake relief, and Athens is helping
Turkey prepare for membership in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Greece does not believe that Turkey's Muslim culture should be
an obstacle to joining the 15-nation EU, Papandreou told reporters
at the Greek Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is truly a blossoming of nongovernmental contacts,
business people, journalists,'' he said. ''Day in, day out.''
</P>
<P>
   The same spirit prevails among the Turkish and Greek Cypriot
communities on divided Cyprus, he said. He cited a turnout of blood
donors from both along the dividing line to help two children with
leukemia, one Turkish Cypriot, the other Greek Cypriot.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this new spirit, this dividing line is an anachronism,''
Papandreou said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the United Nations due to convene a third round of
talks on May 23, Papandreou said, ''We haven't seen much of a
change'' on moving toward a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides was to have an
intestinal operation Friday, and will be on the sidelines for two
weeks, possibly forcing him to postpone negotiations with Turkish
Cypriots, Cyprus Radio said Wednesday in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish troops invaded the island in 1974, occupying about
one-third of the country. An independent republic was established
that is recognized only by Turkey and is bolstered by Turkish
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Rauf Denktash was sworn in last month for his fourth term as
president of the republic and pledged to work ''to elevate the
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus.''
</P>
<P>
   Papandreou said Denktash apparently wants to be ''king of the
hill.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternative, the Greek minister said, is to build on
increasing good will and contact between the two communities and
consider ways two zones can be locally administered under a federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one knows if this round is going to be successful,''
Papandreou said.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the long run, he said the new atmosphere between Greece
and Turkey and on Cyprus itself ''will play a role -- either in
solving this problem or making it difficult for Turkey to be
accepted by the European Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Papandreou said later in a speech to the American Jewish
Committee that ''the road to reconciliation is not paved with
roses. Both in Greece and Turkey, there have been voices of
dissent. Extremist militant and nationalist elements have attempted
to undermine'' the improving relationship between Greece and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ''Cyprus can and must become a showcase -- living
proof of how different races and religions can live together in
harmony.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
