<HEADLINE> Dry Outlook Boosts Grains, Soybeans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Dry weather forecasts pushed soybeans futures
prices higher in trading Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade,
where they briefly reached new 17-month highs for the third
straight day.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat futures also closed strongly higher, partly due to worries
about dry weather in some of China's growing regions and
speculation that China will place orders for U.S. wheat next week.
</P>
<P>
   Corn futures prices also continued to rise on news of dry
conditions in the western corn belt, and despite heavy planting.
</P>
<P>
   Grains and soybeans prices have been affected by forecasts
calling for continued hot, dry weather in the U.S. Plains and
western corn belt. Forecasts indicate that a complex weather
pattern could prolong the dry, warm conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose 6\ cents to $2.72 a bushel; July
corn rose 4{ cents to $2.50} a bushel; July oats rose 1} cents to
$1.28\ a bushel; and July soybeans rose 6{ cents to $5.72 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures prices fell in trading Wednesday on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle was unchanged at 68.90 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle fell .77 cent to 84.70 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell 2 cents to 74.27 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 3 cents
to 92.62 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
