<HEADLINE> Bail cut for man accused of killing ex-girlfriend on wedding day  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) -- A state judge on Wednesday reduced the
bail for a prominent businessman accused of killing his
ex-girlfriend on her wedding day from $5 million to $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Agustin Garcia, however, are uncertain how quickly
they can post the new bail and indicated they will still pursue a
''passion provocation'' defense. They said they expect an
indictment soon, and that a trial is at least a half-year away.
</P>
<P>
   During a half-hour bail hearing, Assistant Bergen County
Prosecutor James V. Santulli argued against any reduction and said
a decision on whether to seek the death penalty ''would be made
shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, 48, of North Bergen, has been jailed since the Sept. 26,
1999, shooting of Gladys Ricart at her home in Ridgefield as she
prepared to marry James Preston, 36.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, well-known in the Dominican community in New Jersey and
New York as head of several nonprofit organizations, did not speak
during the half-hour hearing. He was shackled at the wrists and
ankles, and wore an orange jail jumpsuit.
</P>
<P>
   He was unaware that the 39-year-old accountant was marrying
another man, his lawyers maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Judge, this was not a premeditated situation,'' Garcia lawyer
Fernando J. Oliver said, arguing Garcia poses no danger if
released.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver discounted prosecution claims that Garcia had stalked
Ricart for eight months, asserting that defense investigators have
interviewed more than 60 people, including 24 who place Garcia and
Ricart together during that period.
</P>
<P>
   Those people say the couple introduced each other at political
and business events as ''husband and wife,'' and were ''in a
romantically involved relationship,'' even ''up to the night before
her death,'' Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   Although born in the Dominican Republic, Garcia is a U.S.
citizen and has deep family and social ties to the area, so would
be unlikely to flee, Oliver said, pointing to 40 Garcia supporters
in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Santulli, pointing to Preston and Ricart's family in the
audience, countered that Garcia is both a danger to them and a
flight risk since his parents remain in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ''In taking a life in front of all those witnesses shows he is a
very desperate person, and a desperate person is a risk to flee,''
Santulli said, noting Garcia faces, at a minimum, significant
prison time.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said it was ''uncontroverted'' that Garcia walked
into Ricart's home and emptied an illegal handgun by firing five
shots ''nearly point-blank'' at Ricart, striking her three times.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had additional bullets in his pocket and had opened the
chamber to reload'' when he was subdued by Juan Ricart, the bride's
brother, Santulli said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say a videotape taken by a professional wedding
photographer hired by Ricart shows some of what happened at
Ricart's house.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has not seen it yet and maintained that Santulli's
statements cannot be considered facts.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge William C. Meehan, noting that the
Dominican Republic has an extradition treaty with the United
States, said that in addition to posting $1.5 million bail, Garcia
cannot be freed until he provides the court with the New Jersey
address where he will reside and sign a waiver of extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, who set the $5 million bail in September, also ordered
that Garcia wear an electronic ankle bracelet to ensure he remains
under house arrest, aside from visits to lawyers and other approved
trips.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Oliver said it appears that family and friends
will have to post property in order for Garcia to make bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 1604 </TRAILER>
