<HEADLINE> Postal Finance Chief Named  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Northern Virginia district postal manager
was named acting chief financial officer for the Postal Service on
Wednesday, replacing a man who resigned last month amid a furor
over excessive moving expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Strasser was appointed acting chief finance officer
and executive vice president by Postmaster General William
Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming Northern Virginia operations manager, Strasser,
a 30-year veteran of the agency, had held postal financial and
management jobs, including serving as the agency's chief marketing
officer and chief planning officer.
</P>
<P>
   He succeeds Richard Porras, who retired after a report from the
post office's inspector general criticized payment of $248,000 in
moving expenses for Porras and then controller John Ward, both of
whom moved less than 50 miles and continued working in the same
offices. Ward has been reassigned to the service's marketing
department.
</P>
<P>
   The uproar over the payments also prompted the agency's board of
governors to assume oversight of all future management moving
expenses and to launch a study of management pay and benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
