<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retrial Sought in Jail Chief Death  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES E. BEGGS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, Ore. (AP) -- Eleven years after the murder of Oregon's
corrections chief, the man convicted in the stabbing is asking for
a new trial -- with the support of the victim's family -- based on
the claim that his lawyer was drunk during his 1991 trial.
</P>
<P>
   After years of appeals and repeated claims of innocence from
drug dealer Frank Gable, two days of hearings on his request for a
retrial were set to conclude Wednesday. It could be weeks before
Judge Frank Yraguen rules.
</P>
<P>
   Gable, 40, was convicted in 1991 of stabbing Corrections
Director Michael Francke in the heart while trying to break into
Francke's car outside state corrections headquarters. A jury spared
Gable the death penalty and gave him life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Gable, himself a recovering alcoholic, said his court-appointed
attorney, Robert Abel, was drinking during the trial and botched
his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''The job he did ... was horrendous,'' Gable said at the hearing
on Tuesday, recalling that he smelled alcohol on Abel's breath at
various times. ''He popped breath mints like they were going out of
style.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing on Wednesday, Abel denied the allegation that he
was drunk during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Gable's claim of innocence is getting support from a surprising
quarter -- Francke's mother and two brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear Frank Gable was not properly represented and was
denied his rights under Oregon law,'' said Kansas City businessman
Patrick Francke. He added: ''I don't think Frank Gable killed my
brother. There is nothing that connects Frank Gable to the murder
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Francke's mother, 86-year-old Helen Francke, and brother Kevin
Francke all said Tuesday they believe someone else committed the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Francke was 42 and had been head of
the state prison system for two years. The 1989 murder shocked
Oregon. There was speculation -- later discounted -- that the murder
was linked to an investigation by Francke into allegedly shady
dealings in his department.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gable's current lawyer called five witnesses who
testified that Abel smelled of alcohol at various times.
</P>
<P>
   Gable also contended that at least two people called as
witnesses at his trial lied about his whereabouts at the time of
the killing, and that Abel failed to counter them with witnesses
who could support his alibi.
</P>
<P>
   One of the witnesses, convicted drug dealer Cappie Harden,
testified at the trial that he saw Gable stab Francke. Harden was
apparently the only witness to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Gable also said Abel wouldn't let him testify at the trial. ''I
demanded to testify, and Abel stood up and rested'' the defense
case, Gable said.
</P>
<P>
   Abel denied that he was drunk during the trial and rejected the
assertion that he didn't give Gable a chance to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never told him he couldn't testify,'' Abel said. ''That
would be insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Abel also rejected the claims that he had mounted an incompetent
defense. ''In a case like this, you do everything you can,'' said
Abel, adding that he made long and detailed preparations for the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, District Attorney Dale Penn said the
right man was convicted. ''Our goal was to get to the truth, and
there's no doubt in my mind that Frank Gable killed Michael
Francke,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1609 </TRAILER>
