<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Plunges to Yet Another Low  </HEADLINE>
By CONSTANT BRAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The euro tumbled to yet another low in
its steepest selloff ever Wednesday, not only falling below 90
cents for the first time, but also retreating below 89 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless the European Central Bank performs a miraculous rescue
mission, anyone on board the euro may as well be on board the
Titanic,'' said Neil Parker, senior European economist at Royal
Bank of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The response of the central bank was calm, as its vice chairman
appeared before the European Parliament and predicted that the
currency of 11 nations would rebound due to economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want a stronger euro and are confident that this will
materialize,'' Christian Noyer, the vice chairman of the ECB, told
the EU assembly's economic affairs committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly we have no sacred wish to push the euro down,''
Noyer said. He added that the central bank is well aware that a
falling currency can push inflation higher by raising the price of
imports, especially oil -- which is priced in dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The euro fell as low as 88.85 cents Wednesday, down 2.2 cents
from its high point Tuesday of 91.07 cents, the biggest such
one-day decline ever. By the end of trading in New York, the euro
had recovered some lost ground and was quoted at 89.61 cents
compared with a late rate Tuesday of 90.73 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's previous low of 90.30 cents was reached during
trading last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The selling came as the European Commission and central bank
backed the entry of Greece into the monetary union, which critics
contended would further weaken the euro. Some analysts said the
currency was on its way down anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a very established trend, and once a trend develops,
it's hard for it to turn on a dime,'' said Grant Wilson, vice
president of foreign exchange at Mellon Bank in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   At its new low, the euro was down 25 percent from the all-time
high of $1.1886 reached during its first day of trading, Jan. 4,
1999. It also was down 12 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   As the low euro raises the price of imports, it makes it more
difficult for businesses in the United States, Britain, Japan and
other strong economies to sell their products in the 11-nation
zone. But it helps tourists stretch their vacation dollars in
Europe and bolsters exports from the euro region.
</P>
<P>
   Noyer reiterated the central bank's concerns that a weak
currency carried inflationary risks over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   But he would not comment on the euro's new low, or whether the
ECB would step in to try to turn it around-- a move the Frankfurt,
Germany-based institution has resisted so far.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will never comment on possible intervention before'' it
happens, Noyer told the parliamentary committee.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB nudged its key short-term interest rate up one-quarter
of a percentage point last week, to 3.75 percent, to counter
''inflationary pressure'' already being felt he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Bernhard Pfaff, from Commerzbank in Frankfurt said the
interest rate hike by the ECB last week was interpreted by the
markets as not enough, thus it gave no support to the sinking
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaff said the latest drop of the euro could not be explained by
fundamentals in the European economy, which are mostly good.
''Dollar investments just look more attractive,'' said Pfaff
especially given the ''dynamic U.S. economy.''
</P>
<P>
   European leaders kept a stiff upper lip, insisting that the
economic recovery under way across the continent was bound to turn
the euro around soon.
</P>
<P>
   Danish Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen said the euro
''should not be measured on its value against the dollar (but) on
what it can safeguard in our area.''
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's spokesman, Uwe-Karsten
Heye, said the German government viewed the latest development
''with great calmness.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the euro's woes, the European Commission and the ECB
backed Greece's bid to join the euro-zone by Jan. 1, 2001
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The EU commissioner for economic and monetary affairs, Pedro
Solbes, rejected criticism that Greek membership would further drag
down the euro-zone's single currency and said Greece's bid was
based on the same economic criteria as the other members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
