<HEADLINE> Denmark Launches Euro Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By JAN M. OLSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- The government launched a campaign
Wednesday to persuade Danes to adopt the euro -- the same day the
currency slid to a new low against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is aimed at garnering support for a referendum
being held in September that will ask voters whether they want to
switch from the Danish kroner to the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we're putting all our strength in getting a 'yes' on Sept.
28,'' said Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen in launching the
''Best for Denmark'' publicity campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate Danes are evenly split on whether to join
the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
   A survey published last week showed 46 percent favor the euro,
44 percent were against, and 10 percent were undecided. The margin
of error was 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Nyrup Rasmussen's ruling Social Democratic party strongly
endorsed the euro at a meeting Sunday. On Wednesday, he introduced
a 10-member team that will crisscross the country to drum up public
support.
</P>
<P>
   ''There won't be much summer holiday,'' Party Secretary Willy
Stig Andersen said. ''But it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Party members and pro-euro activists will make statements,
answer questions and hand out promotional material at market
squares, shopping malls, beaches and just about anywhere they can
find an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Since the euro was launched by 11 European Union countries in
January 1999, it has mostly sagged against the dollar. Denmark,
Sweden and Britain have declined to adopt the euro in its initial
phase.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted as low as 88.85 cents Wednesday -- 25 percent
off its all-time high and the first time it has sunk below 90 cents
-- before moving slightly higher to 89.61 cents in New York trading,
</P>
<P>
   Nyrup Rasmussen said the euro ''shouldn't be measured on its
value against the dollar (but) on what it can safeguard in our
(European) area.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Denmark is not part of the euro zone, its Central Bank
governor and economics minister have little say in policies decided
by the European Central Bank, where their EU colleagues sit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I joined the Social Democratic Youth Party when I was 13
because I wanted to have influence on our lives,'' said Nina Groes,
a 21-year-old party campaigner. ''This is exactly the same we're
doing when we're voting to join the euro. We want to be where the
decisions are taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents -- chiefly on the far right and left political flanks --
say the euro will undermine Denmark's sovereignty and its social
welfare system. They claim Denmark would lose part of its national
identity if coins and bills with the image of Queen Margrethe were
replaced by EU coins and bank notes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
