<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. F. Examiner Publisher Suspended  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The Hearst Corp. suspended the San
Francisco Examiner's publisher after he testified that he offered
Mayor Willie Brown favorable editorials if he supported the
company's deal to buy the San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Brown denied there was any impropriety and said he thinks the
Examiner's Timothy White was ''bushwhacked.''
</P>
<P>
   White, editor and publisher of the Hearst-owned Examiner, was
taking an ''indefinite leave of absence,'' Hearst announced late
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   White testified Monday in the federal antitrust trial
challenging Hearst's $660 million purchase of the rival Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   In statements Tuesday, Hearst contended that the conversation
White described on the witness stand never happened, or, if it did
happen, violated company policy. And White recanted his testimony
in a statement issued by Hearst: ''I was tired and confused by the
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Examiner Executive Editor Phil Bronstein said he was present at
the lunch meeting when Brown talked with White and there was ''no
discussion whatsoever about any favorable coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In terms of the kind of things that are being talked about,
'horse trading' and so forth, there was none of that,'' Bronstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown told the Chronicle on Tuesday: ''There was no impropriety
to speak of.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember a very pleasant lunch,'' Brown said. ''It sounds
like Mr. White was bushwhacked, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's spokeswoman told The Associated Press today that
Brown was referring to his questioning on the witness stand by
lawyer Joseph M. Alioto, representing businessman and political
figure Clint Reilly, who is challenging the newspaper sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''A wide variety of subjects were discussed but nothing seemed
inappropriate,'' Kandace Bender, Brown's spokeswoman said today.
''The mayor has led the charge to keep the Examiner alive. He wants
a two-newspaper town.''
</P>
<P>
   White's duties will be handled by George Irish, president of
Hearst Newspapers, the company said. White did not return a phone
message left at his office.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's lawyers said that no denial of White's statement was
offered in court under oath and that Hearst lawyers passed up a
chance to call White back to the stand Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's cowardly,'' Alioto, one of the lawyers, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto asked today for a restraining order prohibiting Hearst
Corp. from punishing employees for their testimony. He was turned
down by U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said Tuesday that Irish, Hearst CEO Frank Bennack Jr. and
other Hearst executives had to know about White's comments to Brown
because they received e-mail from White describing the meeting. He
said White was being used as a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   At the Chronicle, Managing Editor Jerry Roberts said the staff
was surprised and even upset about White's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it calls into question the credibility of what you
read on the editorial page,'' Roberts said. ''In other words, is
this really what the editorial board and the editorial writers
believe, or is this somehow something that's put in there for some
ulterior motive.''
</P>
<P>
   White's disclosure overshadowed the opening of the trial on
Reilly's lawsuit seeking to prevent Hearst from buying the
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends the acquisition of California's second-largest
newspaper would give Hearst an illegal monopoly, despite approval
of the sale by the Justice Department's Antitrust Division.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, an unsuccessful bidder for the Examiner, contends
Hearst's agreement to give its flagship newspaper to publisher Ted
Fang, along with a $66 million subsidy over three years, is
designed to let the paper fail quickly and leave the city with a
single newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   White testified Monday that he met with Brown on Aug. 30, as the
mayor's re-election campaign against Reilly and two other
candidates was heating up. Brown had publicly opposed Hearst's
plans, announced Aug. 6, to buy the Chronicle and sell or merge the
Examiner into the larger paper.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto asked White if he had told Brown that support of the sale
would get him ''more favorable treatment in the Examiner.'' White
said yes, and later specified that he was talking only about
editorials, not news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail sent afterward to the head of Hearst's newspaper
division and read in court, White said, ''I asked Willie how I was
going to justify to my superiors in New York wanting to support him
and cooperate with him when he was seeming to go out of his way to
make our lives difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In the months after the meeting, Brown worked behind the scenes
to support the Examiner sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
