<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Critical of Agency Reports  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ZUCKERBROD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many federal agencies are doing a terrible job
writing mandatory performance reports and should be penalized for
their shoddy work, Sen. Fred Thompson said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Governmental Affairs Committee chairman released a
study that ranked the agencies according to the quality of their
year-end reports.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many of these agencies still don't know how to write a
report,'' said Thompson, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   A then-Democratic Congress passed a law in 1993 requiring the
reports, but the first ones were not due until this year. They
covered fiscal 1999 and had to be completed by March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by George Mason University's Mercatus
Center, analyzed the reports by 24 agencies, then ranked them
according to readability and how well they documented public
benefits, forward-looking leadership and improvement strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agency for International Development and the
departments of Transportation and Veterans Affairs were deemed to
have the best reports.
</P>
<P>
   The National Science Foundation ranked last for its disorganized
and poorly formatted report, according to the study. Among other
things, NSF did not attempt to compare 1999 results to those from
previous years and did not discuss management challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Commerce report was slightly better than the
NSF document but there is ''slim chance that many people will read
its 180 pages laden with undefined acronyms, technical jargon and
poorly designed tables,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies have had seven years to comply with the law and now
should pay for failing to meet all of the reporting requirements,
Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There needs to be some sanctions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he ordered the General Accounting Office, the
inspectors general for the agencies and the Congressional Research
Service to further analyze the reports.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would forward the information they glean to chairs of
the congressional committees that control the agencies' budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll be able to get them some useful information even this
year,'' Thompson said. ''Some people are going to have to answer
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: George Mason University's Mercatus Center:
http://www.mercatus.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
