<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Boosts Stock Option Access  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation approved by the House on Wednesday
and sent to President Clinton would remove a possible obstacle to
companies offering stock option plans to their workers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved 421-0, amends the 1938 Fair Labor Standards
Act to make clear that stock option profits should not be
considered a part of regular pay in determining overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Labor Department issued an opinion stating that
profits from the exercising of stock options would have to be
included in calculating the regular rate of pay. That decision
raised concerns that employers would be disinclined to offer stock
options to hourly workers if that would significantly drive up the
costs of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The House's chief sponsor, Rep. Randy ''Duke'' Cunningham,
R-Calif., said that when the 1938 law was written, no one knew that
want ads today would be filled with jobs offering stock options.
''Workers look at these things when they select a job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, stock options, stock appreciation rights
and bona fide stock purchases would be treated as employee benefits
and would not be used in calculating overtime compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stock option programs are new avenues for the front-line
worker,'' said Rep. Major Owens, D-N.Y., in support of the
legislation. ''However, the right to overtime remains protected by
the Fair Labor Standards Group for this same group of employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The identical Senate bill, sponsored by Sen. Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky., passed the Senate last month by 95-0 and is supported by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   An administration statement said it would ''provide employers
with needed flexibility to reward their workers in a global economy
without weakening the vital protections provided by the Fair Labor
Standards Act for American workers.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is S. 2323.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative information:
http://thomas.loc.gov/home/thomas.html?57,18
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1634 </TRAILER>
