<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats: DeLay Is Racketeering  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats filed suit under civil
anti-racketeering laws Wednesday against House Republican Whip Tom
DeLay, alleging he oversees an organization that extorts campaign
contributions and evades federal disclosure requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., who chairs the Democratic campaign
committee, said Rep. DeLay stands atop an unprecedented operation,
''hammering contributors for money, threatening to punish those who
decline and setting up a shadow party structure outside public view
and our laws ...''
</P>
<P>
   Several of DeLay's aides greeted reporters arriving for the news
conference where the suit was announced and handed them written
statements accusing Democrats of ''resorting to ugly, unfounded,
politically motivated charges ...''
</P>
<P>
   His office later accused Kennedy and House Democratic Leader
Dick Gephardt of ''political terrorism and personal destruction''
and said DeLay deserves ''a personal apology.''
</P>
<P>
   In their legal complaint and in response to reporters'
questions, Democrats cited numerous newspaper and magazine articles
but said they had no independent proof of their claims. They said
they hope to question DeLay's associates as the lawsuit proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court here, is the latest in a
constant refrain of charge and counter-charge between the political
parties over alleged violations of campaign fund-raising laws.
</P>
<P>
   It serves as an election-season counter to a GOP effort to make
a campaign issue of Vice President Al Gore's controversial
fund-raising activities in the 1996 election. At the same time,
beginning with the departure of former Speaker Newt Gingrich 16
months ago, Democrats have periodically tried to turn DeLay, a
Texan whose nickname is ''The Hammer,'' into a symbol of the GOP
Congress they constantly accuse of arrogant extremism.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Gross, a private lawyer and former general counsel at the
Federal Election Commission, said ''it's a stretch to say you can
apply the (anti-rackeeting laws) to political fund-raising and make
it stick.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, though, that if Democrats can win the right to
subpoena documents, they could gain access to internal memoranda
and ''cause a lot of consternation'' to DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic lawsuit alleges that as whip, DeLay has long
''threatened to withhold favorable action on'' legislation unless
an affected party increased contributions to Republicans and cut
them to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay and his agents ''have engaged in a scheme to extort
political contributions from individuals and entities with
interests before Congress and to avoid otherwise applicable
reporting requirements relating to donors and political
contributions and expenditures,'' the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   It alleges that DeLay has established a network of political
organizations, independent from traditional GOP groups, that are
not registered under federal election law and don't report on their
donors. The suit says DeLay's operation directs GOP donors to
contribute to these organizations, thus evading reporting
requirements that would otherwise apply.
</P>
<P>
   These organizations were identified as the U.S. Family Network,
the Republican Majority Issues Committee and Americans for Economic
Growth. The DeLay associates involved in their operation were named
as Ed Buckham, his former chief of staff; Karl Gallant and Jim
Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Gallant issued a statement labeling the suit ''an attack by
(Democratic) party hacks against independent issues groups, and
therefore an attack on the First Amendment as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy asked the Justice Department a year ago to investigate
whether the Republicans were violating campaign laws by raising
funds for the Republican Majority Issues Committee. The complaint
was eventually referred to the Federal Election Commission, often a
graveyard for such politically-charged disputes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1635 </TRAILER>
