<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes $140M Lake Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A $140 million effort to restore the Lake
Pontchartrain Basin would be launched under a bill the House passed
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The basin is 5,000 square miles and encompasses 16 parishes in
southeast Louisiana and four Mississippi counties. At its center is
the 630-square mile Lake Pontchartrain, the second largest lake in
the United States after the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed by a 418-6 vote, amends the Clean
Water Act to establish a program for water quality restoration
activities in the basin. The Senate has not acted on a companion
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the basin has been hurt over the years by
wetland loss, human activities and natural forces.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Rep. David Vitter of Louisiana, the bill's sponsor, said the
measure would, ''facilitate and accelerate the restoration,
maintenance and cleanup of truly one of America's most significant
bodies of water.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 2957
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1635 </TRAILER>
