<DOCNO> APW20000503.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak: Settle Treaty's Basic Terms  </HEADLINE>
By DANA BUDEIRI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Trying to win political support for land
concessions, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak wants to settle the
basic terms of a peace treaty before saying how much land he will
give the Palestinians in an interim withdrawal, an aide said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. mediator said the two sides will need at least six more
weeks of intense negotiations to reach an outline of the treaty --
meaning they will miss yet another peace deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The outline was initially due Feb. 13 and then postponed to this
month. The full treaty, which will tackle issues like Palestinian
statehood, Palestinian refugees, contested Jerusalem and Jewish
settlements, is due Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are also to discuss the scope of a third and final
interim Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank. But Barak is trying
to postpone those talks, in exchange for giving the Palestinians
full control over three Jerusalem suburbs as a good will gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Barak hopes that Israelis will be more likely to support giving
land to the Palestinians if the broad outlines of a final peace
treaty are already in place. He has promised to bring the treaty to
a national referendum and is considering putting the outline
agreement to a referendum vote, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon, who often speaks for Barak, said
talks in the Red Sea resort of Eilat would stall if negotiators
tackled the interim withdrawal now.
</P>
<P>
   ''To go now directly to negotiations on the third phase of
redeployment means that there is no chance to reach any
agreement,'' Ramon told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   During the latest round of talks, which began Sunday, there have
been alternating sessions on both issues.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Barak cannot even get his diverse Cabinet to
agree to give up the three villages.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the issue, originally planned for Wednesday, was
postponed due to opposition from parties in Barak's coalition,
including the ultra-Orthodox Shas party that wants Barak to hand
over millions of dollars to its struggling religious school system.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon said he hoped Shas would agree to the handover within
days.
</P>
<P>
   Two hawkish coalition parties, the National Religious Party and
Israel B'Aliya, which represents immigrants, have threatened to
leave the government if Israel hands over the suburbs, which are
already under Palestinian civil control.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have reacted coolly to the initiative, calling
it a ''trial balloon.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said Israeli coalition
politics were hurting the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Gaps remain wide between the two sides, and U.S. Mideast envoy
Dennis Ross said he would shuttle between the negotiators, Barak,
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say that over the next six to eight weeks, we are
going to see if there is a potential and a need to make big
decisions to reach a framework agreement,'' Ross told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Ross is to hold separate talks with Barak and
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians want to establish a state in all of the West
Bank, Gaza and east Jerusalem, areas Israel captured in the 1967
Mideast war. Israel wants to keep all of Jerusalem and annex parts
of the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has said it would step up its involvement,
including presenting its own proposals at some stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1643 </TRAILER>
