<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kids Are Kidnap Targets in Colombia  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY PRATT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALI, Colombia (AP) -- Less than a month before he was snatched
off a school bus by three armed men, 9-year-old Dagoberto Ospina
drew a poster of a child with a red band over his mouth, tears on
his cheeks and chains on his hands and feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is this how you shape Colombia's future?'' the boy wrote
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Dagoberto's kidnapping last week has become a rallying point for
national outrage over the increased targeting of children by
leftist rebels, drug gangs and common criminals. Dagoberto remained
missing on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty children and teen-agers were reported abducted in the
first three months of this year in Colombia -- an increase of
one-third from 1999, according to the independent anti-kidnapping
group Pais Libre.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia, which has the world's highest kidnapping rate, had
2,945 reported kidnappings last year; 7 percent of those victims
were children.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is consistent with the logic of the war here,'' said
Nidia Quiroz, 50, a UNICEF child psychologist in Bogota, the
capital. ''As the peace process continues,'' she said, ''the rebels
want to show more force, and need more money.''
</P>
<P>
   President Andres Pastrana's government has been engaged for 15
months in peace talks with Colombia's largest rebel army, the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, for whom ransom
kidnappings are a key revenue source.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has a sort of domino effect with common criminals,'' said
Quiroz. ''And within Colombia's culture of easy money, well,
children are a gold mine -- parents would pay anything to recover
their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Dagoberto was kidnapped on April 25 as he, 32 classmates and
three teachers were riding in a school bus to the Alferez Real
school on the outskirts of Cali, Colombia's third-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   A pickup truck cut off the bus and three men with revolvers and
grenades rushed aboard. One pointed his gun at the driver's head.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lower your heads or we'll blow up everyone,'' screamed
another, according to adult witnesses. They asked for ''Victor
Ospina,'' getting the child's first name wrong. No one responded
and they began checking notebooks until they got to one that said
''Ospina.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the men grabbed the boy, who began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't take me!'' he pleaded before being dragged into the
waiting truck.
</P>
<P>
   Dagoberto's kidnapping followed the March 1 seizure of three
teen-agers from another Cali school by the country's No. 2
guerrilla band, the National Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   His poster of the child in chains was made as part of a school
project to protest that abduction. The poster showed a child in
shorts and a blue baseball cap -- similar to the one he himself was
wearing in a photo Colombian news media have distributed in a
''Free Dagoberto'' campaign demanding his release.
</P>
<P>
   Parents in Cali now fear letting their children play outside,
often keeping them indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Ramirez, 10, misses ''playing hide-and-seek and soccer''
with his friend Dagoberto.
</P>
<P>
   The two boys helped formed a school group called ''Shapers of
Peace'' two years ago after watching armed guerrillas on the TV
news.
</P>
<P>
   The group's goal was ''to get adults to listen to us, since we
have ideas, too, and want children left out of the conflict,''
Cesar said.
</P>
<P>
   After Dagoberto's abduction, the ''Shapers of Peace'' decided to
go to the FARC rebels to ask if the guerrilla group was holding
their friend.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a FARC commander, Marcos Calarca, spoke by
walkie-talkie with about 50 children at the school and told them
his group did not have the child. Then he fielded questions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were scared at first,'' said Cesar. ''We didn't want to say
our last names, because maybe they would come for us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The children's questions included, ''Why do you kidnap
children?''
</P>
<P>
   Answer: ''We don't kidnap, we raise funds -- just as the
(Colombian) army does with the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   And, ''Don't you have children?''
</P>
<P>
   That was met with silence.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, four police agents shot and killed one of
Dagoberto's alleged kidnappers in a Cali shopping center. Officials
said he was part of a band that abducts people and turns them over
to guerrillas, drug mafias or other outlaw groups for up to
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The groups then demand ransoms of families. But as of yet,
nobody has asked the Ospina family for a ransom for Dagoberto,
authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Saturday was Children's Day, a holiday widely
commemorated in Latin America. An estimated 30,000 children marched
in Colombia's major cities, waving white flags and chanting
Dagoberto's name.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Farlis Calle, 18, an activist with the Children's
Movement for Peace, a youth group twice nominated for the Nobel
Peace Prize for its work preaching nonviolence.
</P>
<P>
   ''My generation is going to be different,'' Calle said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
