<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal O'Connor Is Near Death  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cardinal John O'Connor, ailing since he
underwent brain surgery last summer, was near death Wednesday, his
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we say in the Hail Mary, pray for us at the hour of our
death,'' said Joseph Zwilling, spokesman for the Roman Catholic
Archdiocese of New York. ''The cardinal is at the hour of his
death. We do not know precisely when he will die ... but I think it
is clear that he is, in Catholic terms, at the hour of his death.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, 80, was in his residence behind St. Patrick's
Cathedral with a sister, other relatives, co-workers and clergy,
Zwilling said. The spokesman said the cardinal was not able to
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the night, the condition of His Eminence ...
worsened,'' Zwilling said. ''We invite the prayers of all for His
Eminence at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling said the cardinal was not in any pain, and two to three
visitors at a time were being allowed to sit with him.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, long one of the city's most visible public figures,
began to fail when he had a brain tumor removed in August 1999. He
suffered complications from his treatments and often appeared weak
and bloated.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor frequently missed Mass and made his last public
appearance at St. Patrick's Cathedral on March 5, when he did not
lead the service but spoke briefly to parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   He traveled to Italy for a final visit to the pope in February.
He was unable to take his customary spot in front of the Cathedral
in March to bless the St. Patrick's Day Parade. He missed Easter
services in April.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has not yet named his successor. Many speculated
that the pope would replace O'Connor soon after his Jan. 15
birthday because cardinals lose their power to vote for a new pope
when they turn 80.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, born in 1920, spent most of his clerical life in
military uniform, joining the Navy in 1952 in response to a call
for more chaplains during the Korean War. He rose to rear admiral
and chief of Navy chaplains before leaving the Navy in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   He became an auxiliary bishop and was assigned to the military
vicarate under Cardinal Terence Cooke of New York. In May 1983,
O'Connor was appointed bishop of Scranton, Pa. He held that post
less than a year before being chosen to succeed Cooke -- who died of
cancer -- as New York archbishop in 1984. He was elevated to
cardinal in May 1985, and has since been the spiritual leader of
2.4 million Catholics in Manhattan, Staten Island, the Bronx and
seven upstate counties.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor once said he would have been satisfied to be a parish
priest or teacher: ''What I would like my epitaph to say is simply
that 'He was a good priest.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
