<HEADLINE> Judge Sends Edwards Jurors Home  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIE GOTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Jurors in the federal racketeering trial
of former Gov. Edwin Edwards were sent home Wednesday, marking the
second day in a row that deliberations in the four-month trial were
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Frank Polozola told the jurors that he is
still conducting an investigation related to the case and would not
finish it by the end of the day. Polozola has not said what the
investigation involves. Attorneys on both sides refused to discuss
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know this is an aggravation, but I can't avoid the
circumstances,'' Polozola told jurors when he dismissed them at
1:30 p.m. and told them to return Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Polozola dismissed the jury after private meetings with
attorneys and defendants in the courtroom and in his chambers. The
judge met behind closed doors with the parties in the case Monday
and Tuesday as well.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, his son Stephen, state Sen. Greg Tarver and four others
are accused in a series of extortion schemes to manipulate the
licensing of Louisiana riverboat casinos from 1991 through 1997. If
convicted on all counts, Edwin Edwards, 72, would face more than
300 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors got the case April 24, but have spent very few days
deliberating, either because of their own requests to be excused
early or because they were awaiting responses from Polozola about
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The jury could continue to deliberate if the judge removes one
juror from the case, leaving 11 to sort out the long verdict form.
An alternate juror must be called up if two jurors are removed.
</P>
<P>
   Once jurors resume deliberations, they must vote on 91
individual counts. Edwards is accused on 26 counts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
