<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Inflation Threat Looms  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The record-breaking U.S. economy is putting
pressure on employers to boost wages as they scramble to find
scarce workers, the Federal Reserve said Wednesday in a national
survey that sounded the central bank's strongest warning bells
about potential inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's survey, based on reports from its 12 regional banks,
said shortages of workers persisted in all areas, something Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan and other economists fear could lead to
future wage and price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Given the strong economic growth and the tight labor market
conditions cited in the report, economists believe it lays the
foundation for the Fed to boost interest rates on May 16 and in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average tumbled 250.99
points to close at 10,480.130 as fears of higher interest rates
rattled the market and investors punished companies that warned of
slowing earnings growth. The Nasdaq was more resilient, cutting a
late loss of 192.66 points to 78.14, finishing at 3,707.31.
</P>
<P>
   ''The report confirms that there are some inflationary pressures
building in the labor market and the Fed will do all it can to
combat that and make sure it doesn't filter into consumer prices,''
said Richard Yamarone, an economist with Argus Research Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed survey, known as the beige book for the color of its
cover, said ''there were more frequent reports of intensifying wage
pressures as shortages of workers persisted in all districts. ...
Difficulty in finding and retaining qualified employers remained a
common refrain.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer prices remained ''relatively stable'' in most areas as
competition and increased productivity helped keep them in check,
the Fed said. But Philadelphia, Minneapolis and Kansas City
reported more frequent price increases in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The surging economy, in its longest-ever streak of uninterrupted
growth, has pushed the nation's unemployment rate near a
three-decade low of 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To attract workers, employers have been getting more creative in
their recruitment efforts, offering bonuses, child care, education
and better health care benefits, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   While that's good for workers, economists and some members of
the Fed worry that these increased costs could be passed along to
consumers in the form of sharply higher product prices, touching
off inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed said New York, Cleveland and Chicago cited significant
increases in health care costs as contributing to intensified cost
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   While companies reported rising prices for certain materials --
some of which were related to surging energy prices -- there were
few instances in which these increased costs resulted in higher
consumer prices, the Fed said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey will be used when Fed policy-makers meet May 16 to
review the central bank's stance on interest rates. It was based on
information collected before April 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has boosted interest rates five times by a quarter-point
each since June 30 in an effort to slow the supercharged economy
and keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   Given the outlook for strong continuing growth, many analysts
widely expect the Fed will raise rates at the May meeting and again
in June.
</P>
<P>
   The economy showed ''moderate to strong'' growth in the majority
of areas around the country during March and part of April, the Fed
survey said. Retailing, commercial construction and manufacturing
activity all were brisk. The volatile stock market did little to
cool red-hot growth.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report, the Commerce Department said that new
orders to American factories rose a bigger-than-expected 2.2
percent in March after two straight sluggish months.
</P>
<P>
   Orders for electronic and electrical equipment, including
household appliances and communications equipment, led March's jump
in total factory orders, rising 10.2 percent, the biggest gain
since August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The beige book: 
http://www.federalreserve.gov/FOMC/BeigeBook/2000/20000503/Default.h
tm
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders report: http://www.census.gov/indicator/www/m3
</P>
</TEXT>
