<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Possible AIDS Crisis Seen in Asia  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In 10 years, the AIDS epidemic could be
sweeping through Asian and Pacific Rim countries even faster than
it's going through sub-Saharan Africa today, an intelligence
official says.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, sub-Saharan Africa led the world in AIDS deaths in
1998 with 2 million -- four-fifths of the world's HIV-deaths, said
David Gordon, the National Intelligence Council's national
intelligence officer for economics and global issues. The council
advises the CIA director.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sub-Sahara Africa ... will continue to remain the most
vulnerable region to infectious diseases over the next 20 years,''
he told a Congressional forum on infectious diseases and national
security.
</P>
<P>
   However, ''Asia and the Pacific ... is likely to witness a
dramatic increase in infectious disease deaths, largely driven by
the spread of HIV/AIDS in south Asia and southeast Asia and its
potential spread to east Asia,'' he said Wednesday. ''In the next
decade the region could surpass Africa in HIV deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was one of the people who produced the national
intelligence estimate called ''The Global Infectious Disease Threat
and Its Implication for the United States.'' The report said
dependance on traditional medicine and the vulnerability of the
private health care delivery system to economic downturns were part
of the problem in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has used the National Intelligence
Council report to defend their decision to classify AIDS as a
threat to national security. Administration officials say AIDS has
become such an epidemic that, in years to come, it threatens to
destabilize nations and the economies of whole continents.
</P>
<P>
   The quick spread of the disease has the potential to destabilize
relations between already shaky countries and could lead to
internal upheaval in countries that have high death rates, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   And ''although several emerging infectious diseases, such as
HIV/AIDS, were first identified in the United States, most,
including HIV/AIDS, originate outside U.S. borders, with the entry
of the West Nile virus in 1999 a case in point,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Nils Daulaire, president of the Global Health Council, cheered
the quick declassification of the January report, saying government
officials will have to adjust their thinking away from what would
normally have been America's traditional enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The enemy here is microbes,'' he said. ''They only care about
meat. They don't care whether it's American meat or Iraqi meat or
Russian meat or Chinese meat. And they don't read.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joseph Crowley, D-N.Y., has introduced a bill to increase
U.S. funding for global health initiatives to $2 billion annually,
double what is currently spent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was Crowley's district that was hit with the West
Nile Virus, which killed seven people in New York City. This was
the first time the virus had appeared in America.
</P>
<P>
   ''This outbreak was a wakeup call,'' Crowley said. ''A disease
knows or respects no boundaries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1741 </TRAILER>
