<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Spar Over Social Security  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush's plan for individual Social
Security investment accounts, which Al Gore attacked Wednesday as
''stock market roulette,'' is an idea that has long enticed
lawmakers and Americans. The trade-offs and potential risks make it
a tough political sell, however.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very bold move for sure'' by Bush, said Alicia Munnell,
a former member of President Clinton's Council of Economic Advisers
and now a professor at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate will outline a Social
Security proposal that includes personal stock market accounts next
week, advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, his Democratic rival, has already begun to hound the Texas
governor, accusing him of being too willing to take risks with the
nation's retirement program -- something polls show Americans are
wary of.
</P>
<P>
   In a January poll by CNN-USA Today-Gallup, six in 10 people said
they favor proposals to divert some Social Security taxes into
personal retirement accounts invested in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   However, previous polls have shown supporters drop to four in 10
if the questions mention that such a move could leave retirement
income vulnerable in case of a stock market decline.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, Gore wants to give Social Security future
government surpluses, which he says will come from the interest
savings gained from his plans to pay down the national debt. He has
tried to dissociate himself from a Clinton administration proposal
that would have the government, rather than individuals, invest
some of those surpluses in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Bush trusts Americans; Gore trusts big government,''
said a statement from the Bush campaign on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is appealing to an emerging class of voters, including a
new generation of senior citizens who have been investing in the
stock market and 401(k) retirement accounts and who may be more
open to the idea of putting Social Security money into Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of personal investment accounts say Gore's surplus
plan carries its own risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think that workers would find it more risky to bet that
(government) debt is going to be paid off down the road than to
have the choice of investing themselves,'' said Leanne Abdnor,
director of a lobbying coalition that includes the National
Association of Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security, which is financed with a special tax deducted
from workers' paychecks, is expected to run short of cash after the
huge baby boom generation begins collecting benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting retirement benefits or raising payroll taxes are
possible solutions, but politically unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   Raising money by letting individuals invest Social Security
taxes in the stock market has seemed like a magic remedy by
comparison, and has drawn devotees among lawmakers in both
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   It has also grown in public appeal during the Wall Street boom
of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers attempting to flesh out the idea have had to answer
some difficult questions, however -- often asked by opponents on the
campaign trail. Chief among these: What happens to people's
retirement income if their investments do poorly?
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm actually surprised that anybody is still advocating
individual accounts given the enormous fluctuations that we are
seeing in the stock market,'' said Munnell.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways to protect people against investment risks,
however, said John Goodman, a Bush adviser on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   First, investment choices could be limited to relatively safe
stock and bond mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Also, under congressional proposals Bush is studying, only a
small portion of a person's Social Security taxes would go into his
investment account. The rest would be kept in the old system and
used to pay the balance of benefits, with a government guarantee
that no one would end up worse off.
</P>
<P>
   The hidden costs of switching to a new Social Security system
are also problematic. Right now, current workers' taxes pay the
benefits of current retirees.
</P>
<P>
   But if younger workers are allowed to divert their Social
Security taxes into stock market investments, where would the money
come from to pay promised benefits to those already retired or near
retirement?
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that additional cash would be needed for the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan congressional proposals suggest possible solutions:
using government surpluses that are also being eyed for tax cuts or
new spending programs, a higher retirement age or more modest
annual cost-of-living raises for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Social Security investment accounts say they are
anxious to know which of those tradeoffs Bush supports.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Hickey, director of a campaign by labor and civil rights
groups to oppose Social Security privatization, said: ''Those are
very, very controversial and objectionable elements to most voters
and I think you're going to see a lot of political debate as to
whether that's a wise thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1742 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
