<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA To Buy Surplus Apples  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Agriculture Department will make a large
purchase of apple products for school lunches and government food
programs to help growers get rid of a huge surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The department will buy nearly 1.65 million cases of applesauce,
juice and slices. It will take bids from growers around the country
and buy the cheapest apples for delivery from July 1 to Sept. 30,
George Chartier, spokesman for the USDA's agricultural marketing
service, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to help out the farmers, which is something we do
with these purchases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apple farmers from Eastern states have been lobbying the federal
government to buy apples to keep the 59 million bushels sitting in
storage as of April 1 from going to waste. The purchase will only
eliminate a small percentage of the surplus, but growers say
anything is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Frost-free nights, adequate moisture for good pollination and a
long fall harvest period allowed the apples to grow plump and
plentiful in the East. Michigan, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania,
Virginia and West Virginia each had crops 17 percent to 31 percent
higher than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions were not as favorable in Washington state,
which typically produces about half the nation's apples. Washington
harvested 121.5 million bushels last year, about 10 million less
than the average of the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
   Kraig Naasz of the U.S. Apple Association said U.S. growers also
were hurt by China selling apple juice concentrate at below-market
prices. The International Trade Commission is expected to rule May
15 on increased duties on Chinese apple imports.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're thankful for the recognition of the terrible economic
conditions now confronting our industry,'' said Naasz, adding that
he would be ''happier still'' when the commission rules on the
association's complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA's purchase includes 1.06 million cases of apple sauce,
285,600 cases of apple juice, 228,000 cases of canned apple slices
for pies and other desserts, and 66,000 cases of frozen apple
slices.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Apple Association: http://www.usapple.org.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural Marketing Service: http://www.ams.usda.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
