<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 250; Nasdaq Down 78  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average tumbled as much
as 331 points Wednesday as interest-rate worries weighed on the
market and investors punished companies that warned of slowing
earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Selling pressure eased in the final hour of Wall Street's
regular session, allowing market averages to pare their losses.
Nonetheless, analysts said the broad-based selloff was a stark
reminder that the pessimism that dominated the market just a few
weeks ago still hangs over Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been a significant change in investors' perceptions,''
said Rao Chalasani, chief investment strategist at First Union
Securities in Chicago. ''Until early March, bad news was ignored.
Now, bad news is perceived as bad news and even good news is
treated with skepticism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow average fell 250.99, or by 2.3 percent, to close at
10,480.13, having edged back from a drop to just above 10,400 in
late afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was more resilient, cutting a late
loss of 192.66 points to 78.14 and closing at 3,707.31, a drop of
2.1 percent. Broader stock indicators were also sharply lower. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 31.19 to 1,415.10.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell for a second session as interest-rate fears kept
many buyers on the sidelines. The Federal Reserve is widely
expected to raise interest rates on May 16 in its continuing bid to
slow the economy enough to keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists are expecting a quarter-percentage point
increase, but worries that the Fed could boost rates by as much a
half-percentage point are rattling the market.
</P>
<P>
   The next key piece of economic data will hit the market on
Friday, when the Labor Department releases employment data for the
month of April. Until then, analysts say, buyers will remain
scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is looking for some comfort in the numbers to come
on Friday,'' said Chalasani, ''Especially for investors in the Old
Economy stocks, interest-rate worries are there.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe that non-technology, ''old economy''
stocks could be hurt the worst by rising interest rates because
their earnings are growing more slowly than the profits of
high-tech companies. Higher interest rates cut into earnings by
making it more expensive to borrow money to finance growth.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, AT&AMP;T fell 2 1/8 to 39 13/16, adding to Tuesday's
14 percent slide and further hurting the blue-chip Dow. PaineWebber
and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette downgraded the stock a day after
company officials warned that full-year operating profits will
likely come in below previous estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ''The company is still at least a few quarters away from hitting
its stride in key business segment operations,'' said Eric
Strumingher, telecommunications analyst at PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Also, software maker Novell fell 6 15/16 to 10| on the Nasdaq
after warning Wall Street that it will miss financial targets in
its fiscal second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sector fell broadly after Goldman Sachs remove
several prominent retailers from its list of recommended stocks.
Kohl's fell 3 13/16 to 48, Target fell 5[ to 63} and Costco fell 2
9/16 to 52 3/16; all were downgraded from ''recommended'' to
''market outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman also lowered its rating on Dow component Wal-Mart,
sending its shares down 4 3/16 to 53 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest gains in Wednesday's market came from the typically
bland food sector. Bestfoods rose 10 11/16 to 61\. Late Tuesday,
the maker of Skippy peanut butter and Hellmann's mayonnaise
rejected an $18.4 billion takeover offer from multinational
consumer products conglomerate Unilever.
</P>
<P>
   The offer valued Bestfoods at 66 per share, a 31 percent premium
to Bestfoods' closing price Tuesday. But Bestfoods said the offer
was not financially adequate and not in the best interest of
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever fell 2 3/16 to 22 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Several other food companies rose Wednesday as investors
anticipated that any or all could come into play. Heinz gained 3
11/16 to 37| and Campbell Soup rose 3 1/16 to 29 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 1.19
billion shares, compared with 1.22 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, decliners led by a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 9.79 to 495.56.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japanese markets were closed for a holiday. Germany's
Xetra DAX index fell 2.4 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 3.0
percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 1.9 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
