<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservation Group Buying Islands  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An isolated speck in the center of the Pacific
Ocean, the Palmyra Atoll, a pristine network of 52 small islands is
being purchased by a conservation group to guarantee the
preservation of its pristine marine wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The Nature Conservancy will announce Thursday that it is buying
the uninhabited islands -- 680 acres of land in all -- and adjacent
coral reefs and lagoons, from the Fullard-Leo family in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The price was not disclosed, but is said to be in the range of
$30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although privately owned, the atoll is considered a territory of
the United States and under the civil jurisdiction of the Interior
Department. The Nature Conservancy hopes that two-thirds of the
atoll eventually will be administered by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service as a wildlife refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it a ''jewel of America's Pacific coral reefs,''
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said the atoll -- just north of the
equator and 1,052 miles south of Honolulu -- ''should be protected
from exploitation'' and preserved for future generations to see.
</P>
<P>
   The island's colorful history dates back more than two centuries
and includes everything from buried pirates' treasure and talk of
an island curse to a battle before the U.S. Supreme Court over
ownership. It played a key part in a murder mystery that eventually
produced a best seller and a made-for-television movie. And while
now seen as an ideal place for ecological research, in the 1970s it
almost became a placed to dump nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   Folklore has it that in 1816 a Spanish pirate ship, full of Inca
treasures, wrecked on the Palmyra reefs and its crew supposedly
buried the loot under a palm tree. But treasure hunting is only one
of the potential threats to the island's plush, tropical foliage,
pristine coral treasures and crystal clear lagoons.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been a range of threats over time'' prompting the
Nature Conservancy's interest in buying the atoll, says Nancy
Mackinnon, who has been working on the Palmyra project for the
conservation group since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the Energy Department saw Palmyra as a place to
dump nuclear waste, only to abandon the idea. Private entrepreneurs
more recently wanted it for chemical and nuclear waste storage.
Other buyers have had plans to build a hotel and casino and even a
retreat for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Palmyra was a U.S. Navy waypoint for
airplanes crossing the Pacific. A 6,000-foot runway and other
buildings were built, but they are now dilapidated and overgrown by
jungle. No one lives on the islands today.
</P>
<P>
   Mackinnon says the island's rich ecological treasures will
provide a paradise for research and ecotourism. ''But only in small
groups,'' she adds quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The islands, which receive 175 inches of rain a year, are
covered by lush tropical vegetation that provides a place for an
estimated million nesting seabirds. Countless birds rely on the
islands as a resting place as they migrate -- some from as far away
as Alaska to the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The atoll's reefs have three to five times the number of coral
species found in Hawaii or the Florida Keys. Black-tip and tiger
sharks abound in its waters and other marine species include pilot
whales, bottlenosed dolphins, hawksbill turtles, giant clams and
the coconut crab, the world's largest land-based invertebrate that
cracks open coconuts with its claws.
</P>
<P>
   Some old salts have suggested the atoll is cursed because of
tales of mariners who have landed there and later fell upon
misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, a San Diego, Calif., couple were murdered aboard their
expensive yacht by another couple they had befriended, and their
bodies were dumped in waters near Palmyra. The woman's skeletal
remains were found six year later after they had washed ashore. The
double murder later became a best selling book, ''And The Sea Will
Tell'', and a made-for-television movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1802 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Push for Patient Rights  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton plans to meet with House and
Senate negotiators next week to discuss the holdup in legislation
that would grant Americans more rights when dealing with health
insurers, administration officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan negotiators who have worked for 10 weeks on a
patient' bill of rights have made some progress in reconciling
differences in legislation passed by both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But the conference committee has yet to tackle thorny questions
about who should be covered by the federal protections and whether
the bill should allow patients to sue health plans for damages they
suffer because they were denied coverage for treatments.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting set for Monday, Clinton wants to help lawmakers
work through their differences and stress that this legislation was
a top priority, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is pushing to give patients that right to sue and is
seeking to extend federal protections to all Americans with private
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are working to combine a House-passed bill, favored
by Clinton, congressional Democrats and some Republicans, with a
Senate-passed bill backed by Republicans that would not expand
rights to sue and would cover fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is concerned that lawmakers have yet to begin
discussions on resolving these differences, said Chris Jennings,
Clinton's health policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to get a status report and talk about time frames and
substance,'' said Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers invited to the meeting include Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla., the conference committee chairman, along with the
co-chairman, Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., and lawmakers from
committees with jurisdiction over health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Osterberg, Nickles' spokeswoman, said he was waiting for
more details from the White House before responding. She stressed
that the committee has been making progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are important decisions that will affect every health
plan in America and the conferees, Republican and Democrat alike,
are taking the time to make sure they do it right,'' said
Osterberg.
</P>
<P>
   Activists complained about the committee's slow progress and
expressed concern that other health care issues, such as
prescription drug coverage and correcting medical mistakes, are
diverting lawmakers' attention.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed some lawmakers returning from a two-week spring break
have said voters are more concerned about getting help paying for
their medicines than reining in HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue has lost focus,'' said John Crosby, executive
director of the American Osteopathic Association. ''They forget
that this is our highest priority''
</P>
<P>
   The two bills at issue have many similarities, including
provisions that would make it easier for patients to see
specialists, give patients the right to appeal to an outside panel
when coverage is denied and allow patients to use out-of-plan
hospitals in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill expands lawsuits and covers all Americans who
have private insurance -- about 161 million people. The Senate bill
does not expand existing rights to sue and covers only those people
whose health plans are exempt from state regulations -- about 55
million.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats contend that state laws are inadequate and that HMOs
should be held liable for care decisions, just as other private
companies can be sued if they are negligent.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, insurers and business groups say Americans with
health plans regulated by states don't need federal protections and
warn that lawsuits will drive up insurance costs, leading companies
to stop offering health benefits to workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1804 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert Outlines Upcoming Strategy  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Speaker Dennis Hastert told fellow
Republicans on Wednesday he hopes to pass several tax cuts in the
next few months while agreeing to compromises on Democratic
priorities such as minimum wage and HMO legislation, party sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Hastert
outlined an ambitious goal of completing work on all 13 annual
spending bills by the end of August. In the past, the last of these
measures has rarely reached the White House until late September or
early October.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert included legislation to provide prescription drug
benefits for the elderly on his agenda, and said he hopes it can
pass the House by early summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois lawmaker addressed fellow House Republicans at
their weekly closed-door meeting, the first since a long spring
break.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP sources said he provided an upbeat assessment of the
majority Republicans' political fortunes. Recent polling indicates
the two parties are at rough parity in support. That represents a
sharp improvement for the GOP from 18 months ago, when they were
reeling from the loss of seats in the mid-term elections and
attempting to recover from the fallout of their impeachment of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are mounting a strong effort to gain the six seats
they need to win a House majority this fall, and routinely charge
Republicans with failing to act on important legislation, the
minimum wage and health bills among them.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Nichols, spokeswoman for House Democratic Leader Dick
Gephardt, said that if the GOP wants compromises on important
bills, ''they have a funny way of showing it.'' She said the
minimum wage and HMO bills are stalled, and on prescription drug
legislation, ''they are late to the game and their proposal is
inadequate. ...They've made no overtures to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In rebuttal, Hastert spokesman John Feehery, said, ''The
Speaker's confident we can have a very successful year.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hastert, House Majority Leader Dick Armey told
Republicans in closed session what he said on Tuesday to reporters:
the leadership hopes to win approval for permanent normalized trade
status for China in the new few weeks, as well as a spate of
measures aimed at supporting the ''new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's remarks amounted to a political playbook for the final
several months of the 106th Congress, and these sources said he
stressed the need to play offense on issues such as taxes, while
playing ''smart defense'' on legislation such as the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts Hastert mentioned include income tax relief from
the so-called ''marriage penalty.'' Legislation on that subject has
passed the House, but is held up in the Senate by Democrats, who
want to force votes on a series of alternative proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the speaker mentioned a reduction in estate taxes,
passed as a companion to the minimum wage increase; a repeal of the
3 percent federal telecommunications tax; and liberalized
contributions to individual retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed a minimum wage measure, and efforts to
fashion a compromise with the Senate have been held up in part by
Democratic objections to a bankruptcy bill.
</P>
<P>
   Both houses have approved legislation to enhance the rights of
patients dealing with their HMOs, but compromise efforts have
sputtered recently.
</P>
<P>
   Neither House has yet tackled a prescription drug measure,
although House Republicans unveiled a proposal earlier this spring,
and Democrats are attempting to unite behind an alternative that
builds on a White House proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1820 </TRAILER>
