<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Cos. Seen As Ripe for Mergers  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-dormant U.S. food companies are suddenly
being appraised like so much fine wine.
</P>
<P>
   An $18.4 billion offer by international food conglomerate
Unilever for Bestfoods, with brands including Skippy peanut butter,
Hellmann's mayonnaise and Knorrs soups, has rekindled interest in
the sleepy U.S. packaged food industry.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were so enthusiastic Wednesday at the proposition of a
wave of food company takeovers that they bid up the stocks of
virtually every well-known U.S. food company.
</P>
<P>
   The surge came despite a broad selloff throughout the rest of
the stock market that saw the Dow Jones industrial average fall
250.99 points.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods' stock benefitted the most, climbing $10.68}, or 21
percent, to close at $61.25 on the New York Stock Exchange. Campell
Soup, up $3.06\ to $29.56\, and ketchup maker H.J. Heinz, up $3.68}
to $37.62{, also saw strong gains. But Unilever's U.S. shares
slipped $2.31\, or 5 percent, to $43.12{.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Unilever's offer means that two of the largest U.S.
food companies are now takeover targets. Nabisco Group Holdings put
itself on the market last month after financier Carl Icahn
announced he was prepared to buy the company, which owns a
controlling stake in the maker of Ritz crackers and Oreo cookies.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Englewood Cliffs, N.J.-based Bestfoods rejected
Unilever's bid of $66 a share, or a 31 percent premium on
Bestfoods' closing price Tuesday, shows that Bestfoods feels it has
strong leverage in any negotiations, analysts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the huge multinational companies that are looking
to expand their markets through acquisitions of smaller companies
know they will need to add strong brand names, similar to those now
owned by companies like Bestfoods, Heinz and Campbell Soup.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need more power brands,'' said Prudential Securities
analyst John McMillin.
</P>
<P>
   That need evidently served as the impetus for Unilever's recent
acquisitions of gourmet ice cream company Ben &AMP; Jerry's for $326
million and diet food company Slim-Fast Foods for $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The global food industry has grappled with slow sales growth for
much of the past decade, said William Leach, an analyst at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, a New York investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, food company executives are under pressure to
expand their markets while at the same time cutting costs. And the
best way to do that is to acquire well-known brand names that can
be sold through existing distribution systems.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor adding to the apparent urgency of large food
companies to purchase smaller ones has been consolidation with in
the retail grocery store sector.
</P>
<P>
   As grocery chains have merged and become larger and stronger,
food companies have realized that they must keep pace, according to
McMillin.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't have your customers getting bigger and bigger and
you're doing nothing,'' he said. ''You're forced to find partners
to gain some scale so you can look them in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   While Unilever's $18.4 billion offer for Bestfoods fits
comfortably into the changing landscape of the food sector,
analysts said the proposal was unique in several respects.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was the largest of its kind for more than a decade,
since the British distiller Grand Metropolitan bought Pillsbury Co.
for $5.8 billion in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Second, $18 billion deals aren't expected to come along every
day since only two companies -- Unilever and Nestle -- can afford to
pay such a high price.
</P>
<P>
   So in the absence of numerous large companies being bought up by
even bigger companies, analysts expect so-called ''mergers among
equals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
