<HEADLINE> Humana Earnings Improve in 1Q  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE SCHREINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Humana Inc. reported improved
first-quarter earnings Wednesday, but fell short of Wall Street's
expectations. Revenue increased 7 percent and the company's new
chief executive predicted a turnaround for the managed health care
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it had net income of $21 million, or 13 cents
per share, for the quarter ending March 31, compared with a loss of
$16 million, or 10 cents per share, for the same period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter showing fell short of analysts' expectations
of 15 cents per share, according to a survey by First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter revenue reached $2.6 billion, the company said.
The increase was due mainly to significant increases in premium
yields, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McCallister, named Humana's president and chief
executive officer earlier this year, said the company was making
strides toward solid profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would like to have seen even more progress during the
quarter,'' said McCallister.
</P>
<P>
   McCallister said that as Humana carries out its business
strategy, he was ''cautiously optimistic'' about new momentum for
the second half of 2000, continuing into next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We remain confident that the steps we are taking -- investments
in infrastructure, ongoing market and product rationalization and
emerging e-health initiatives -- will return Humana to solid growth
rates and improvement in operating results,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Humana Inc. has been trying to regain its footing after losses
incurred a year ago because it underestimated medical care
expenses. The company also has undergone considerable upheaval
since a planned multibillion-dollar merger with United HealthCare
Corp. collapsed in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   David Shove, who follows the managed care industry for
Prudential Securities Inc., said Humana executives ''have a lot of
work to do'' to complete their turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Shove said the disappointing first-quarter numbers underscored
that Humana has a number of unresolved problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems to me that they have a lot of irons in the fire,'' he
said. ''They are trying to fix things at once, and they aren't
getting things fixed as fast as they had hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   Humana said commercial premium yields averaged 11.4 percent for
the first quarter, compared to 6.3 percent for the same period last
year. The company said the increase did cause its commercial
membership to decline 3.4 percent to 2,977,500.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare premium yields rose to 6.2 percent in the first
quarter, compared to 2.1 percent a year ago, Humana said. Medicare
membership increased 29,500, or 6 percent, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's positive. They are getting better pricing,'' Shove
said. ''Some things are improving, but they still have some
Medicare markets that are not performing up to their expectations,
and they have some small-group business that is not performing up
to expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Humana also received an approximate $125 million cash influx at
the end of the first quarter for the sale of its workers'
compensation business. Humana said it expects to use the money to
reduce debt and invest in technology and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville-based Humana is one of the nation's largest publicly
traded managed health care companies, with about 5.9 million
medical members primarily in 15 states and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Humana settled down $1.31\, at $6.68} on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
