<HEADLINE> Congressional Pay Raise Considered  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two top House lawmakers have discussed the
possibility of pursuing a cost-of-living pay raise for members of
Congress this year, but they and others say no final decisions have
been made.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, and Rep. Steny Hoyer,
D-Md., acknowledged Wednesday that they had a brief discussion
about a possible pay raise earlier this year. Many lawmakers are
reluctant to publicly support higher congressional salaries,
particularly in election years, but the two men long have been
vocal supporters of regular increases for legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're simpatico, that's for sure,'' DeLay said of himself and
Hoyer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Congress gave itself a 3.4 percent raise that took
effect this past January, pushing lawmakers' pay to $141,300
annually. Under a formula set by law, the new increase -- which
would take effect next January -- could be no more than about 3
percent, or about $4,200.
</P>
<P>
   This year's increase was the second in the past three years.
Prior to that, the last raise took effect in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1989 law, members of Congress' salaries are
automatically increased each year unless lawmakers specifically
vote to block it. The mechanism is designed to avoid annual,
potentially politically embarrassing salary votes.
</P>
<P>
   That law also established a formula that keeps members' raises
below those received in private industry or by federal workers.
President Clinton has proposed raising federal employees pay next
year by 3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a surplus, we've managed the finances of the country
very well,'' said Hoyer, top Democrat on the House Appropriations
Committee subcommittee that oversees the Treasury. By tradition,
any vote to block the raise occurs as an amendment to that
subcommittee's bill.
</P>
<P>
   The next step will be for leaders of each party to explore
whether the pay raise can be approved without a partisan or
embarrassing battle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We won't do it if one side will try to get the other side,''
Hoyer said.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., and John Feehery,
spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., both said
Gephardt and Hastert have not met to discuss the issue. Such a
trust-building meeting is often held before a final decision on
raising lawmakers' salaries is made.
</P>
<P>
   The 27th Amendment to the Constitution forbids lawmakers from
approving salary increases that take effect before the next
congressional election. This increase, should it occur, would take
effect after the next election, when the 107th Congress begins.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, federal courts have ruled that raises enacted under
the 1989 law do not violate the Constitution because it is that law
-- and not a new act of Congress -- that triggers the pay increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 1846 </TRAILER>
