<HEADLINE> Refugee Agency May Leave Kosovo City  </HEADLINE>
By DANICA KIRKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A U.N. refugee agency threatened on
Wednesday to pull out of a tense ethnically split city in Kosovo
because ''we're not prepared to be sitting ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis McNamara of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, or
UNHCR, issued the warning days after Serb rioters attacked U.N.
workers in the city of Kosovska Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   The northern Kosovo city is one of the few in the overwhelmingly
ethnic Albanian province where many Serbs remain, and a UNHCR
pullout could lead to the exodus of other humanitarian agencies who
follow the refugee group's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Although no UNHCR worker was hurt by the Serb rioters who
pummeled a Kenyan policeman with the U.N. administration, McNamara
said his agency would leave if security fails to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not prepared to be sitting ducks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. administrators and 40,000 NATO-led troops moved into
Kosovo in June after a 78-day NATO bombing campaign forced Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to withdraw his forces, which had
carried out a massive crack down on ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   McNamara planned to meet on Friday with the local Serb leader,
Oliver Ivanovic, before making any recommendations to superiors on
whether to pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic criticized McNamara's warning, calling it a ''a
reckless act that is supposed to blackmail,'' the Serbs, who live
in the northern part of Mitrovica, with the ethnic Albanians in the
south.
</P>
<P>
   ''The security situation in Mitrovica is no worse than elsewhere
in Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Riots and disturbances have broken out frequently in Kosovska
Mitrovica in recent months amid building frustration by Serbs who
reject U.N. and NATO control of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 Kosovo Serbs rallied Wednesday in the tense city
demanding a safe return for Serbs who fled. The city's Serbs massed
on the main square and shouted ''We Want Our Homes.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, UNHCR reported progress on the return of
Kosovo's 30,000 non-Serb minorities, including Roma, or Gypsies,
targeted by ethnic Albanians who accuse them of being Serb allies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
