<DOCNO> APW20000503.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Spent $762,000 on Elian Case  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department has spent more than
$762,000 on the Elian Gonzalez case, including nearly $230,000 on
the April 22 operation that removed him from the home of his Miami
relatives and reunited him with his father here.
</P>
<P>
   The figures released Wednesday cover federal government costs
from the discovery of the 6-year-old Cuban boy off Florida last
Thanksgiving through last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The swift, predawn raid April 22 by heavily armed federal agents
followed by the boy's flight to Washington on a government jet with
medical personnel aboard, all dubbed Operation Reunion, cost
$229,686. That includes overtime, security, travel, transportation
and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 131 Immigration and Naturalization Service agents and
18 U.S. marshals participated, including the Border Patrol's
tactical unit brought by commercial aircraft from El Paso, Texas.
They trained for a week before the raid. The cost of travel for a
Public Health Service flight surgeon and a psychiatrist who
accompanied Elian aboard the flight to Washington was $2,811.
</P>
<P>
   The largest costs were incurred by INS which spent 420,000. The
Marshals Service has spent 299,000.
</P>
<P>
   Private sources are paying the costs for Elian, his father, Juan
Miguel, step mother and infant half brother to stay at the secluded
Wye River Plantation on Maryland's Eastern Shore.
</P>
<P>
   But the INS and marshals have paid to provide security there,
using 58 agents at a cost of more than $168,000 for the first five
days.
</P>
<P>
   The marshals have 18 witness security inspectors and 19 deputy
marshals on duty at Wye River. From April 26 through April 30, the
marshals spent $27,600 for daily travel and transportation expenses
plus $35,100 for overtime and $75,000 for equipment.
</P>
<P>
   INS has 21 agents at Wye, working 12-hour shifts. During the
same period, INS has paid $14,910 in daily travel and
transportation expenses and $15,755 for overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The government also will pay $8,000, including travel, for three
mental health experts brought in to evaluation the Gonzalez family.
</P>
<P>
   It did not pay for Juan Miguel Gonzalez' stay at the home of a
Cuban diplomat in Bethesda, Md., before he was reunited with his
son.
</P>
<P>
   Travel, transcripts and copying for lawyers in U.S. Attorney's
offices and in the department's civil division have come to
$18,000.
</P>
<P>
   The department's Community Relations Service spent $25,000 to
send mediators and conciliators to Miami and to communicate with
them as they helped with negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   There are no figures for the regular salaries for lawyers,
agents, or mediators because the salaries would have been paid
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The federal figures are dwarfed by those incurred by the City of
Miami, which last estimated its costs at $1 million, mostly in
police overtime, but that was before the April 22 raid and the
street disorders that it set off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
