<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Research Deaths Probed  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration was accused
Wednesday of doing too little to protect thousands of people
enrolled in medical research despite warnings two years ago that
the current safeguards were inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to do something to stop the foot-dragging,'' Rep.
John Mica, R-Fla., said at a hearing before the House Government
Reform subcommittee that he heads. ''We'll subpoena the (Health and
Human Services) secretary if we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The HHS inspector general's office warned in 1998 that the local
review boards supposed to oversee clinical tests were overworked.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the inspectors' suggestions have been put into practice,
George Grob, deputy inspector general for evaluations and
inspections, told the subcommittee on criminal justice, drug policy
and human resources.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am disappointed in the lackluster response to the inspector
general's report,'' said Rep. Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The death in September of Jesse Gelsinger, 18, of Tucson, Ariz.,
while undergoing a gene therapy procedure at the University of
Pennsylvania put a new focus on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The intense scrutiny since Gelsinger's death will help change
things, Grob said. ''I think the interest is there now and I expect
to see some changes coming down the pike,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   William Raub, HHS's deputy assistant secretary for science
policy, said officials conducted on-site investigations at 10
institutions between June 1998 and March 2000, compared with only
one on-site investigation the previous 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   Raub also said the number of routine on-site investigations by
the Food and Drug Administration increased from 213 in 1997 to 336
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Department of Health and Human Services is fully committed
to protecting human research subjects,'' Raub said, acknowledging
more needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The subcommittee site:
http://www.house.gov/reform/cj/
</P>
</TEXT>
