<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall on Inflation Pressures  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell sharply on Wednesday amid two
reports showing that inflationary pressures persist despite the
Federal Reserve's attempt to cool the economy with higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the Treasury's 10-year note fell 21/32 point, or
$6.56 per $1,000 in face value. It's yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, rose to 6.39 percent compared with late
Tuesday's rate of 6.30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond fell 1 13/32 points, or $14.06 per $1,000 in
face value. The long-bond's yield rose to 6.11 percent compared
with 6.01 percent a day earlier, according to Bridge Telerate news
service.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the session, the Commerce Department reported that new
orders to American factories rose a bigger-than-expected 2.2
percent, led by the largest jump in demand for electronic equipment
in more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the Federal Reserve issued a report on
regional conditions that said employers may be forced to boost
wages as they scramble to find scarce workers, heightening
pressures to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has boosted interest rates five times since last June in
an effort to slow the economy and keep such pressures in check. But
given the strong growth and tight labor market conditions cited in
Wednesday's report, economists believe the Fed may see no other
choice but to boost rates a few more times in the coming months.
Inflation makes the fixed payoff on bonds less attractive to
investors.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Wednesday, short-term Treasury securities fell
between 5/32 point and [ point while intermediate maturities fell
between 5/16 point and 7/32 point.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were unchanged at 5.90
percent while the discount held steady at 5.74 percent. Six-month
yields finished at 6.21 percent with a discount of 5.95 percent, up
0.01 percentage point. One-year yields slipped to 6.17 percent as
the discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 5.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6.06\ percent compared with late Tuesday's 5.87{
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 17/32 point to 93|. The average yield
to maturity rose to 6.10 percent compared with 6.06 percent a day
earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
