<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves Special Ed Funding  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House agreed Wednesday to live up to a
promise made a quarter-century ago by backing a gradual increase in
federal aid to special education from $5 billion this year to $25
billion in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Full funding for the Individuals With Disabilities Education Act
has been a top priority of Republicans, but the 421-3 vote
reflected strong backing from Democrats as well. The money would
still have to be approved in annual budget bills.
</P>
<P>
   The near unanimous House vote contrasted with a partisan fight
in the Senate, where Republicans used their majority to advance
their own measure governing the federal education effort for grades
K-12 and reject a Democratic alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal includes a provision to give states more
discretion in their use of federal funds, although they would also
be required to demonstrate improved performance. ''If more
decisions are made closer to our students lives by people who know
those students, the quality of their education will improve,'' said
Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said that instead of investing
in proven reforms that work, the Republican bill ''gives a blank
check to the states to conduct business as usual.'' A Democratic
alternative was rejected, 54-45, strictly along party lines. It
would have targeted funds for more teachers and smaller classes.
</P>
<P>
   No final vote is expected until next week at the earliest, and a
fight looms over Democratic efforts to attach a gun control
provision to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The House-passed legislation on special education, which now
goes to the Senate, would authorize spending of $7 billion in
fiscal year 2001 and allow an increase of $2 billion a year until
the figure reaches $25 billion in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   At that level, the federal government would be providing about
40 percent of the extra costs needed to give children with special
needs access to education.
</P>
<P>
   The 1975 law requiring schools to educate children with
disabilities allows the federal government to contribute up to 40
percent of those costs, but it has never come close to that amount,
shifting the cost burden to the states and local school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't put our money where our mouth was,'' said Education
and the Workforce Committee Chairman Bill Goodling, R-Pa., the
chief sponsor. He said that in the past four years the GOP-led
Congress has managed to more than double IDEA funds to $5 billion,
but that still only takes care of 12.6 percent of the national
average of $6,300 a child it takes to educate the 6 million
children with special needs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep, Matthew Martinez, D-Calif., who has promoted similar
legislation, said the Los Angeles unified school district must
spend $891 million a year to educate 81,000 special needs kids. He
said it receives $500 million from the state and $42 million from
the federal government, meaning it must tap into its general
education funds to make up the more than $300 million shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Even with passage of the bill, it still remains for the
Appropriations Committee to actually insert the money in the annual
budgets, and that could be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the difficult work comes in finding appropriations to
meet those levels,'' said Education Department spokeswoman Erica
Lepping. She said the administration supports full funding, ''but
in order to achieve that goal, other important initiatives
shouldn't be jeopardized.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration has argued that priority in education
spending should go to hiring more teachers, reducing class sizes
and rebuilding old and inadequate school structures. Republicans
have countered in the annual budget battles that full federal
financial support for special education would free up states and
local school districts to fund other pressing education needs,
including more teachers and new buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill numbers are H.R. 4055. and S2
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Education Committee site:
http://www.house.gov/ed--workforce
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
