<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean Student To Live on Internet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- A Chilean journalism student sequestered
himself in a house on Wednesday planning to live the next eight
months with only one link to the outside world: the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Enrique Piraces, 23, carried only a sleeping bag, as he moved
into an empty house in the Chilean capital. The other essentials of
apartment life -- a bed, a television set, a microwave oven,
refrigerator, books and food -- he plans to buy over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I think my first purchase will be a heater,'' he said,
referring to the Southern Hemisphere's descending winter. He added:
''I am not afraid as I know I will be able to find everything
through the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Piraces said his eight-month project is in part to test the
''the state of virtual trade in Chile.'' The project is being
sponsored by several local businesses, and his experience will be
broadcast over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Piraces said some sixteen cameras have been installed throughout
the house -- apart from the bathroom -- enabling people to track his
experiences over the Internet as they happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cameras are not to keep watch on me, but to share my
experience with people who might be interested,'' Piraces said
before entering the four-room house.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to leave the house at the end of the year, although
will not abandon his studies during that time -- he plans to do his
schoolwork over the Net, too.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said the experience is unique in Latin America, where
the Internet has only recently began to take hold, although similar
projects have been developed in the United States and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Those entering the Pirace's Internet address will be able to
chat with him, he said, ''and give me their opinions, whatever they
might be.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   www.vivonline.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
