<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aide Questions Arrival of E-Mails  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Dan Burton said Wednesday he doubts the
White House will produce any messages in the e-mail controversy
until well after Election Day, but presidential aides stuck to
their timetable of saying the first e-mails will be turned over as
early as June.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute arose after Burton's staff on the House Government
Reform Committee disclosed that a White House contractor will take
two months longer than expected to complete work on an archive of
hundreds of thousands of e-mails that presidential aides have never
reviewed in connection with various subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor, Eric Duong, told committee staffers April 25
that loading information into an archive won't be finished until
the day before Thanksgiving. The White House originally projected
the material could be searched completely by the end of September.
The cost of the system also has gone up dramatically, to between $8
million to $10 million, Michael Lyle, director of the White House
Office of Administration, told the committee at a hearing. An
earlier White House estimate was $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe we will get'' e-mail ''until after the
election,'' on Nov. 7, Burton told reporters. ''I think they will
run this thing beyond the election. I doubt seriously they will
give us any before Thanksgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   But White House spokesman Jim Kennedy predicted that ''we'll
still be able to search and produce e-mails as early as June and
we'll be able to continue to do so on a rolling basis throughout
the summer and fall. We also expect to do our searches on a
priority basis so that the most important information can be
derived early on.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the White House still needs to establish a priority
list of which material will be searched first. The e-mails are
stored on thousands of back-up tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the rising costs stem from the need for another
contractor to review the work to ensure it is done in a proper
manner and extra hardware and labor to expedite the process.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers want to know why the White House didn't
reveal the e-mail problem in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   White House computer experts say the White House counsel's
office was told of the problem, but presidential aides say the
lawyers thought it was a ''glitch'' that had been corrected. In
fact, incoming e-mails haven't been archived from the summer of
1996 to November 1998. That period covers the Lewinsky and the
campaign fund-raising scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, R-Ind., suggested the White House didn't ask Congress
for money to correct the problem last year because it was trying to
cover up.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did not ask for funds'' to correct the e-mail problem
because ''our singular purpose was Y2K,'' Lyle testified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
