<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Studies Women's Treaty  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mother's Day could be threatened by
international enforcers if the United States ratifies a global
treaty on women's rights, Rep. Christopher Smith contended
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement caused a stir at the House International Relations
Committee, where witnesses urged lawmakers to pass the 20-year-old
U.N. Convention on Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination
Against Women.
</P>
<P>
   One fellow committee member challenged Smith's interpretation of
the treaty and another joked about it.
</P>
<P>
   But it was no laughing matter for an anthropologist and women's
rights activist from Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to get up and slap him,'' Zieba Shorish-Shamley said
later. ''But then I wouldn't be able to come here again.''
</P>
<P>
   Shorish-Shamley was one of three women who never got to tell the
committee Wednesday how systematic discrimination in their
homelands has hurt them. No discrimination victims were scheduled
to testify, so three spoke afterward at a news conference scheduled
by Rep. Lynn Woolsey, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Shorish-Shamley said she lost her 56-year-old sister to cancer
because access to health care is denied to women in Afghanistan,
along with education, jobs, or even the right to leave their homes
unaccompanied by a man.
</P>
<P>
   Meme Akoko of Nigeria said her genitals were cut with an
unsterilized razor blade when she was 3 months old, under a tribal
practice aimed at keeping women sexually faithful to their
husbands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been to many doctors and none have been able to undo
what damage the circumcision has cause,'' she said, adding that an
aunt, younger sister and a cousin died because of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''The brave women ... who tell their personal stories know just
how much ratifying CEDAW will mean to women everywhere,'' Woolsey
said.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty, adopted by the U.N. General Assembly in December
1979, requires that women have equal rights to work, pay, benefits
and safe working conditions and prohibits discrimination against
women in political activities. So far, 165 nations have ratified
it.
</P>
<P>
   At the committee hearing, Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., called
it an ''an absolute embarrassment'' that the United States has not
ratified the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the convention promotes abortion, could override
the U.S. Constitution and could force social engineering by
dictating the roles husbands and wives will have in their own
families.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many countries have come under the scrutiny of CEDAW and been
encouraged, admonished, and even compelled to change their laws,''
said Smith, R-N.J., calling the treaty ''controversial and
fundamentally flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Do our constituents ... really want a group of international
bureaucrats telling them that the day set aside to honor our
mothers must be abolished,'' he said. ''I think not!''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., came in for harsh criticism at the
hearing and the press conference. The chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, Helms for years has refused to
schedule hearings or submit the treaty to the full Senate for a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is trying to stonewall crucial protection for women's
rights around the world,'' Woolsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Helms was not immediately available for comment, but said on
International Women's Day March 8: ''This treaty is not about
opportunities for women -- it's about denigrating motherhood and
undermining the family.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Women's Alliance for Peace and Human Rights in Afghanistan
http://www.wapha.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
