<DOCNO> APW20000503.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Peacekeepers Killed in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leone's rebel leader agreed
Wednesday to free any hostages held by his movement, after dozens
of U.N. peacekeepers and unarmed military observers were seized and
at least seven peacekeepers killed in clashes.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, Revolutionary United Front rebels have captured 50
U.N. workers in three towns in Sierra Leone's interior, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven peacekeepers were killed and three more were injured in
clashes in the central towns of Makeni and Magburaka, U.N.
officials said. The fighting in Magburaka, where the U.N. post came
under heavy attack, ended Wednesday morning, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. mission reported another clash Wednesday in the
northwestern town of Kambia. There were no details, U.N. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The abductions and killings came with the U.N. peacekeeping
force taking charge of security in the country, which has been
wracked by years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel leader Foday Sankoh -- in an agreement signed Wednesday
after meeting with Nigerian National Security Adviser Alieu
Mohammed and read on state radio and television -- pledged to ''to
release any hostages if held'' by his group.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Sankoh also said he would continue with
dialogue about the peace process, allow freedom of movement by U.N.
peacekeepers, humanitarian workers and civilians in all the areas
formerly under RUF control, and to work toward disarmament based on
the July peace accord that ended eight years of fighing in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   But Sankoh has repeatedly made similar promises in the past, and
it was unclear exactly when the U.N. hostages -- who he did not
directly acknowledge were held by the RUF -- would be freed.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of U.N. peacekeepers surrounded Sankoh's home in Freetown
while negotiations continued for the release of the hostages, U.N.
officials said. Officials denied they were planning to arrest
Sankoh, saying they wanted to make sure he was available for
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The 8,500-member U.N. force was dispatched to replace a West
African intervention force, known as ECOMOG, that defended the
government during the civil war. The last ECOMOG troops left the
capital, Freetown, this week.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the increasing violence, U.N. Security Council
members and countries that contributed troops to the U.N. mission
in Sierra Leone on were discussing increasing the size of the force
closer to its authorized strength of 11,100, U.N. and diplomatic
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The council and Secretary-General Kofi Annan both condemned the
deaths of the peacekeepers, and laid the blame on Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who was in Paris Wednesday night, said that several
African heads of state were sending envoys ''to put pressure on him
(Sankoh) to pull his men back so that peacekeepers can do their
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan said that the situation was not ''encouraging'' for future
U.N. missions in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, we need to reassess after this incident ... what
changes in attitude, what changes in our relationship with him
(Sankoh) and others have to be made,'' Annan told Associated Press
Television News.
</P>
<P>
   He added that ''We went into this realizing there will be risks
... but I hope we will be able to ... continue our work.''
</P>
<P>
   United States officials suggested Wednesday that Sankoh be
declared a war criminal, which would enable U.N. peacekeepers to
arrest and detain him. There was no indication, however, that the
United Nations supported that move.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
the actions by the rebels violated the peace accords meant to end
the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States condemns these actions in the strongest
possible terms,'' Boucher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
