<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foe of class-actions defends proposed diet-drug settlement  </HEADLINE>
By BILL BERGSTROM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A Columbia University law professor who
often criticizes class actions defended a proposed $3.75 billion
national settlement of health claims against the diet drug
combination fen-phen, saying Wednesday it would be likely to
benefit those claiming injuries from the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a case where my usual criticisms do not apply,'' John
C. Coffee said in documents filed with U.S. District Judge Louis
Bechtle.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee testified Wednesday that there are marked differences
between the diet drug case and other settlements which he has
opposed, particularly a large asbestos settlement involving Amchem
Products Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He said that unlike potential victims of asbestos exposure,
those who took the diet drugs Pondimin or Redux, the ''fen''
portion of the so-called fen-phen combination, did so under
doctors' prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   They were aware of their exposure, and in many cases have
undergone tests to determine the likelihood of ill effects, Coffee
said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence with the diet drugs of the ''latency''
effect of asbestos exposure, in which victims may not be aware they
have been exposed and may not develop symptoms for 30 years or
more, said Coffee, whose arguments were cited by the U.S. Supreme
Court in rejecting the Amchem settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the proposed diet-drug settlement avoids the problem of
potential future claims that could not be accurately anticipated in
the asbestos case, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a much tighter, less sprawling, less amorphous
class,'' Coffee said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 9,000 lawsuits were filed in connection with the
drugs, which were taken off the market by American Home Products
Corp.'s Wyeth-Ayerst division in St. Davids, Pa., in September 1997
after a Mayo Clinic study linked the combination to potentially
fatal heart valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   Bechtle tentatively approved the settlement in November, and is
hearing arguments from attorneys for Madison, N.J.-based American
Home Products and patients who took the drugs. He is expected to
decide this summer whether the settlement will stand.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee said other provisions he favored included provisions that
allow claimants to opt out of the agreement at three separate
stages without losing rights to pursue litigation against the drug
maker on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement provides for those injured by the drugs to
receive payments ranging from about $37,000 up to $1.5 million, but
Coffee noted that those who accept less than the maximum would have
the right to later seek more money if their condition becomes
worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 2012 </TRAILER>
