<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rabbi's lawyer demands reporter's notes of interview with slayingsuspect  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Lawyers for a rabbi accused of arranging
his wife's killing subpoenaed the notes Wednesday of a newspaper
reporter who said she witnessed the confession of the middleman in
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Dennis Wixted said he wants all notes and records kept by
Philadelphia Inquirer reporter Nancy Phillips during interviews
over the years about the 1994 killing.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips ''crossed the line'' when she talked to Leonard Jenoff
and allowed the prosecutor and a homicide investigator to join the
conversation at a diner, Wixted said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper plans to fight the subpoena, said Phillip Dixon, a
deputy managing editor. Any additional information that Phillips
has about the case will be reported in the paper, Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a reporter provides information in a criminal case, either
at the behest of the prosecution or defense, the reporter runs the
risk as being perceived as partisan to the side that benefits from
the information,'' Dixon said. ''We believe that undermines the
free flow of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Wixted said he personally served Phillips with the subpoena when
she arrived at his office Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the prosecutor must by law turn over to the defense a
summary of the interview with Jenoff, but Phillips is under no
requirement, thus the need for the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a witness. We don't know whether she entreated him or
encouraged him or what,'' Wixted said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff said Rabbi Fred Neulander offered him $30,000 to hire
someone to kill 52-year-old Carol Neulander, according to Phillips'
account in Tuesday's newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The confession was made Friday. Jenoff, 54, and Paul Michael
Daniels, 26, were arrested Monday in the Nov. 1, 1994, beating
death.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, who had been the only person charged, faced a trial
next month. The trial has been postponed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, a private investigator who had been counseled by
Neulander for his own marital problems, was in a car with Phillips
to visit a location that he said was essential to the story, the
Inquirer reported Wednesday. Instead, Jenoff asked Phillips if they
could meet with Camden County prosecutor Lee Solomon because he had
something to say.
</P>
<P>
   The three, along with homicide detective Martin Devlin, went to
a New Jersey diner, where Jenoff confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff said the rabbi offered him the money to kill a person he
claimed was an enemy of Israel, the newspaper reported Tuesday.
Jenoff said the rabbi told him he could get him a job with Israel's
secret service if he pulled off the murder, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff's lawyer, Francis Hartman, said his client was haunted by
what had happened and felt compelled to confess.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was something that was eating at him. The trial is coming
up and the thought occurred to him that the rabbi might be
acquitted and that might be a terrible thing,'' Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels has also confessed, prosecutors say. Jenoff was being
held on $200,000 bail. Bail for Daniels was $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi's lawyer said Phillips became much more than a
reporter working on the story when she called the prosecutor to
join the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips ''was not a reporter any more'' when she arranged the
interview and held off on reporting the story, Wixted said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, 57, who founded what became the largest synagogue in
Cherry Hill, was long suspected in the killing but was not charged
until 1998. He resigned three months after his wife's death, after
reports surfaced about two extramarital affairs with members of his
congregation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 2012 </TRAILER>
