<HEADLINE> Man Cleared in Rapper's Murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A mortgage broker has been cleared of
suspicion in the killing of rap artist Notorious B.I.G.,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Amir Muhammad said he learned in December that he had been a
suspect when he read a Los Angeles Times article that cited
confidential police documents.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Martin, the detective in charge of the case, said Tuesday:
''We are not pursuing that theory and have not been for more than a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times article included Muhammad's driver's license
photograph. Muhammad said he spent days hiding in his home for fear
an angry rap fan might seek revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Notorious B.I.G., 24, who real name was Christopher Wallace, was
gunned down outside a Los Angeles museum on March 9, 1997. No
arrests have been made.
</P>
<P>
   The Times had reported that police were investigating whether
Muhammad was paid to shoot Wallace by rival rap mogul Marion
''Suge'' Knight and Muhammad's former college roommate, David A.
Mack.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, a former police officer, is now in prison for bank
robbery. Knight is serving nine years for a 1992 attack on two
rappers in a recording studio.
</P>
</TEXT>
