<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest fire threatens housing developments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MEDFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Firefighters in southern New Jersey managed
to contain a forest fire that threatened housing developments in
Medford and Shamong townships Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The fire broke out shortly after 6 p.m. in a wooded area between
Quail Ridge Court in Medford and Bunker Hill Road in Shamong.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had considered evacuating the 25-unit Woodside
development in Shamong, but were able to bring the fire under
control before that became necessary, said Bert Plante, the state
Forest Fire Service's assistant warden.
</P>
<P>
   The fire burned about 20 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Fire Service had four pumpers at the scene and one
tractor-plow to help fight the fire, along with volunteer
firefighters from six Burlington County departments.
</P>
<P>
   Additional manpower was being rushed to the fire scene, and
small ''backfires'' were being set along the perimeter of the fire
in order to deprive it of fuel it needs to spread.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was centered on an old cranberry bog, making it
difficult for firefighters to reach it, Plante said.
</P>
<P>
   But winds in the area were light, which assisted firefighters in
bringing it under control.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
