<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Baseball Game Notes  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees-Indians:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Derek Jeter singled in the first inning of Wednesday
night's game and has reached base in 25 of 26 games and hit safely
in 21. ... 2B Chuck Knoblauch missed his second straight game with
a sprained left hand and wrist. Manager Joe Torre said Knoblauch
would be examined again on Thursday and a decision about placing
him on the DL would be made Friday. Knoblauch went 1-for-16 before
Torre decided to sit him. ... Torre said the key to the success of
New York's bullpen has been the pitching of Jeff Nelson and Mike
Stanton. Nelson has not allowed a run in his last five appearances
(6 1-3 innings) and Stanton has pitched seven straight scoreless
innings. ''We get to the seventh inning and we really don't
consider anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Manager Charlie Manuel said Roberto Alomar, who
entered the game in a 2-for-19 slump, has a sore left elbow. Manuel
wanted to rest Alomar for Wednesday's game, but the All-Star second
baseman insisted on playing. ''He keeps telling me he's fine,''
Manuel said. ''But his timing isn't there right now and he's not
getting good swings.'' ... RHP Charles Nagy was fined for his
involvement in Sunday's brushback war with Boston. ... Catcher
Sandy Alomar left for Florida where he will join the team's
extended spring program. Alomar, who has been on the DL since April
18 with a pulled hamstring, will join the Indians in Minnesota on
Sunday.
Angels-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: SS Gary DiSarcina was not in the starting lineup with
tightness in his right shoulder. ... RHP Troy Percival, the
normally dominating closer who blew a save in the Angels' 7-6 loss
to Baltimore on Tuesday, is 0-4 with a 6.08 ERA lifetime versus
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: 1B Will Clark was placed on the 15-day DL with a
strained left hamstring. ... The Orioles recalled INF Ryan Minor
from Triple-A Rochester, where he was hitting .265 with five homers
and 17 RBIs. ... RHP Tim Worrell, who had been designated for
assignment when the Orioles claimed INF Mark Lewis from Cincinnati
last week, was waived.
Tigers-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: The Tigers were without manager Phil Garner and third
baseman Dean Palmer, who are serving eight-game suspensions for an
April 22 brawl in Chicago. ... Juan Encarnacion extended his
hitting streak to 15 games with a first-inning single. He is
5-for-7 against Pete Schourek in his career. ... The Tigers won
coming from behind after the seventh inning once all last year.
They have already done it twice this year. ... After not facing a
lefty in their first 12 games, Detroit has faced six in their last
13 games.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Pedro Martinez was suspended for five games and fined
for plunking Roberto Alomar on Sunday. Martinez will appeal the
suspension, and he will be able to pitch until the appeal is heard.
... With his second-inning homer, Mike Stanley has four homers in
his last five games.
Rangers-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: DH Rafael Palmeiro was scratched from the lineup because
of tightness in his left hamstring. ... It could be a couple of
days before a decision is made on whether OF Gabe Kapler will go on
the DL with a strained right hip flexor. ... Jason McDonald
replaced Kapler in the lineup Wednesday night ... LHP Justin
Thompson, recovering from shoulder surgery, threw for 20 minutes in
the bullpen and didn't report any soreness. ... OF Rusty Greer, who
had arthroscopic surgery April 26 to remove bone spurs from the
front of his right ankle, has been running in the outfield and
batting off a tee. He could be ready to return in a couple of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: SS Kevin Stocker was not in the lineup after being
hit by a pitch on the right calf by Rick Helling on Tuesday. He was
replaced by Ozzie Guillen, but could be ready to return Thursday.
... The Devil Rays organization and Dwight Gooden will deliver
supplies and a cash donation Thursday to the Belmont Heights Little
League in Tampa. The youth group's baseball complex lost about
$5,000 worth of supplies, food and baseball equipment in a burglary
last weekend. Gooden, Gary Sheffield and Derek Bell are major
leaguers who once played for Belmont Heights.
Athletics-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Dan Glass, son of new owner David Glass, was
walking around the stadium before the game meeting people. The new
club president this week and already is discussing ideas of
improving the stadium, including installing a picnic pavilion
behind the Royals' bullpen. He dismissed any suggestion that the
Glass family has long-range plans to move the team out of Kansas
City. ''This team will be here forever,'' he said. ...
Right-fielder Jermaine Dye was named the AL's player of the month
after hitting .388 with 28 RBIs and leading the league in home runs
(11) and doubles (12).
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: RHP Kevin Appier, who has been nursing a strained right
forearm, is due to come off the DL next Wednesday. But the A's do
not expect him to pitch that day against Anaheim, figuring he will
take a few more days to get ready. ... The A's had a group of fans
from Russia. Twenty-eight members of the touring Russian national
team were in the stands and most seemed to be fans of the A's.
''There are many players on the A's that our players like very
much,'' said Andrei Artamonov, commissioner of the Russian Baseball
Federation.
Blue Jays-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays 6.42 ERA .42 in April was the highest for
any month in team history. The previous was 6.04 in April, 1996.
... Blue Jays closer Billy Koch is another successful survivor of
''Tommy John'' ligament replacement surgery. After appearing in
just three minor league games in 1997, Koch blew out his elbow. He
came back one year and a day after the surgery, won 14 games in the
minors and then made the majors the following season. Dr. James
Andrews, who did the surgery on the Cubs' Kerry Wood, performed the
operation. ''I just had a great surgery. It didn't affect my arm
angle or my mechanics,'' said Koch, whose fastball this season has
been clocked at 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Manager Jerry Manuel served the sixth of an eight-game
suspension as punishment for a brawl with Detroit last month.
Manuel is keeping his whereabouts during the games a secret until
after his sentence is over. ''It's been difficult,'' he said. ''I
didn't realize it would be as tough. I guess the length of it is
what is frustrating.'' ... The White Sox are averaging one error a
game. SS Jose Valentin made 11 in the first 24 games, including
four in one contest. ... The White Sox play an exhibition game
Thursday night against their Class AA affiliate at Birmingham,
Ala., then begin a six-game trip to Kansas City and Boston.
Mariners-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: The Mariners have used 23 lineups in their first 24
games. ... Seattle has not lost a season series against Minnesota
in seven years under manager Lou Piniella. ... Seattle pinch
hitters entered Wednesday hitting just .125 (2-for-16) with no
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Twins lefty J.C. Romero, out since spring training
because of a strain in his pitching shoulder, started a 30-day
rehabilitation assignment at Class A Fort Myers. ... Twins
president Jerry Bell traveled to Milwaukee on Tuesday to meet with
commissioner Bud Selig and discuss realignment. Minnesota is not
pleased with the league's proposal of putting six teams in the
Central Division and four in both the East and the West.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Reds-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Deion Sanders agreed to a 10-day rehab assignment
extension at Triple-A Louisville through May 11. He has three
homers and eight steals in 18 games. ... The Reds are 2-0 in the
only two games in which their projected opening day lineup has
played. Sean Casey opened the season on the DL and Barry Larkin was
injured two games after Casey's return.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Terry Francona flip-flopped Ron Gant and Mickey
Morandini in the batting order after just one game. Gant returned
to the No. 2 spot in the order and Morandini dropped back to No. 7.
... The Phillies have faced their opponent's ace in each of their
nine series this season. ... The Phillies haven't beaten the Reds
in a series since taking two of three in Cincinnati in September
1998.
Astros-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Jeff Bagwell may have a gaudy batting average, but he
gets in slumps just like everybody else. He was 0-for-13 until his
single in the ninth inning Wednesday. ''I've had three bad games,
but this early in the season, it makes it look like 40 games,''
said Bagwell, who is hitting .319. ''But I'd rather go 0-for-5 and
get the win than get that single in the ninth.'' ... Jose Lima,
shelled for nine runs and 13 hits Tuesday by the Cubs, didn't hold
it against their fans. He sat on top of the Astros' dugout signing
autographs before the game, turning around at one point to sit with
the crowd of fans waiting for his signature. ... Richard Hidalgo
was 0-for-5 this series before hitting a solo homer, his seventh
this season, in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: When Mark Grace crossed home plate in the first inning,
driven in by Henry Rodriguez's double, it was his 1,000th career
run scored. He's the eighth Cub to reach the milestone. ''I've
scored 1,000 more runs than I was supposed to,'' said Grace, a
24th-round pick in 1985. ''I've really exceeded everybody's
expectations. Including mine.'' ... Almost lost among the Kerry
Wood hoopla is the return of Ismael Valdes, who's been on the DL
all season with tendinitis in his shoulder. Valdes is scheduled to
start Thursday. ''I'll probably look at him the same way as Kerry,
maybe 20 pitches less,'' manager Don Baylor said. ''Just take it
for five innings or whatever he can do, bring him along maybe a
step behind Kerry.'' ... The Cubs have beaten the Astros four
straight times, the most since winning four in a row at the end of
the 1991 season and beginning of 1992.
Diamondbacks-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Steve Finley, who hit two homers in Monday's 5-1
victory in Milwaukee, raised his average to .330. But he's hitting
.395 at County Stadium, including 10-for-18 with 13 RBI in his last
four games in Milwaukee. ... In its last 37 road games in 1999,
Arizona was 29-8; thus, the team is 38-12 in its last 50 away from
home.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Manager Davey Lopes celebrated his 55th birthday.
''I'm just thankful that I'm still healthy,'' Lopes said. ... With
his offense struggling, Lopes started Sean Berry at third base
against Arizona. Berry is batting .118 (2-for-17). ''You've got to
try something,'' said Lopes, whose team batting average of .231 is
ahead of only Philadelphia (.226) in the majors. ... LHP Matt
Williams cleared waivers and had to be offered back to the Yankees,
who claimed him for $25,000. That's half what the Brewers paid the
Yankees to obtain him as a Rule 5 player. ''I still think he's
capable of doing a good job,'' Lopes said. ... The Brewers sent P
Ray King to Indianapolis to make room for P Horacio Estrada, who
was 2-1 with a 2.67 ERA in five starts at Indianapolis.
Pirates-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: The six-run eighth inning Tuesday matched the team's
season high, also done April 7 at Arizona. ... The Pirates were
6-for-17 with runners in scoring position Tuesday, ending a
1-for-29 slide. ... Pirates pitchers had allowed a league-low 20
homers before giving up four Tuesday. ''Like I said, we were going
to silence their home run bats,'' manager Gene Lamont joked. ... In
the first 10 road games, Pirates starters did not have a single
1-2-3 first inning. Jason Schmidt gave up a two-run home run to
Mark McGwire in the first Tuesday. ''He didn't hit 70 home runs for
nothing,'' Schmidt said. ''He got it up in the air, and when he
does that, it's going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Pitcher Matt Morris, out since April 1998 due to
elbow surgery, will make his second rehab start for Double-A
Arkansas Sunday at Little Rock. He threw 55 pitches Tuesday and
will be at that same pitch count in the second start. ''I like the
way my curve and changeup are coming along,'' Morris said. The
Cardinals expect to active him in June. ... The Cardinals'
two-error game Tuesday matched their season high. ... Mark McGwire
entered the game with 531 career homers in 5,705 at-bats. Jimmie
Foxx, who's in ninth place with 534 homers, had 8,134 at-bats. ...
Half of Shawon Dunston's six hits are home runs. ... Backup catcher
Eli Marrero has two stolen bases, both as a pinch runner.
Expos-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: OF Rondell White did not play Wednesday and may not
return until Saturday because of a sore left knee. He has been
playing in pain since being hit by a pitch April 20. .... The Expos
optioned RHP Jeremy Powell and RHP Brad Rigby to Triple-A Ottawa
and replaced them with RHP Mike Johnson and RHP Felipe Lira. ...
LHP Graeme Lloyd was placed on the 60-day DL. He is scheduled to
have surgery on his left shoulder Friday. ... OF Vladimir Guerrero
was named NL Player of the Month on Wednesday after hitting .410
with eight homers and 27 RBIs in April. ... C Chris Widger returned
to the lineup after missing Tuesday's game with soreness between
his left thumb and index finger. He went 0-for-2. ... The 24 hits
allowed by the Expos on Wednesday broke a 29-year-old team record
for an opponent. The Cincinnati Reds had 23 hits against Montreal
on June 29, 1971. ... Montreal's team ERA jumped to 5.29 from 4.15
in three games against the Rockies.
</P>
