<HEADLINE> MSU's 'Flintstones' Celebrate  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA R. MOSES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- Waving green-and-white pompoms, hundreds
gathered Wednesday to cheer the Michigan State players who put
their hometown on the basketball map.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a wild ride,'' Spartans guard Charlie Bell said at
the homecoming celebration honoring him and national championship
teammates Mateen Cleaves and Morris Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Flint Mayor Woodrow Stanley unveiled banners bearing their names
that will hang in the IMA Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ''We salute you and we salute Michigan State University,''
Stanley said as a band played the school's fight song.
</P>
<P>
   The trio, known as the ''Flintstones,'' combined for 48 points,
14 assists and 12 rebounds as Michigan State beat Florida 89-76 on
April 3 to win the school's first national championship in 21
years.
</P>
<P>
   Spartans coach Tom Izzo was recognized as an honorary
''Flintstone'' in the Greater Flint Area Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo praised each player, saying ''These guys, you should be
proud. ... They worked harder than any players I've coached and
I've coached a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Each player also thanked his family and presented a bouquet of
flowers to his mother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
