<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate budget committee scowls at budget cut for parks  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Members of the Senate budget committee
balked Wednesday at the Department of Environmental Protection's
plan to cut $4 million from its budget for maintaining state parks.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, $10.4 million of the department's $416 million budget
is allocated for maintenance projects at state parks.
</P>
<P>
   Department Commissioner Robert Shinn spoke of the cut during his
presentation to the committee on the department's spending plan.
Lawmakers are reviewing the various agencies to be funded in Gov.
Christie Whitman's $21.3 billion budget for the 2000-2001 fiscal
year beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Littell, R-Sussex, the committee chairman, reminded
Shinn that state parks need to be maintained before the department
embarks on any bold open-space preservation program to buy more.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are actively buying land, a lot of (it) has buildings on
it, and we can't take care of what we have,'' Littell said.
</P>
<P>
   Shinn acknowledged that many open-space acquisitions ''do
increase the responsibility for staffing and maintenance.'' He told
Littell he would discuss the park appropriation with Treasury
department officials, who design the overall budget.
</P>
<P>
   But Littell said either way, he will see to it himself by
proposing to amend Whitman's budget bill to replace the $4 million
cut and perhaps to add more.
</P>
<P>
   ''Otherwise, we should never buy another acre of land,'' Littell
said. ''It is frustrating. I thought we went all through this one
time (last year) and made it clear this was a priority of the
Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   If Littell succeeds, the Department of Environmental Protection
would still be short of the $16 million-per-year goal for annual
maintenance work recommended in a 1998 report by the Council on New
Jersey Outdoors, a panel Whitman created by Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   The report found a $160 million backlog of maintenance projects
over 10 years that left natural resources unused or underused, and
threatened historic structures with ruin, like the recently
demolished High Point tower in Sussex County. The historic tower
once provided a vantage of three states.
</P>
<P>
   ''How are we ever going to catch up,'' asked Littell.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Sierra Club Director Jeff Tittel said park neglect
''has been a real disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What I can't understand, at a time of record budget surpluses
... is that we're nickle-and-diming our parks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All six senators at the meeting raised the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''If every legislator is talking about it, I have to be
sensitive to it, aside from the need,'' Shinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Also during his presentation, Shinn said the department has made
progress in reducing air pollution, improving water quality in
lakes and streams, and formulating ambitious plans to regulate
pollution and development according to their effect on regional
watersheds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
