<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers rush toward midnight deadline  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Rushing toward a midnight deadline, the
General Assembly on Wednesday passed a $12.3 billion budget that
includes $171 million in new tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also approved a $270 million bonding package that
includes money for the University of Connecticut and the state's
public university system. It passed the Senate on a unanimous vote,
and the House on a 138-12 vote after an hour of debate.
</P>
<P>
   The tax and spending plan caps a 12-week legislative session
that focused on governmental reform, and a major riverfront
development for the capital city.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature passed bills to abolish the state's sheriff
system, revamp the treasurer's office and reform Connecticut's
campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland signed the sheriff and treasurer reform
bills, but has not said whether he will make the campaign finance
measure law.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has already signed legislation to use $455 million
of state money to build Adriaen's Landing in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes a 700-room hotel, a convention center,
entertainment and retail space and nearly 400 housing units. Also
planned is a $90 million stadium in East Hartford for the
University of Connecticut. The development is expected to create
about 3,400 construction jobs and more than 1,100 permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new state budget, motorists will get a 7-cent
reduction in the gas tax and shoppers will have more money in their
pockets after buying clothes.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Wednesday afternoon, it did not look like parents who
send their children to private elementary and secondary schools
would get the tuition tax credit that Gov. John G. Rowland was
pushing for. Leading Democratic lawmakers blocked the $500 credits
from the budget, and Republicans had not tacked the measure on a
separate bill.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also includes $75 million in tax breaks to the
state's hospitals and $54 million in tax cuts for industry, of
which $15 million goes to Bristol-based ESPN. The sports
broadcasting giant is planning a $500 million expansion of its
world headquarters that could mean up to 1,000 new jobs in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Warburg Dillon Read, the former Swiss Bank based in Stamford, is
getting $157 million in loans and tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the major tax breaks, the Legislature showed it's
sweet side to candy lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday night, the Senate slipped in a $200,000 tax
exemption for items sold through vending machines for 50 cents or
less, such as gum balls.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Belden, R-Shelton, called the cut ''frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is $200,000 worth of revenue that disappears, that we
won't have to spend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Anne McDonald, D-Stamford, said there wasn't enough time
left to whittle the so-called ''rat'' out of the tax package.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you have to swallow hard and accept something you
really don't like,'' she said. ''We cannot at this time send this
whole package back to the senate over gum ball machines.''
</P>
<P>
   The $12.3 billion budget is about $150 million more than what
the Legislature agreed to spend last year for the 2001 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $40 million of the increase is going to new programs; the
rest is needed to make inflation adjustments and cover agencies and
programs running in the red.
</P>
<P>
   About $3 million is slated for beefing up the state's three
juvenile detention facilities in Bridgeport, Hartford and New
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Another $4.4 million is earmarked to ease prison overcrowding by
creating more treatment programs. Since last year, 484 Connecticut
inmates have been transferred to a Virginia prison to thin the
state's prison population.
</P>
<P>
   About $1.5 million is being used to expand eligibility
requirement for the state's ConnPACE prescription drug program.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the budget expenditures, lawmakers doled out $250 of
the state's surplus money.
</P>
<P>
   About $20 million of that is earmarked for a bailout of
deficit-plagued University of Connecticut Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   Another $34 million of the surplus would be given to towns in
one-shot grants. Municipalities would be able to decide how best to
use the grant money, which ranges from $22,000 for Union to $3.3
million for New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus also will sink $43 million into school construction
and $10 million into getting classrooms wired for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also has a Democratic-backed measure that pushes the
clothing tax exemption from $50 to $75. In return, the GOP won a
one week-long sales tax exemption on clothing priced up to $300.
</P>
<P>
   The gas tax cut is expected to save $85 to $140 a year for a
family that drives 30,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.3 billion budget stays about $51 million under the
state's mandatory spending cap. But expenditure of the surplus
breaks the spending cap by about $200 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-03-00 2130 </TRAILER>
