<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Nuke Treaty Changes Denounced  </HEADLINE>
By DAFNA LINZER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The former U.S. government official who
leaked the Pentagon Papers sharply criticized proposed U.S. changes
to the Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty and warned Wednesday that it
would put the world in danger.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. efforts to change the treaty to build a limited missile
defense would encourage an arms race with Russia at a time when the
former Soviet Union's nuclear forces are ''vulnerable and
accident-prone,'' Daniel Ellsberg told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke at the United Nations on Wednesday where meetings were
continuing on the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty. Joined by the
mayor of Hiroshima and the deputy mayor of Nagasaki, Ellsberg said
current discussions on weapons programs demonstrated that the world
had forgotten lessons learned after the atomic bombings of the two
Japanese cities in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the current policies of my country, and other weapons
states, there is no assurance whatever that the crime and error
will not be repeated,'' said Ellsberg, a former U.S. nuclear war
planner.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants Russia to clear a legal path for a
limited missile defense system to shield the United States from an
attack from ''rogue'' states such as North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The move would require modifying the 1972 U.S.-Soviet
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. Russia so far has refused, warning
that changes could touch off an arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsberg said the changes would encourage Russia to resume
stockpiling weapons and return missile warheads to a state of
alert.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is considering a limited missile defense, but
many conservative Republicans in the U.S. Congress would go further
by scrapping the pact and proceeding with a space-based weapons
program.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to advance a domestic political agenda ... the U.S.
is encouraging the Russians to remain on and advance a
launch-on-warning system,'' Ellsberg said, explaining that a new
American program would force Russia to devise new deterrents.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the U.N. conference to establish a strong disarmament
agenda over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsberg joined the U.S. Defense Department in 1964 and then
worked for the State Department. Outraged by U.S. policies in
Vietnam, he copied a classified 47-volume study of the U.S. role in
Indochina and gave it to The New York Times, which published the
so-called Pentagon Papers in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Ellsberg, who is based in Washington, has been
an activist against nuclear proliferation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
