<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Runner en Route to Colombia  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The British man trying to become the
first person to run the length of each of the Earth's continents
left the Venezuelan capital Wednesday for Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   After a one-month rest in Caracas, during which he acquired a
new girlfriend and stocked up on new clothes and camera equipment,
33-year-old Robert Garside took off from a midtown square for what
he expects to be an eight-day journey to the Colombian border.
</P>
<P>
   He spent much of his time in Caracas trying to get safety
assurances from armed groups in Colombia, where a Russian cyclist
on a similar round-the-world mission was murdered four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm probably not going to get any armed protection,'' he told
The Associated Press from a cell phone. ''I'm going to keep it nice
and simple. Just smile and be friendly because I don't know what
else is going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Garside, who calls himself The Running Man on his Web site, has
already run across Australia, Asia and Europe and the length of
South America in a three-year journey that has taken him more than
20,000 miles and earned him the world record in long-distance
running.
</P>
<P>
   To complete his goal, Garside must still run across North
America, Africa and Antarctica. He aims to accomplish that within
two years.
</P>
<P>
   But to get to Central America, he must first run through
northern Colombia, where leftist rebels, right-wing paramilitary
death squads and drug runners control huge swaths of territory.
</P>
<P>
   Garside said he has received two assurances by telephone from
rebels of Colombia's National Liberation Army that he would be safe
in the northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Since setting off from set London's Piccadilly Circus of Dec. 7,
1996, the former psychology student has dodged bullets in Russia,
got robbed in Brazil, collapsed from heat exhaustion in Australia
and went to jail in China.
</P>
<P>
   While running, Garside films himself every 90 minutes or so to
prove he's actually running, and also collects receipts and witness
statements along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Garside broke the world long-distance running record in
September 1998 in Australia, where he eclipsed the old mark of
11,134 miles held by American Sarah Lovington-Fulcher.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying a 15-pound backpack, Garside runs to the music of
Pavarotti, Beethoven, Dire Straits and Enya.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid being classified as a walker, he must maintain an
average speed of 6 mph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
