<DOCNO> APW20000503.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Williams Visits Team Before Surgery  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- On the eve of surgery to repair an aneurysm
near his right armpit, pitcher Woody Williams came to the ballpark,
put on his uniform, hung out around the batting cage and sat in the
dugout with his San Diego Padres teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He figured it was the least he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ''After all the support they showed last night and the phone
calls and thoughts and prayers that had been given on their part, I
just wanted to come and show my support back to them,'' Williams
said Wednesday before the Padres played the Florida Marlins. ''It's
hard for me to stay away. It was real hard watching the game on TV
last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams had gone home from the hospital on Tuesday after an
angiogram revealed the aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   The most emotional part for Williams was seeing his jersey
hanging in the dugout, placed there by his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no idea that I meant so much to so many people. It made
me feel good,'' said Williams, who pitched 8 1-3 innings in a loss
to Florida on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he received a phone message from catcher Carlos
Hernandez that was so touching that he's not going to erase it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted to make him feel better because I know in this
time, he needs that,'' said Hernandez, who missed all of 1999 after
rupturing his left Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Williams will have surgery Thursday morning and could be
sidelined for up to four months.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres say Williams' situation is similar to when New York
Yankees pitcher David Cone had an aneurysm in his right shoulder in
1996, sidelining him for four months.
</P>
<P>
   Cone and Williams were teammates in Toronto, and Cone called
Williams on Tuesday while he was still at the hospital, to
encourage him. Williams said he was having a hard time dealing with
the news when he got the call.
</P>
<P>
   ''When David called me, it kind of made me realize that
everything's going to be OK,'' Williams said. ''I just hope that
I'm no worse off than he was. I'm very positive and optimistic that
I'll be back. It may not be this year, it may be. I'm going to do
everything I possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had performed tests during the weekend, one of which
showed a small blood clot had reached Williams' right forearm.
Another test showed that the circulation in his hand was fine, and
the team's medical staff felt any risk from him pitching Monday
night was relatively low.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he was disheartened when he heard he had an
aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the same time, they say if I kept pitching, there's a
chance I could have lost my hand. My family's everything to me and
I'm just thankful they caught it when they did. Regardless of what
happens on the field, or if I ever get back, I can still play with
my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said his wrist was sore and a little red after his
first start on April 5, and that his fingers started getting numb
and cold during his second start. He felt better during his third
start. ''The last three were pretty hard to get through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams felt the symptoms only when he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said everytime I raise my arm up, the aneurysm would act
kind of like a tube of toothpaste. Everytime I raised my arm it
would squeeze another drop out (of clotted blood) and it would go
down to my wrist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 2203 </TRAILER>
