<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cardinal John O'Connor Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cardinal John O'Connor, who charmed New Yorkers with his wit
and warmth while using his opposition to abortion and homosexuality to make
headlines and chastise politicians, died tonight. He was 80. O'Connor had been
ailing since he underwent brain surgery last summer. He frequently missed Mass
and made his last public appearance at St. Patrick's Cathedral on March 5, when
he did not lead the service but spoke briefly to parishioners. He traveled to
Italy for a final visit to the pope in February.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Unveils China Enforcement Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administariton today proposed a $22 million
program to make sure China lives up to its market-opening promises if Congress
approves a China trade bill. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers called it ''the
most intensive enforcement and compliance effort ever mounted for a single trade
agreement.'' The proposal would include a new position of deputy assistant
secretary for China at the Commerce Department to head up a ''rapid response
compliance team'' of at least 12 trade specialists working in Washington and
China.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Feds Nix Biotech Food Labels
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Food labels will not have to disclose any genetically
engineered ingredients, the Clinton administration decided today, instead
adopting a series of industry-backed steps intended to assure the public that
the products are safe. Critics of the industry say there isn't enough known
about possible allergic reactions to the food or the potential harm to the
environment and have been demanding both mandatory labeling of the products and
tougher testing standards for biotech plants and animals.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
12 Years Later, Lockerbie Trial Begins
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- Twelve years after a bomb blew Pan Am Flight
103 from the sky over Lockerbie, Scotland, two Libyans accused in the attack
that killed 270 people finally came to trial Wednesday -- and quickly sought to
shift blame to Palestinian militants. After years of diplomatic wrangling and
painstaking investigations, the trial of the alleged Libyan intelligence agents
began with victims' relatives here and across the Atlantic watching a video
showing the final seconds of the flight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
7 Peacekeepers Killed in Sierra Leone
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leone's rebel leader agreed Wednesday
to free any hostages held by his movement, after dozens of U.N. peacekeepers and
unarmed military observers were seized and at least seven peacekeepers killed in
clashes. Since Monday, Revolutionary United Front rebels have captured 50 U.N.
workers in three towns in Sierra Leone's interior, officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miss. Bans Homosexual Adoption
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Mississippi today became the third state to ban gay
couples from adopting children, although the plan is likely to be challenged in
court. Democratic Gov. Ronnie Musgrove signed the bill after it easily cleared
the Legislature in the final days of the recently concluded 2000 session.
Florida and Utah have similar laws. The American Civil Liberties Union has vowed
to file a lawsuit on behalf of an unidentified gay couple planning an adoption
in Mississippi.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lawmakers Join Vieques Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- With opposition growing in the United States --
including from Hillary Rodham Clinton -- federal agents faced the prospect today
of arresting bishops and a congressman who have joined protesters occupying a
Navy bombing range. Rep. Luis Gutierrez arrived today on the Puerto Rican island
of Vieques, where he planned to remain and face arrest with dozens of others
intent on making the Navy end its bombing exercises.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Celebrities Go On 'Millionaire'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Do Drew Carey and Rosie O'Donnell sweat like regular folks
when confronted with big-money questions on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''?
Maybe not, though Carey admitted he was nervous. What was more important to ABC
was the record-breaking number of people watching this week to see how
celebrities perform in the hot seat. Monday's first celebrity edition of
''Millionaire'' drew 35.8 million viewers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Stocks Dive: Dow Ends Off 250
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The stock market plunged today over new interest rate
worries. The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 10,480.13 points, down
250.99. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 2,154-844. The Nasdaq, cutting a late
loss of 192.66, was down 78.14 at 3,707.31. Japanese markets are closed Thursday
for a national holiday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ky. Derby Favorite Gets Post No. 16
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Fusaichi Pegasus, the curious colt who likes to look
around, will view the start of the Kentucky Derby from the No. 16 post. He also
is the early 9-5 favorite to get a good look at the winner's blanket of roses
after a full field of 20 3-year-olds contest the 1\-mile Derby at Churchill
Downs on Saturday. The last favorite to win the Derby was Spectacular Bid in
1979.
</P>
