<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Millionaire' Fuels Disney Earnings  </HEADLINE>
By GARY GENTILE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Increased revenue from the ABC Television
Network helped boost earnings by 31 percent at the Walt Disney Co.	   Profits
generated by television and cable programming as well as
its theme parks fueled the company's profitable quarter, making up
for disappointing results from its film studio and consumer
products divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Disney reported net income for the second quarter ended March 31
of $369 million or 18 cents per share, compared with $281 million,
or 13 cents per share, for the same quarter last year. The results
handily beat the 14 cents per share expected by stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison was reported on a pro forma basis, as if the
company had created its Go.com subsidiary and sold Fairchild
Publications at the beginning of fiscal year 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Disney officials happily reported that hit game show ''Who Wants
to be a Millionaire'' marked an all-time ratings high Monday night
despite the fact that ABC was blocked out of Time Warner Cable
outlets in New York, Los Angeles and several other cities. The
network was taken off the cable system for more than a day after
talks broke down in a dispute over how much Disney should be paid
for its programming.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Iger, Disney's president, said the popular game show
hosted by Regis Philbin won its ratings victory, ''with one hand
tied around its back.''
</P>
<P>
   A huge surge in advertising on the network, due largely to the
game show, increased revenue at Disney's media networks division by
30 percent in the quarter, to $2.4 billion. Improved ratings for
its ''Good Morning America'' daytime show also contributed to the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The results were partially offset by rising costs at ESPN,
stemming from deals the network made to broadcast National Hockey
League and Major League Baseball games in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Disney also made more money at its theme parks without opening a
single new attraction. Officials said attendance and spending was
up at the parks due to its yearlong Millennium Celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues from film and video operations increased by 4 percent
during the quarter, but operating income fell 97 percent because of
declines in home video sales and lackluster performance by Disney
films at the box office. Profits from its hit ''Toy Story 2'' were
more than offset by losses from such films as ''Mission to Mars''
and ''Bicentennial Man,'' Disney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 2209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000503.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 19 Dead in Algeria Highway Attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Islamic insurgents opened fire on a bus
Wednesday, killing at least 19 people after the driver refused to
stop at a rebel roadblock near Algiers, according to area
residents.
</P>
<P>
   About 26 others were injured in the 5 a.m. attack on the road
between Blida and Medea, about 50 miles south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre was the worst in recent months in Algeria, which
has been in the grip of an Islamic insurgency for the past eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   The residents told reporters that some 20 militants opened fire
on the bus when the refused an order to stop at a roadblock the
rebels had set up. The residents said the attackers set fire to the
bus before fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   The Blida-Medea road is surrounded by mountains that provide
cover for armed groups, which use such roadblocks to rob travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Insurgency violence in Algeria has continued despite the effort
at national reconciliation by President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, who
offered partial amnesty to insurgents turning themselves in by Jan.
13.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 people have been killed since the insurgency
erupted after the army canceled legislative elections that a
now-banned Muslim fundamentalist party, the Islamic Salvation
Front, was poised to win.
</P>
<P>
   The bloody attack came as a delegation from Amnesty
International began a 12-day visit to Algeria, the first since the
London-based human rights organization was expelled from the
country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty is one of four human rights and press advocacy groups
invited here in May and June by Bouteflika who is campaigning to
refurbish the image of his country.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation head, Roger Clark, said on arrival Tuesday that
the group's ''priority of priorities'' would be inquiring about
past massacres and the thousands of people who have disappeared
since the start of the violence. Questions had been raised in the
past about village massacres that occurred near police and army
posts.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of the violence, Algeria has systematically
shielded what is referred to here as the ''national tragedy'' from
the probings of outside observers, expelling groups and refusing or
limiting visas to foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Daily violence continues despite Bouteflika's effort at national
reconciliation through an offer of partial amnesty for insurgents
who have not killed, bombed or raped. He said some 6,000 insurgents
had turned themselves in at the expiration date on Jan. 13. It is
not known how many insurgents remain active.
</P>
<P>
   The radical Armed Islamic Group, blamed for most massacres, and
a smaller group that targets soldiers and police refused the
amnesty outright.
</P>
<P>
   The violence erupted after the army canceled legislative
elections that a now-banned Muslim fundamentalist party, the
Islamic Salvation Front, was poised to win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 2214 </TRAILER>
