<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Woman To Stay in Peruvian Jail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Presidential candidate Alejandro Toledo
promised Wednesday that an American woman serving a life sentence
in a Peruvian prison for terrorism will not go free if he is
elected in the May 28 runoff vote.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Lori Berenson turned into a campaign issue last week
when Toledo said in New York that he planned to create an
independent judiciary and that a new trial for the 30-year-old New
York native could be possible if evidence is found that she was
denied due process.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Peru, television networks and newspapers aligned with
incumbent President Alberto Fujimori seized on the comment,
reporting that jailed leftist rebels could be set free if Toledo's
Peru Possible party comes to power.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Berenson's fate during a campaign stop in Arequipa,
465 miles southeast of Lima, Toledo responded by saying that if
he's elected ''no terrorist, independent of his nationality, will
get out of prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Berenson was convicted of treason by a hooded military judge on
Jan. 11, 1996, for helping to lead a thwarted assault on Peru's
Congress by leftist Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement rebels. She
has maintained her innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has been widely credited with stemming leftist rebel
violence since he was first elected in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Toledo accused Fujimori's government of setting
a runoff election to coincide with Venezuela's May 28 presidential
vote to divert the international spotlight away from irregularities
and charges of electoral fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old economist on Wednesday called for a two-week
postponement of the second round showdown, also scheduled for Mary
28, to allow sufficient time to implement the recommendations of
international observers to ensure a clean vote.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has threatened to pull out of the race unless ''effective
measures'' are taken to guard against any irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate received the majority required for victory in
the April 9 first-round election.
</P>
<P>
   Romulo Munoz Arce, one of five members of the election board,
ruled out postponing the runoff vote, saying the constitution
required the ballot be held within 30 days after final returns were
officially registered.
</P>
<P>
   Slow ballot counting and rampant computer glitches sparked
suspicions that Fujimori was in the process of rigging an
unprecedented third term victory, a charge he has denied.
</P>
<P>
   The government has promised to improve its vote counting system
and Fujimori's campaign this week started direct negotiations with
Toledo's camp on terms for a debate between the candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 2214 </TRAILER>
