<HEADLINE> Colombia Comic's Death Said Ordered  </HEADLINE>
By JARED KOTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Prosecutors said Wednesday they believe
the head of Colombia's notorious right-wing paramilitary ordered
last year's slaying of the country's most beloved humorist.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Castano is the ''presumed'' mastermind of the August 13,
1999 assassination of television and radio satirist Jaime Garzon,
the federal prosecutor's office said in a statement also linking
the militia boss to two massacres.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement could lead to new arrest warrants and
indictments of the fugitive Castano, who is already wanted in
connection with numerous mass killings of villagers and
assassinations of leftists.
</P>
<P>
   Garzon was found slumped in his Jeep Cherokee after motorcycle
gunmen sprayed it with bullets while the 39-year-old comic headed
to his morning program at a Bogota radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The crime shocked and saddened Colombians, and speculation about
who might have order Garzon's killing immediately turned to
Castano.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands attended teary memorials to protest the slaying of man
whose irreverent lampooning of politicians and celebrities provided
comic relief for the Andean nation subsumed by daily news of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   One man is under arrest in the case, a 22-year-old detained in
January on suspicion he was one of the two shooters. Federal
investigators believe the alleged hit man, Juan Pablo Ortiz,
belonged to a gang of Medellin assassins who work on contract for
Castano.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also announced Wednesday that Castano was suspected
of ordering massacres in the eastern towns of Tibu and La Gabarra
last year in which 51 unarmed villagers were killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
