<HEADLINE> Angels 6, Orioles 5  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Mo Vaughn and Garret Anderson homered in a
three-run sixth inning that powered the Anaheim Angels past
Baltimore 6-5 on Wednesday night in a game that featured six home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck and Benji Gil also connected for the Angels, who
had lost nine straight and 14 of 15 to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle and B.J. Surhoff hit solo homers for the Orioles.
Belle went 3-for-4 and scored three runs.
</P>
<P>
   With the score 3-3, Vaughn led off the sixth inning by driving a
3-0 pitch from Jason Johnson (0-1) over the right-field scoreboard.
Tim Salmon then singled and Anderson homered on the first pitch
from Chuck McElroy.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Conine hit a two-run single in the Orioles' half. But with
the bases loaded and one out, Mike Bordick popped out before Mike
Holtz retired Brady Anderson on a grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim starter Ramon Ortiz (2-2) allowed four runs in five-plus
innings. Troy Percival, the fifth Angels pitcher, got three outs
for his seventh save. He got Surhoff to fly out with a runner on
second to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   One night earlier, Percival blew his first save of the season by
allowing two ninth-inning runs in the Orioles' 7-6 victory. He
entered the game with a lifetime 6.08 ERA against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Belle led off the second inning with his first homer since April
7, a towering fly to left that barely cleared the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck's solo homer in the third tied the score and doubled
both his home run and RBI output this season. Gil, the No. 9
hitter, followed with his first homer since August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore went up 3-2 in the fourth. Surhoff sent an 0-2 pitch
over the right-field wall before Belle singled and scored on a
sacrifice fly by Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels pulled even in the fifth when Troy Glaus drew a
leadoff walk, took third on a double by Orlando Palmeiro and scored
on a two-out wild pitch by Johnson.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Anaheim's Darin Erstad, held hitless Tuesday, went 2-for-4
with a walk. He has reached safely in each of his 27 games. ...
Belle's homer was his 361st, tying him with Joe DiMaggio at No. 49
on the career list. ... The Angels have hit consecutive homers four
times this season. ... Baltimore fell to 10-3 at home. ... Before
the game, the Orioles put 1B Will Clark (strained hamstring) on the
disabled list and recalled INF Ryan Minor from Triple-A Rochester.
</P>
</TEXT>
