<DOCNO> APW20000503.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Derides Publisher Suspension  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The San Francisco Examiner publisher who
was abruptly suspended after admitting at trial that he offered
favorable editorial coverage to the mayor was only repeating what
he told the Justice Department several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. reacted with shock and suspended Timothy White,
publisher of the company's flagship newspaper, after he said he
offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable editorials if Brown supported
the company's effort to buy the San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst said the conversation White described with Brown may not
have taken place, and was a ''serious breach of Hearst's policy''
if it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   But a deposition White gave in December to government antitrust
lawyers was virtually identical to his explosive testimony in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apparently they have fired this man not because of the
information itself, but because it was revealed in a public
forum,'' attorney Joseph M. Alioto said in court Wednesday as he
read from White's earlier deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto is representing businessman Clint Reilly, the former
mayoral candidate suing to block Hearst's purchase of the San
Francisco Chronicle and sale of the Examiner. Trial of the civil
case began Monday.
</P>
<P>
   White, in a statement issued by Hearst after Monday's testimony,
said he had been ''tired and confused by the question.'' He was
placed on indefinite leave Tuesday, and was replaced as publisher
by George Irish, head of Hearst's newspaper division. Hearst said
it was launching an internal investigation into White's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   According to a transcript of White's Dec. 16 deposition, Justice
Department lawyers questioned him about his meeting with Mayor
Brown on Aug. 30. At the time, Brown was publicly opposing Hearst's
plans to buy the Chronicle and sell or merge the Examiner into the
larger paper.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department lawyer asked if White was intending to
convey to Brown that his support for Hearst's purchase of the
Chronicle ''would result in more favorable treatment'' by the
Examiner. White answered yes.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the same answer to the same question in court Monday,
and later specified that he was talking about editorials, not news
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Both Brown and Examiner executive editor Phil Bronstein, who
also attended the lunch meeting with the mayor, said outside of
court that no such discussion took place.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Corp. director of corporate communications Debra Shriver
said White was suspended entirely because of what he revealed in
his testimony on Monday. Regardless of whether any lawyers for the
company were present, ''senior executives at the company were not
aware of the content of the testimony'' until White testified in
open court, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The deposition transcript shows that two Hearst lawyers were
present at White's deposition -- Gary Halling, the company's chief
attorney at the trial, and Jonathan Thackeray, Hearst's vice
president and general counsel. Shriver said Thackeray told her he
left the session before it ended and did not hear the testimony in
question. She did not know whether Halling remained throughout the
deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounds like it's not the fact of these actions but the
exposure of these actions which motivated his removal,'' said Tom
Rosenstiel, director of the Project for Excellence in Journalism,
affiliated with Columbia University's Graduate School of
Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said Hearst must have known what White told the Justice
Department, and cited White's deposition in asking for a court
order prohibiting Hearst from punishing witnesses for their
testimony. He was turned down by U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker,
who is overseeing the non-jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   In a note to its readers Wednesday, the Examiner said: ''The
newsroom employees of The Examiner are proud that our editorial
support is not, and never has been, for sale. We fully expect any
employee to be held accountable for actions that undermine our
editorial integrity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 2242 </TRAILER>
