<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Complains About Guatemala Head  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Human rights leaders on Wednesday filed a
criminal complaint against former President Fernando Romeo Lucas
Garcia in connection with 10 alleged massacres carried out during
the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, the first presented against a former Guatemalan
head-of-state, also accuses the ex-president's brother, Benedicto
Lucas Garcia, a former army commander, and former defense minister
Luis Rene Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   With some chanting ''Justice! Justice!'' leaders from the Human
Rights Legal Action Center presented their complaint to Guatemala
City's Municipal Prosecutor's office Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Garcia ruled Guatemala with an iron fist from July 1978
until March 1982, when he was ousted in a coup by Efrain Rios
Montt, a retired general who is now president of the country's
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint centers on 10 massacres that occurred between Dec.
4, 1978 and Feb. 15, 1982 in indigenous villages in the western
Guatemalan highland states of Rabinal, Baja Verapaz and Quiche. It
is based on the testimonies of 48 survivors of those massacres in
which more than 150 peasants were killed, said Edgar Perez one of
the lawyers representing the center.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Garcia, who lives in Venezuela and is reportedly suffering
from Alzheimer's disease, offered no public comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Peace accords brought an end to the 36-year civil war in 1996.
The country's truth commission, which investigated abuses committed
during the war, issued a report last year blaming government
security forces for most of the 200,000 killings during the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 2244 </TRAILER>
