<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressRobert F. Craig:
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Robert F. Craig, an activist who pushed AIDS
education, fought for West Hollywood's cityhood and founded the gay
newsmagazine Frontiers, died Friday from complications of AIDS. He
was 65.
</P>
<P>
   Craig co-founded Frontiers in 1982 and eventually became the
sole owner, turning the 16-page tabloid into a magazine with a
current circulation of 86,000.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Frontiers publicized the new threat of AIDS, to the
discomfort of gay bars and bathhouses, who vowed a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, he co-founded a group for gay and lesbian business
owners that is now called the Los Angeles Business Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 he was elected chairman of the West Hollywood
Incorporation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Craig is survived by a sister, a half-sister, Catherine, and a
nephew, great-nephew and great-niece.
Alonzo Crim:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Alonzo Crim, the first black school
superintendent of a major Southern city, died Wednesday following a
car accident. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Crim was named superintendent of Atlanta Schools in 1973. Over
the next 14 years, he was credited with raising school attendance
to more than 92 percent and increasing the graduation rate to more
than 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped down from his post in 1987.
Arthur Dake:
</P>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Arthur Dake, the Portland chess expert who
became the first American to beat a sitting world champion, died
April 28. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, Dake defeated world champion Alexander Alekhine of
France just five years after learning the game from Russian
immigrants at Portland's YMCA. He also played on gold-medal winning
American Olympiad teams in 1931, 1933 and 1935.
Jonah Jones:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jonah Jones, a Grammy award-winning jazz
trumpeter who began his career on a Mississippi riverboat and
became a star playing with Cab Calloway, died Sunday. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Jones performed around the Midwest with artists and bands
including Jimmie Lunceford, Stuff Smith, McKinney's Cotton Pickers
and Lil Armstrong, the wife of Louis Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   His energetic solos with Smith's Onyx club band in the late
1930s earned him widespread attention, and he soon earned a spot
playing with Calloway from 1941 to 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Jones played Dixieland with Earl Hines and in 1954, made a
European tour.
</P>
<P>
   He sold a million copies of his versions of ''On the Street
Where You Live'' and ''Baubles, Bangles and Beads.'' Jones won a
Grammy award in 1959 for the album ''I Dig Chicks.''
Harry Newman:
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Former All-American quarterback Harry Newman, who
threw the first touchdown pass in an NFL championship game and
played with former President Ford at Michigan, died Tuesday. He was
90.
</P>
<P>
   Newman played for the New York Giants from 1933 to 1935. His
29-yard touchdown pass to Red Badgro gave the Giants a 7-6 halftime
lead in the first NFL title game in 1933, but they lost to the
Chicago Bears 23-21.
</P>
<P>
   With Newman's help, the Giants won the NFL title the following
year, beating the Bears 30-13 for the championship in the famous
''Sneakers Game.'' The Giants fell behind 10-3 at halftime, then
switched to basketball shoes for better traction on an ice-covered
field at the Polo Grounds.
Cardinal John O'Connor:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cardinal John O'Connor, who charmed New Yorkers
with his wit and warmth while using his opposition to abortion and
homosexuality to make headlines and chastise politicians, died
Wednesday. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was the oldest active bishop in the United States and
one of the country's most influential Catholics. His health began
to fail after he had a brain tumor removed in August.
</P>
<P>
   Although he mustered the strength to make a farewell visit to
the pope in February, he made his final appearance at St. Patrick's
Cathedral in early March.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal was a familiar figure to devout Catholics as well
as average New Yorkers. He blessed parades as they passed St.
Patrick's Cathedral on Fifth Avenue; provoked a firestorm by
recommending excommunication for Catholic politicians who support
abortion rights, and he used his pulpit to weigh in on
controversies large and small.
</P>
<P>
   ''For more than 50 years, he has reached out with uncommon
fortitude to minister to the needs of America's Catholics,'' said
President Clinton. ''The courage and firm faith he showed in his
final illness inspired us all.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor condemned a controversial painting of the Virgin Mary
at the Brooklyn Museum; held a conciliatory interfaith service
after police shot an unarmed African immigrant, Amadou Diallo; and
made front-page news by saying in 1990 that listening to certain
rock songs was ''a help to the devil'' that could ''lead to demonic
possession.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when American Catholics were increasingly inclined to
go their own way on matters of faith and morals, O'Connor staunchly
championed the Vatican line on birth control, abortion and
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal also led opposition to local gay rights legislation
and kicked a gay Catholic group out of a parish church where it had
met for years. In 1989, enraged activists responded by chaining
themselves to pews and throwing condoms in the air during Mass at
St. Patrick's.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, O'Connor made unannounced visits to Catholic
hospitals where he ministered to AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said he would have been satisfied to be a parish priest
or teacher, and feared he might instead be remembered for ''the
alleged -- and to me, the mythical -- power, about my purported
political manipulations and all that kind of nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What I would like my epitaph to say is simply that 'He was a
good priest.'''
Steve Reeves:
</P>
<P>
   ESCONDIDO, Calif. (AP) -- Steve Reeves, star of European-made
action films of the 1950s and '60s whose Mr. Universe physique won
him a signature role as the mythical strongman Hercules, died
Monday of complications from lymphoma. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong bodybuilder, Reeves won the Mr. America title in
1947, which he followed with Mr. World and Mr. Universe titles in
1948 and Mr. Universe again in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   His imposing 6-foot-1, 215-pound frame attracted the attention
of filmmakers, who cast him in 18 films before he retired from
acting in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, Reeves became one of the world's biggest box office
draws based on the success of ''Hercules,'' his third movie.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hercules'' was filmed in Italy with an all-European cast. It
was followed by films such as ''Goliath and the Barbarians,''
''Hercules Unchained,'' ''Last Days of Pompeii'' and ''Thief of
Baghdad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
