<HEADLINE> Chavez's Ruling Coalition Strong  </HEADLINE>
By FABIOLA SANCHEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez's coalition
showed signs of cracking Wednesday, a day after a showed him with a
strong lead over his closest rival in this month's presidential
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Fatherland for All, one of three parties making up
Chavez's leftist coalition, met to consider withdrawing their
support from Chavez in the May 28 vote. After the meeting, the
leaders said they would maintain their support for Chavez's
re-election bid as a group, but gave individual party leaders,
including two state governors, the option of breaking away from
Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the organization's members have accused the president of
verbally attacking their candidates in local elections.
</P>
<P>
   Fatherland for All ''has no intention of voting for Chavez,''
said Alexis Rosas, one of the group's leaders and the governor of
the eastern state of Anzoategui. ''It is useless for us to remain
in this alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez was elected in December 1998 and is up for re-election in
May 28 after a new constitution he pushed through last year called
for new balloting to ''re-legitimize'' most public offices
including the presidency, governorships and congress.
</P>
<P>
   While a poll released Tuesday showed Chavez with a 21-point lead
over his closest rival, Francisco Arias, the political struggle
could hurt the president's pledge to help his political movement
sweep the elections for governorships and the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Arias, a former military leader who helped Chavez stage a failed
1992 coup attempt, has accused Chavez of amassing power and
abandoning the ideals behind their rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   The feud is just the latest in a series of pre-election
political clashes involving Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   A delegation from the Atlanta, Georgia-based Carter Center
arrived in the Venezuelan capital last weekend to meet with
political representatives in an attempt to ensure fair balloting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
