<HEADLINE> White Sox 7, Blue Jays 3  </HEADLINE>
By RICK GANO, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Jose Valentin, Frank Thomas and Paul Konerko hit
consecutive homers in the sixth inning Wednesday night and the
Chicago White Sox ended a three-game losing streak, beating the
Toronto Blue Jays 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Johnson also homered in sixth, with his two-run shot
breaking a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin homered in the first, and the long ball display made it
easy for James Baldwin (5-0).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's homer and Valentin's second solo shot finished Kelvim
Escobar (2-4). Thomas and Konerko then connected off reliever John
Frascatore.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin, who didn't win his fifth game last season until Aug. 1,
allowed four hits and three runs in 7 1-3 innings, including solo
homers to Marty Cordova and Darrin Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin left after Homer Bush hit an RBI single in the eighth to
break an 0-for-20 skid.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Foulke pitched 1 2-3 innings for his fourth save.
Notes: Baldwin's 5-0 start is the best by a White Sox pitcher
since Wilson Alvarez went 8-0 in 1994. ... The White Sox sixth
marked the first time the Blue Jays had ever allowed four homers in
one inning. ... The last time the White Sox went
back-to-back-to-back was May 26, 1996, when Thomas, Harold Baines
and Robin Ventura connected in order against Milwaukee. ... The
five homers give the White Sox 43 in 28 games ... Toronto's two
homers gave the Blue Jays seven in the three-game series and an
AL-leading 50 in 29 games this season. ... Escobar, now 0-4
lifetime against the White Sox, walked six.
</P>
