<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cops: Woman Snatches Baby, It Dies  </HEADLINE>
By MARTHA IRVINE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAYWOOD, Ill. (AP) -- A woman who had told neighbors she was
pregnant snatched a premature baby from a hospital, apparently
concealing the child under a coat as the alarms went off, police
say. The baby was later found dead in a clothes hamper in her
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they identified 24-year-old Vanecha Cooper
from surveillance video at Loyola University Medical Center in
suburban Maywood, where she had been visiting another baby on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When investigators arrived at her apartment about 2 a.m.
Tuesday, prosecutors said, Cooper hid the baby in a clothes hamper.
</P>
<P>
   ''By the time police were able to get permission to search the
apartment, the baby had died,'' Bob Benjamin, a spokesman for the
Cook County State's Attorney's office, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The county coroner said 2-week-old Zquan Wakefield, whose body
was found about 7 a.m., suffocated.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper told investigators the baby was alive when she put him in
the hamper and covered him with clothes, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   She was charged with murder and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Michael Sheahan said Cooper told investigators that she
had had two miscarriages. ''Her motive possibly could be that she
wanted a baby,'' the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   Loyola officials said they first noticed Zquan was missing from
the nursery when an alarm sounded at the hospital about 10:30 p.m.
Monday, triggered by the baby's ID bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials said in a statement that Cooper, who had
visited the nursery frequently, had been on a list of approved
visitors provided by her brother, whose girlfriend had recently had
a baby there.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital spokeswoman Patricia Cassidy said a wristband alarm on
the baby was supposed to trigger the locking of a set of doors that
would have prevented the abduction, but a wiring malfunction
prevented that from working. Cassidy said that has been fixed and
new security measures have been installed.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, a woman large enough to pretend she was pregnant, had
told neighbors she was going to have a baby and due to have labor
induced Monday. Tests showed that she was not pregnant and had not
given birth.
</P>
<P>
   At a preliminary hearing Wednesday, Cooper's lawyer, Larry
Sommers, received permission to have her undergo a mental
evaluation. Bail was set at $2.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 2250 </TRAILER>
