<HEADLINE> Log Truck Crash Kills 4 in Maine  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORNVILLE, Maine (AP) -- A logging truck plowed into a station
wagon at the intersection of two highways Wednesday, killing three
young children and a 24-year-old passenger and leaving a 4-year-old
in serious condition, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of the three children, Stacy Corson, was pulling into
the intersection when the logging truck hit the station wagon's
passenger side, said Stephen McCausland of the Maine Public Safety
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The crash happened about 1 p.m. in a wooded area near Cornville,
about 100 miles north of Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Killed were Nathan Raymond, 25, of Solon and Corson's children
Vincent, 7, Wyonna, 4, and Trevor, 1. Raymond's son Jacob, 4, was
hospitalized in serious condition Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Corson, 25, of West Athens and 18-year-old Michelle Bouley of
Vassalboro were hospitalized in fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, who was uninjured, apparently tried to avoid
the station wagon but couldn't, McCausland said. He said the truck
struck the vehicle and rolled into a ditch, spilling some of its
logs.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were reconstructing the accident Wednesday
afternoon and had not determined whether Corson stopped at the
intersection's stop sign, McCausland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
