<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Courts Californians for Votes  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE DeARMOND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Brushing aside claims that he has
written off California, Texas Gov. George W. Bush pledged Wednesday
to campaign ''all up and down'' the state, saying his efforts here
will propel him to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last time I was here in your great state, I think my opponent
might have been talking some wishful thinking out loud,'' Bush
said. ''The word was that somehow the George W. campaign wasn't
going to campaign in California. That's wishful thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate kicked off his three-day
swing through Southern California with a brief rally under the
98-degree desert sun at the Palm Springs International Airport.
About 200 supporters crowded around him under a tent next to the
runway.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush visited the area, known as the Coachella
Valley, in March to raise money for his son's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   California has 54 of the nation's 270 electoral votes, giving it
the largest political pull in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore leads in California presidential polls,
but Bush has tried to bridge that gap by reaching out to the
state's Hispanics and distancing himself from former Republican
Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor alienated many of those voters with his
support for a measure to outlaw most state aid to illegal
immigrants and his opposition to affirmative action and bilingual
education.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Parsky, chairman of the California Republican Party,
pointed to the GOP candidate's trip this week as proof that he has
not ceded the state to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Parsky introduced Bush at the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the candidate's motorcade left Palm Springs for ritzy
Rancho Mirage, where Bush was to attend a fund-raiser at the estate
of billionaire philanthropist Walter Annenberg.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 50 couples were invited to the event, which Parsky
said would raise money for both the Republican National Committee
and the California Republican Party. The fund-raiser reportedly
cost $25,000 per couple, although some sources said it was $25,000
per plate.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's more evidence,'' Parsky said. ''Money is raised and
staying in the state. ... This is the kind of enthusiasm we haven't
felt in the Republican Party in the last 16 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has collected a record $80 million for his campaign and,
just last month, raised a record $18 million at a single event for
the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He planned to continue his trip to California with a visit to
San Juan Capistrano on Thursday, where he was expected to speak
about school choice.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech to the predominantly white, non-Hispanic crowd in
this GOP stronghold included a series of promises to help Americans
pay less taxes, which was greeted with cheers from flag- and
pompom-waving supporters.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to return some of the national surplus to taxpayers,
eliminate the so-called death tax and lamented the amount of taxes
the poor pay.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said he plans to use a projected surplus in Social
Security taxes to improve Social Security and pay down the federal
debt. Gore chastised Bush on Wednesday for not yet revealing
details of his plan to repair Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he planned to outline the principles of his plan next
week, but wouldn't reveal specifics. He did not mention his plans
at the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked glowingly about his wife, Laura, during the rally
and told supporters he was sorry they didn't get to meet her. He
made no mention of a decades-old accident report that was released
Wednesday, revealing that a 17-year-old Laura Bush ran a stop sign
in 1963 and collided with another car, killing her boyfriend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
