<DOCNO> APW20000503.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: More Vigilance in Dept.  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
''furious'' about recent security lapses at the State Department,
delivered an impassioned plea to department employees Wednesday for
greater vigilance to protect the nation's secrets.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 minutes, Albright admonished a
standing-room-only crowd of about 1,000 employees that the
country's vital secrets can be put at risk unless security measures
are strictly observed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't care how skilled you are as a diplomat, how brilliant
you may be at meetings, or how creative you are as an administrator
-- if you are not a professional about security, you are a
failure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every senior department official attended the session
held in the agency's largest auditorium. The proceedings also were
made available through closed circuit video to offices throughout
the building and to many foreign posts.
</P>
<P>
   The ''town hall'' meeting was convened following February's
unexplained disappearance of a department laptop computer
containing highly sensitive information, and an incident last year
in which a seventh floor conference room was found to have been
bugged. A Russian diplomat was expelled from the country as part of
the fallout of that incident.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Albright announced several steps aimed at improving
security.
</P>
<P>
   Among others, she asked all principal supervisory personnel to
stress the importance of security to their staffs. In addition,
annual refresher security briefings will be intensified, with
mandatory attendance for all appropriate department employees.
</P>
<P>
   An interagency panel, consisting of experts from the Secret
Service, FBI, CIA and the State and Defense Departments, has given
Albright a report recommending about 40 changes to improve
security, ABC News reported on its Web site Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations include consolidating the departments varied
security apparatus into its Bureau of Diplomatic Security; spending
more on security personnel, training and equipment; putting tighter
controls on State Department building passes; and further
restricting access to the main building in Washington to protect
against a terrorist threat, the report said. The department also
was advised to stop using private security guards and replace them
with federal law enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Following the disclosure of the missing laptop last month, House
International Relations Committee Chairman Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y.,
announced plans for hearings on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ''casual attitude of the State Department toward
security must change.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, while not endorsing Gilman's premise, said, ''We
cannot and should not accept a culture within the department that
resists paying full attention to our security responsibilities. We
cannot and should not suggest that those responsibilities somehow
interfere with the performance of our jobs. For, in truth, this is
not possible. Security is an inherent, inextricable and
indispensable component of all our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the missing laptop contained large quantities of
documents about arms proliferation issues and highly sensitive
information about sources and methods of U.S. intelligence
collection.
</P>
<P>
   After Albright spoke, a senior official who briefed reporters
said it is still not clear whether the laptop was stolen or simply
misplaced. He also acknowledged that extensive publicity about the
laptop may be inhibiting an employee from returning it for fear of
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The official, asking not to be identified, said many people are
being interviewed as potential witnesses to what may have happened,
including cleaning people and contractors in addition to department
officials and other employees.
</P>
<P>
   The official said it was unfortunate that The Washington Post,
which had the first account on the laptop's disappearance, reported
on the highly classified nature of the information stored in it. If
the computer was stolen, he said, word that it contained top secret
data would increase its value, thereby making it much more
difficult to track down.
</P>
<P>
   The official added that there is a strong likelihood that the
person responsible for taking the computer would be able to access
the documents even if that individual does not know the password
normally needed to download them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-03-00 2314 </TRAILER>
