<HEADLINE> Twins 5, Mariners 4, 10 Innings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Cristian Guzman hit a sacrifice fly in the
10th inning and the Minnesota Twins stopped a five-game losing
streak, defeating the Seattle Mariners 5-4 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jacque Jones went 3-for-3 with a walk and Corey Koskie homered
for Minnesota, which almost blew a three-run lead for the second
straight night.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the 10th, Jones, pinch-hitter Midre Cummings and
Denny Hocking hit consecutive singles off Jose Mesa (1-2) to load
the bases. Guzman then hit a fly ball to left field and there was
no play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Guardado (2-1) pitched a perfect 10th inning for the win.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 4-1, the Mariners scored a run in the sixth and two
more in the seventh to tie it at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Ibanez had an RBI single in the sixth to make it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Mark McLemore and Stan Javier hit one-out
singles. With two outs, John Olerud singled home a run off Brad
Radke and Edgar Martinez, who had three hits, had an RBI single off
reliever Bob Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Javier hit an RBI triple off Radke in the third to give Seattle
a 1-0 lead. Todd Walker had an RBI groundout in the bottom of the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Koskie made it 3-1 with his first homer of the season, a two-run
shot off Brett Tomko in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Walker hit a sacrifice fly in the fifth to make it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota had a three-run lead after five innings Tuesday night
against Seattle, but lost 5-4.
Notes: The Mariners have not lost a season series to Minnesota in
seven years under manager Lou Piniella. ... Jones hit a foul pop in
the third inning that hit one of the speakers attached to the
Metrodome ceiling. Seattle third baseman David Bell was ready to
make the catch, but the ball bounced off the speaker away from him.
... Koskie hit 11 homers last season, his rookie year. ... Right
fielder Matt Lawton made a leaping catch in the seventh on Alex
Rodriguez's foul out.
</P>
